76561198002552924,Recommended,266510,32033484,Posted: 28 May,all,Zondi,"The priest that had begged me seventy times seven for food so the children could survive the winter was on the road ahead of me. I had all the necessary legendary gear required to defeat the king at the end of my quest or some mighty foe that would require a herculian feat; a mace that sharted lightnig, a shield of a defeated skeleton royal that could break skeleton warrios with a touch.The one thing I did not have was food to share, much less for myself. My choice was simple, refuse the priest's request to feed the children and see him badger me for eternity, or sell all my earthly possessions and forgo my own life to support this guys tireless request to feed the children foundation.The thought of seeing this priest one more time made the choice easy. I sold everything I had for all the food I could carry. I approach the priest and before he can open his stupid mouth, I hit him with my bag of food. We share words and he gives me some ring. Thanks...Now I'm starving and I just count down my days until starvation takes me, questioning why I even continue, prolonging the inevitable. Maybe, just maybe the old gods will deliver a miracle and repay me in riches and weapons for my charity.I stumble into a labrynth. This one seemed familiar... oh wait, there's a titanic minotaur in front of me. Well this is appropiate... I find the minotaur I was hunting all along with nothing to defend myself. ""Better than starving I supose"" I think to myself and shrug.I charge it head on to embrace death and glory. He swings his mighty Flail across its torso in almost blinding speed and strength. Either out of habit or not wanting to die (naturally), I roll underneath the attack and ready one swipe at its hoof with a craptastic rusty axe I found, but just then I am blinded by a flash of light. Lightning fell from the sky, striking the minatour and killing it instantly. Standing there with my jaw on the floor in shock I almost couldn't believe it. I can't help but start laughing with joy. The old gods actually came through and I learned a valuable lesson that day.Sacrifice everything to charity to get the incessant priest out of your deck so you never have to give up your food again.10/10 :)"
76561197960666064,Recommended,266510,14520174,"Posted: 17 February, 2015",all,GrinR,"Imagine a board game where the board ""spaces"" are cards laid out side-by-side.  You move your token from card to card, travelling across them until you reach the end of them.  As you ""step"" on each card, it is revealed.  Whatever the card reveals informs the adventure - an ambush by thieves, a mysterious cave, a helpful vendor, it's all randomized and set out under the cards for you to discover.Now imagine the cards are composed of a deck of cards that YOU build, as well as some cards the ""gamemaster"" stuffs in there.  You don't know what you'll get in your travels, or in what order, and that is the core gameplay.All combat is resolved in a simple, but elegant, action combat system similar to the Batman Arkham games (WASD, E to ""counter"", Space to roll, and sometimes # keys for specials) and it's fun.  Are you wearing a magic cap that makes your hits explode with gold?  Sounds good, until you remember that you revealed the ""gold curse"" card and the more gold you're carrying the slower you move.  Or not!  It's up to you.So far only 4 hours in, absolutely loving it.  Why has it taken so long for this kind of action CCG to come out?"
,Recommended,266510,32306687,Posted: 9 June,all,Araganor,"Hundreds of playing cards float in a rotating mass above the table. As you approach, a mysterious hooded figure greets you, and invites you to play a game. This is no ordinary game, however. You will be playing with Fate, the most fickle of mistresses.Hand of Fate presents itself as a seemingly simple rogue-like card game. Face down cards act as the playing board, and each turn you move your figure on the board to a new card. As you reach new cards, they are revealed and you must face whatever challenge Fate decides to hand you. It could be a simple peasant begging for food, a shop where you can restore your health and food supply in exchange for gold, or any number of hostile encounters. Often, you are presented with some choice, and based on your choices (and your fortune) there will be consequences.Combat is played out in real time, which is a nice addition. However, the combat itself leaves a lot to be desired, so if the rest of the game doesn't sound interesting to you, the combat will not make it any better. Most of the time you're either spamming dodge or spamming counter if you have a shield (although later on some of the attacks become unblockable). While not the most fluid combat system ever, it is serviceable enough and helps to keep the game more than just praying to RNGesus (praise be to He).However, what this game lacks in technical polish, it more than makes up for in style and originality. The mysterious host is always giving commentary, injecting a bit of sass into your escapades. This game is at its most exciting when you are discovering something new; even though you get to build your encounter and equipment decks before the game begins, you won't know what a new card does until you find it inside the game.I would recommend this game to anyone who loves good story-telling, atmosphere, and leaving your destiny to the whims of fate. Stay away if you dislike reading, clunky combat, or can't stand RNG.They say fortune favors the bold, so go ahead and try your luck."
,Recommended,266510,15206244,"Posted: 4 April, 2015",all,PlaneShifter,"If I had to describe this game with one world, I guess it would be ""wow"".""Wow""Few games lately have made me feel such wonder, had played many as videogames are my main passtime. But what makes this game so special? So unique? Well, it is a card game, and there are plenty of card games. It is an action game, and there are plenty of action games. And yet this game can suspend my disbelief like no other.This game just want to make you fell like you are... playing a game, and in this simplicity lies its brilliance. It does not try to suspend your disbelief to great heights and in doing that it brings an incredible immersion. All I need to feel is that I am playing a game with that strtange fellow in front of me. A fellow that, like no other character, I wish to pull of the screen just to have a chat over some beverages. Or maybe... a game of cards.It is impressive how a game that does not create anything new, but just mixes what we have already seen in a way we have never seen can fell so fresh, so different.As for the game itself, it plays as a roguelite. The randomness, the decisions based on your circinstances, the reset after a failure. Failure that does not bring the game back to the beggining, as the bosses you already defeated will remain defeated, but the entire board of the one you are chasing gets reset. Failure that can still reveal some minor rewards as you unlock tokens. Or even just comments from the dealer.And I press forward. Not for a quest to save the world, but for the wonder of discovery after each new card. Or even some old ones. Or just to spend some more time with this intriguing character that feels almost real."
,Recommended,266510,14569867,"Posted: 20 February, 2015",all,👻 Morsebid 👻,"Hand of Fate is an amazingly fun card game based adventure with a hack and slash style combat system. Its wildly addictive and honestly some of the most fun I've had in a game for a while, and I intend to play much more.This game makes me feel like I'm sitting down for a single player DnD game with the dealer as sort of a ""dungeon master"", laying out the adventure for me to go through. There are a lot of stories to be told that keep fairly short but interesting, and will occasionally result in combat. The combat of the game isn't amazing or revolutionary, but I find it fun and enjoyable. I'm into hack and slash style gameplay and this game does it well enough while not overstaying its welcome.The combination of RPG, card game, adventure with some roguelike elements mixed in, come together in Hand of Fate to make an outstanding experience that makes you just say ""One more round""Pros:-Unique genre-Strong and interesting atmosphere-Fun stories and adventures-Competent combat system-Several different weapons, armor and accessories to unlock-Strong difficulty(Starting at about 4 hours in)-Nice ambient soundtrackCons:-Occasionally Janky animations-Flow of combat can be somewhat awkwardBuy At Full Price"
