,Recommended,266510,15020550,"Posted: 23 March, 2015",all,Harlack,Deck building & 3rd person brawling… two seemingly disparate styles that play off each other well. It helps if you’ve ever played a deck building game… or any of the Batman Arkham games as the combat style is precisely “Batman with an ax”. Combat is deliberately slow and methodical. Curating you deck is satisfying in that nerdiest of ways(Calculating the ice knife’s slow down effect verses the War Hammer’s added attack strength).  HoF relies a bit to much on the Skinner Box as unlocking tokens and cards is far more engaging than beating the bosses. Also you’ll want to equip the largest helmet you can find because your random viking avatar is the ugliest man… and you have to look at him the whole game. At the start of playing HoF I estimated I’d get about 20 hours out of it and at time of writing I’m at 22. Well worth the money simply for being able to listen to the dealer over and over.
,Not Recommended,266510,33928981,Posted: 31 July,all,Adam Jensen,"First off, I'll start by saying I really, really enjoy the premise. The whole tabletop feel, the deck building, even the dealer's dialogue, it's all solid and amazing. I'll also make it clear that I'm not the best of hack and slash players out there, so my experience might be quite different from those of you well-versed in such games.So should you get this game? The answer is yes if you like challenging games and are prepared to try, try and try again. And only if you can accept that sometimes, you fail because of sheer luck.Pros:+ Beautiful design. Every card is lovingly drawn and the dealer reacts accordingly to your choices.+ An element of luck. For every action, there is a selection of cards. Based on your luck, you either select a Success or a Failure for your choice of action. This makes clearing an encounter particularly exciting - but also vexing, if you're on a failure roll.+ Challenging.Verychallenging. Make one misstep in battle, and you might find yourself in deep♥♥♥♥♥♥ And there are traps to look out for in some battle maps, too.+ An intriguing story. I'm about 3/4 through the story, and it's still rather mysterious, but I feel like I'm getting somewhere, and getting to know the dealer.+ Quests are progressive. Whenever you clear an encounter, you gain a token, which unlocks the next stage of the quest. All the quests are quite original, and nothing is ever as it seems.+ It has a Curse and Blessing system, which randomizes the difficulty of the game in a way. If you're unlucky. If you're lucky, and get a few nice Blessings, the game becomes a smooth run.Cons:- Maybe I'm just unlucky, but sometimes the odds against you are plain ridiculous. I mean, one Jack, six lizardmen and four bandits against one person with a basic axe and shield, with two curses?- No ranged attacks for the player. Enemies can shoot fireballs and arrows freely at you, but you can't whip up magic or a bow. You gotta run up to their♥♥♥♥♥and kick it.- Some achievements are locked in Apprentice (easy) mode. I mean, I get it. I want a challenge too. But sometimes, Adventurer is just too hard because I'm not that quick with my fingers. And I'd still like to get my achievements while struggling away on easy mode.- In story mode, no matter what equipment you collect, you always start out with a basic axe and shield. Good luck trying to kill more than 10 enemies at once, while avoiding traps, if the dealer decides to be pissy with you. At least let me select my gear? I literally get to use a decent weapon only once in about five runs.- Enemies scale as you progress. This means every encounter, no matter how trivial, is difficult... perhaps too difficult. When you're fighting 2 Scales and 4 undead with a basic axe for the 200th time, combat gets repetitivefast. And because of scaling, you can't plough through the common ones even if you've triggered this encounter for the thousandth time.TL;DR: Hand of Fate has a solid premise, intriguing encounters and an element of luck to everything. But the game can be very frustrating and merciless - although one can say it's part of the package when you play a game of this genre. Still, the amount of times I ragequitted this... I can't recommend it when 80% of the time, it makes mesoangry. Even when I have a successful run, I don't feel the urge to continue, because I know it can go to hell just as quickly. This is a game for those with nerves of steel. Or just a♥♥♥♥♥♥ton of patience."
,Not Recommended,266510,32908079,Posted: 27 June,all,Macho Man Randy Savage,"I wish there was an 'undecided' or 'conflicted' choice between recommend and not recommended, because that's exactly how I feel about hand of Fate; conflicted. One half of the game feels polished, well-done, inspired, and enjoyable, while the other half of the game feels clunky, frustrating, and greatly disappointing.Most of the game is played through a large variety of cards which feel like a thoughtful mixture of dungeons & dragons and an at-home tabletop card game. Something like; 'You find an elven maiden in an emerald grove, what do you do?' then, based off your choices(and whether or not you succeed or fail)you are either rewarded with food, health, gold, or items, or you suffer a penalty of one of the above. Or worse, you face a random encounter – which is not to say that random encounters are the most dangerous of penalties in the game, but that they are the most cumbersome and thoughtless segments of the entire game. The combat isn't fun, and it isn't really challenging. At best it' is a bearable distraction, and at worst it's incredibly frustrating.It almost feels like there were two teams(or people)who developed the game completely separate from each other and that one group wanted the game to be an engaging card-based d&d style game, while the other group just wanted to emulate a sloppy hack-and-slash game styled after the bland combat in Batman Arkham Asylum. “Tap left-click to attack and tap Q to parry”. There is some variation if you have unique weaponry or equipment, but it only serves to make combat in Hand of Fate feel like less of a “chore” which exactly how you DONT want your game's combat to feel.Honestly, I admire the idea here: “What if a d&d styled card game had interactive combat?” With proper execution in both parts, we might have discovered an incredibly enjoyable niche game. But, while the card game segment is very well done, the combat isn't and the game suffers as a whole because of it. In my opinion the developers should have left combat to the cards and some dice rolls. It would have felt more in tune with the overall theme, felt much less clunky, and the extra development budget and time not spent on 3d modeling and combat coding could have greatly boosted the already enjoyable card segments. More cards, more card-based encounters, maybe even some cool screen visuals for certain effects, etc. In short, if they had scrapped the combat system, this game could have been so much better.To make things worse, the card-game segment itself is very rouge-like, in that death will end your play and you'll be forced to restart your chapter progress from the start, but with the added benefit of gaining new cards which can bolster your character and add exciting new twists and turns for the next game. That in itself isn't bad at all, in fact it's enjoyable, but the problem comes from RNG and how cards can work in this game. Despite how many new cards you get from playing the game your character will ALWAYS start out a chapter with base equipment and stats(which can get better as you progress through the story but only after key chapters, and the progression is equally tied to enemy strength and difficulty, so the improvements always feel negligible and counteracted). RNG rears it's ugly face in the order by which you draw cards, and playing with the DLC 'characters' which add some new pro's and con's to your playthrough, you might be doomed from the very start thanks to such RNG.For example, I tried my first Endless mode with a character that can only eat Iron Ore from discarded equipment and during my route(which was entirely linear from the start)I didn't come across a single piece of equipment. My character ran out of food and starved to death before I could find any gear to salvage for sustenance, and I wasn't able to scrap any of my equipped gear as a last resort because that's not a function of the game. I was doomed from the start to fail the match and all I gained were a few measly cards. This sort of RNG isn't absent from other rouge-likes, but-in my opinion-it is poor design. I don't expect the RNG to ensure my victory from the start, or at all for that matter, but I should have more control over my character's “Fate” than hoping I land on the exact cards I need to survive, especially in Endless mode where I have ZERO control over which cards are in the deck and which might appear next.An idea that could have fixed this issue would have been 'hand cards' which you draw at the beginning of a game and are added to your 'hand'. You could use them at any time to gain supplies or whichever other benefit they provide and they either can't be refilled or can only be refilled on other rare event cards. For example, when playing the character which can only eat Iron Ore, you could start off with one or two random equipment cards, nothing worth equipping(rusted stuff maybe)but for use in case of emergencies. This way you're not entirely at the mercy of RNG if you run into a stretch of bad luck. Something like that could have been a very simple and enjoyable addition to the game which could have provided a bit more player choice and control. Letting players alter their 'hand cards' at the start of a match, for example, choosing from the pile of new cards they have acquired, would have been a great way to support players who really enjoy certain styles of play but might struggle under the fickleness of RNG.Sadly, the absence of such a feature and the “fate” of your character more often than not relying on RNG isn't ideal for me. I understand that the game is called “Hand of Fate” and that “fate” implies a degree of luck and chance, but that shouldn't mean my character is guaranteed to not survive past the second floor because the RNG layout is entirely non-viable for my character. That isn't just 'fate' that's poor design, and it isn't enjoyable. I'll continue to play this game and I hope that further progression might change my mind, but for right now – I just can't recommend this kind of a game. The card-game segment is well written and clearly a thoughtful and lovingly designed portion of the game, but almost everything else(the combat, RNG, and some card and character mechanics)really ruin the atmosphere for me.6/10 Slightly above average, but the parts that do work are niche elements and I can't recommend the package as a whole."
