,Recommended,266510,17195617,"Posted: 23 July, 2015",all,Rane2k,"What drew me towards this game was the aesthethics and atmosphere shown in the trailers, and I was not disappointed.The game is presented as you, the protagonist, sitting across from the dealer, a mysterious hooded figure, to play game of cards.Everything in the game has a representation as a playing card.The playing field is a bunch of cards, laid out in small mazes.Your equipment is made up of cards like weapons, helms, shields and a plethora of rings.Your enemies are cards in 4 suites (dust, skulls, scales and plague), each of which is a theme (e.g. the card ""2 of dust"" is a pair of bandits).The cards are sorted into various stacks and decks, the most important two are the equipment deck, from which you draw your rewards; and the encounter deck, from which the playing field is drawn.The encounter deck shapes the way the game plays out, which is a mix of ""choose your adventure"" style events, and combat situations.""Choose your adventure"" & Overworld gameplayBetween encounters you move your figure between cards, one per turn. As you step onto a card it is revealed, and the dealer narrates the events that ensue, while you decide how you act in the situation.There is a wide range of different situations presented here, some result in combat, some might draw you cards from the pain deck (punishments, if your decisions or luck are bad) or the gain deck (food, gold, health, equipment).On some encounters you play for a token, which represents one (or more!) cards to unlock for future rounds.Aside from your inventory, you have health, food and gold as resources, all of which are important. On each turn, you consume 1 food, which heals you, unless you have no food, in which case you begin to starve. This quickly results in death, and means that you should plan a few turns ahead. And maybe not spend all your gold on shiny rings, but good instead.Combat & ControlsWhenever you enter combat mode, you enter the world in third person mode and do battle against the monster cards the dealer has drawn for you.Controls are fairly simple, left stick to move around, and the actions at your disposal are ""attack"", ""counter"" (if you have a shield), ""weapon ability"" and ""use artifact"" (usually buffs or area effect attacks)While this may appear shallow at first, it becomes rather taxing once there are more than a few enemies on screen, some of which may have ranged or special attacks, or block your attacks.I played with a controller and felt the game controlled very smoothly. I did not try mouse/keyboard at all, so cannot make a statement about it.Progression, Attrition & Deck building elementsAfter you beat the tutorial, the dealer reveals to you that there are 12 champions (the ""royal"" cards of the suites, Jacks, Queens and Kings) for you to defeat. As you progress through the game you unlock many new equipment and encounter cards.Out of these you build 2 decks which the rounds are based on.But as you gain more cards, the dealer also inserts his own cards into the encounter deck, the pain deck and of course the monster deck from which your opponents are pulled.In one session you will usually accrue a number of items making combat easier for you, but to balance it out, you will also take damage, consume resources and later might be struck by one or more of the dealer´s nasty curse cards.These serve as a means of hampering your progress, to not make it too easy for you. They range from basic debuffs (e.g. starvation causes more damage) to severe restrictions (e.g. you can not sell items, or ""the more gold you carry, the slower you move""), putting you into interesting predicaments.Attrition, difficulty and long term funDeath is permanent, but especially in the beginning of the game you will mostly emerge from a round with several newly unlocked cards, as such, frustration is kept to a minimum.Unlocking new cards is a strong incentive to keep playing, as many of the cards are interesting, and the encounter cards often form little story arcs.I beat the game after about 20 hours, meaning I defeated all of the champions.After beating the main game, there is also an endless mode, in which you dont construct a deck, but have all of your unlocked cards available (and so has the dealer, that sinister man.)There were a few difficulty spikes (mostly the Jack of Scales and the King of skulls for me), but nothing too bad.Graphics, Sound & atmosphereAs mentioned before, the art style and graphics, as well as the beautiful music (with an oriental touch) serve to craft a very nice atmosphere.The sinister musings of the dealer are often interesting (tough they repeat after a while, but not to the point where they are annoying)GripesWhile I can heartily recommend the game, there are a few gripes & nitpicks I have, which I will list here, in case they are a show-stopper to you:Some of the cards seem rather imbalanced, some equipment feel too strong (2 of the rings, I won´t spoil which) and some enemy encounters can stop a round quite early (The kraken especially, but at least it´s a card that you unlock rather late)In-game advertising for the DLC (extra characters, which are basically game modifieres), achievements which can only be done with the DLC.The DLC is only ""okay""Endless mode starts out a bit slow, the first 2-3 floors are usually a cakewalkSometimes the combat can be a bit repetitive, more so if you aim for maximum unlocks/achievementsOur hero´s deadly sin isgluttony, seriously, one food per turn, learn some restraint!"
