,Recommended,266510,14551848,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,AA,"This game is a card game.  It is a resource management game.  It is a brawler. It is a text based, classic adventure game. It is a RPG and a rogue-like. This game is phenomenal, I thoroughly enjoyed my short time with it so far.I played but just 1 hour of Hand of Fate, I closed the game and instantly came to write this piece.  If you are like me and you like a good RPG, choose your own adventure or anything vaguely close to fantasy, I feel you will appreciate the direction that this game embarked upon.Hand of Fate handles the tutorial with such finesse that I wasn’t even aware it was a tutorial until it had come to a end – I was already invested In my character and in my story.When you first boot up the game it will launch you directly in to the “game of life and death”, as is so aptly described by the card dealer. You will proceed to get comfortable at the fortune teller-esque table and Gothic surroundings with a inexplicably cryptic figure who welcomes you to the game of life and death. We do not know who the card dealer is, but you will get a sense of power and mystique as he shuffles the deck. Very quickly you will come to realise that Hand of Fate is not a run-of-the-mill card game, it is that and so much more.The premise is to advance through each area and kill the twelve different heroes, that are under the guidance of the quippy card dealer.  The dealer will lay several cards in front of you on to a table, where you will take control of a game piece, just like in a board game. To advance you must move the game piece on to the different cards and watch the game unfold, for every card you move to one piece of food will be consumed – manage these resources very carefully. Each card brings with it its own adventure and riches, its own danger and fortunes, will you be brave and save the Captain of the Guard or leave him to the fate of the Undead?Defeating a hero card can be rewarding and in some cases, difficult.  With them, hero cards draw different monster cards from the deck that will place them in to the battle, increasing its difficulty. Once a hero is defeated, the game is over and you will be able to use any card tokens that you obtained throughout your journey to unlock more cards.Unlocking cards will allow you to customize your deck to your liking, just like any other collectible card game. If you are not in to fiddling about with so many cards, or are inexperienced with creating card decks, there is a option to create a deck optimized for you – Which the game will do for you.The tone is set from the exact moment you launch the game – it is dark, it is mysterious and it is Gothic. The art direction for this title is spot on, everything just fits in to place, even the cards are designed in such an intricate way they left me feeling that I was really sitting at the table playing this game. The burning candle flickering over the game table sets the perfect mood for a stare-down with a hooded, mystic figure. I would love to be able to buy myself a physical copy of the cards.I genuinely cared for the actions that I took.  I wanted to save the Captain of the Guard, I wanted to loot the goblin cave and plunder its riches and I felt it necessary to make a deal with the devil. I delved in to reading each card and the tales it brought with it.  My hero was a holy-mace wielding, bandit slaying, guard saving badass and I loved it. I wanted to make sure that he had the gear I wanted him to have; maybe not necessary the best gear, but the gear that I believed fit in to his persona. This was a pen and paper RPG at its finest.Did I mention that this game is a brawler?  No?  Well it is.  When the cards are down and the candle flickers, when playing the game of life and death and inhaling the musky atmosphere, expect to kill or be killed. Combat is not turn based – It is not handled like a card game nor is it RPG-like.  I would forgive you for thinking that combat happens like that of a text-based adventure game, but you would be wrong. You, your character and all of the gear you have amassed will be teleported in to a 3D environment along with the monster cards that were drawn, and you will fight.  Combat is much like the Arkham series, but feels less polished.  It is obvious that this was not meant to be the games strong point – And that is okay.  It works and It fits in with the game, hell, at this point what doesn’t?Within 1 hour of gameplay I had created a character that I was entirely invested in and cared about. He had saved the Captain of the Guard who provided us with his powerful Mace masked in a Holy boon to ward off the Undead. I had met a Fair Maiden who blessed me with life longevity by providing me with a +5 health boost. I encountered Mister Lionel, a Goblin disguised as a old man who mysteriously appeared a shield right in front of my face, as a gift. I had scaled the winding vines of a canyon as a glistening metal caught my eye – I had found a sword. The Maze Of Traps had been conquered and the gold plundered. I defeated the Devil’s challenge before looting a Dead King’s Tomb for +10 Max health, food and riches. I was no longer playing as a character in a video game, I was me and I was creating a story.Hand of Fate is fantastic and if you have a vested interest in RPG’s, card games or fantasy I highly suggest that you give this game a go.  It is something different that tries and succeeds in covering many different game genres. This game is a gem that I was not expecting, I had no idea that this game was being released and I am glad I paid a measly £15 for this phenomenal title.  I know for certain I have only scratched at the surface of this game and I need to get back to playing more.For more like this, head toXB92AI.com"
,Recommended,266510,14606889,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,hiero,"A truly unique game and experience, Hand of Fate is part rogue-like RPG with choose-your-own-adventure elements, part Assassin's Creed, Arkham style brawler, and part tabletop deck building game. The game lets you choose your own paths and craft your own story, and no two games are ever alike. A witty and snarky card dealer who sits across the table narrates much of your journey and adds his own personal commentary to the decisions you make and the fates that befall you.The music is great, it's incredibly atmospheric and sets the stage and mood quite nicely. The voice acting is fantastic, the number of cards is large and varied, and the aesthetic is all around perfect.The combat system is the only problem the game suffers, and even then it still works well. At times the animations can be a bit stiff and janky and there isn't much depth to it, but at the end of the day it's a nitpick to an overall fantastic game and experience.If you enjoy rogue-likes, choose-your-own-adventures, deck builders, and story telling, pick this up."
,Recommended,266510,16521766,"Posted: 19 June, 2015",all,Velcro Spider,"Hand of Fate took my interest a while back when it was on Early Access so I put it on my wishlist.  Now it's on sale and with Steam's newly implemented refund system online I thought I would give it a go and I'm very glad I did!To watch the gameplay videos does not do this game an ounce of justice, especially if you watch one from the beginning of the game and the reason for this is also one of it's biggest strengths.  Hand of Fate does a fantastic job of teaching by doing; there are no 'press 1 to feel' tutorials here, you enter the game and press start and before you know it you're already playing.  The first run is short and gives you a good idea about what the game is about but without smothering you in advanced rules and options and things you won't remember later on.For the whole game you sit opposite a nefarious looking fellow akin to a games master, he draws cards for you and tells the story.  You simply have to choose the path you travel through the level and deal with each card as you land on it.  It may be an encounter you enter where you must fight (more on combat below), a series of traps you must negociate or a tradiditional text based quandry to muse over, where the outcome is determined by blind choosing one of four cards.  The likelyhood of being successful is often directly related to your gear, i.e. it's easier to cross a river in light armour than heavy so more of the four cards will give success and fewer failure.As I alluded to previously simply watching the gameplay and combat videos do this game a great misjustice, hack and slash is not terrbily exciting to watch and the very reason you are fighting is lost.  You cannot possibly know the tension created by this being your penultimate fight before the boss of the level, that the card before was a goblin card and they stole your shield and that prior to which was a merchant card where you sold your spare shield.  The story that goes along with each encounter really enriches the combat, which really only makes up a portion of the game on the whole anyway.Finally there is the hearthstone-esque component of Hand of Fate; each time you complete a run you unlock more cards.  There are 3 decks, equipment for yourself (just because you choose to put a fancy new hammer in your deck doesn't mean you will ever draw it - just like in HS where you may be desperate for that flamestrikebut not draw it), modifiers to your character (flavour cards that add boons and debuffs and add great variety to playthroughs) and finally encounters.  When you get new cards you have to experience them in the game to see what they actually do (equipment included) so often you pick new cards with a hint of trepidation.  As you become more powerful and add more of your own cards so must you also add more cards for the game master to play and the enemies also grow in power and variety.In closing I have played this game for 2 hours and felt compelled to write a fairly detailed review in the hopes it might urge others to try this fantastic game.  Worst case you play for just less than 2 hours and ask for a refund if it's not for you, best case you enjoy this gem as much as I did."
,Recommended,266510,32872827,Posted: 27 June,all,Ottawa,"This is a super fun randomly generated dungeon game. It's inventive, you build your own dungeon by placing cards into a deck, then you traverse it. It does get tedious, since the combat is fairly one dimensional, but everything else about this game is super neat."
,Not Recommended,266510,29327326,Posted: 17 January,all,Tartrazine,"If you're STILL on the fence, wait for the sequel to fix the combatI had a LOT of fun with Hand of Fate. Expanding and customizing your deck of equipment and encounter cards is great. Some cards have very finnicky or downright unfair requirements to unlock them, but this FTL-esque difficulty makes it that much more satisfying to edit your deck to max out your slim chances. The dealer who runs the game is like a snarkier version of The Merchant from Resident Evil 4. He has a clever quip for everything, and I never got sick of hearing his lines, even after I had played the game so much that I'd heard most of them twenty times before. (Nothing makes getting a good piece of equipment satisfying like his comment, ""I made that a little too powerful..."").The reason I do NOT recommend Hand of Fate (if you're still not sure if this is worth your time and money) is that the core of the game is a really sloppy copy of the Batman games' combat. Combat feels clunky. The camera can't be rotated, leading to all sorts of frustration. Cannon fodder enemies take too many hits to kill, and they don't have any visual indication that they've taken damage, making it VERY frustrating to figure out which of the dozen identical-looking lizardmen you're fighting only needs one more hit to die. You also aren't shown any numbers for how much damage you're doing to enemies, which is particularly frustrating for one of the final boss fights where it is not NEARLY obvious enough that his minions are invincible as long as he's alive.To make matters worse if your computer is old, there are no separate graphic settings for the combat (where getting a smooth frame rate is crucial) and the card map (where frame rate is irrelevant) so going with ""low"" quality textures so that you can actually win fights makes the cards on the map almost illegible.Hand of Fate 2 is coming out later in 2017, and it looks like it will dramatically improve the combat, so you should probably just wait for it instead of struggling with the flawed original."
