,Recommended,266510,20649998,"Posted: 20 January, 2016",all,bobert awful (F+),"During my review of Chainsaw Warrior (also on Steam), I commented about how the computer game port of Chainsaw Warrior was easier to play than the actual card game published by Games Workshop, because it was easier to play a one-player card game with rules as convoluted and dorky as a computer game than as an actual, physical card game. What would happen if someone walked in on you rolling dice and drawing cards all by yourself?""Oh, are you playing Solitaire?""""No! I'm not playing Solitaire. I'm playing a game where you have to fight zombies and aliens and disarm a nuclear bomb in 60 minutes or the world will be plunged into eternal darkness.""""...it is okay to masturbate, Jimmy. You don't have to be ashamed of your body.""""But I'm not doing the M-word, Daaaaaaaaad!""Hand of Fate is like one of those dorky card games. I think the developers realized this when they started development, and so they threw in the card dealer and added all the stuff about life and death afterwards. It definitely needed it - because the Dealer is what really makes this game work. Without the Dealer, the game is you, sitting at a table, drawing cards and hallucinating these battles and these traps and sometimes wrestling with a convoluted camera angle operated by a narcoleptic operator. Plus there wouldn't be all these interesting story crumbs as to who the Dealer is, why you're here playing this game, the big dust-up that will eventually happen between you and him if he draws one more ♥♥♥♥ing Devilish Traps card.It's not a bad game, but I just feel like it depended on a lot of the momentum from my earlier victories to keep me going, because I got tired of it after I got stuck fighting the King of Scales. Speaking of the King of Scales: This game has a difficulty curve that partially resembles a flat area and then a sudden, large ramp-up in difficulty on the last two stages. The difficulty curve ramps up on the King of Scales because the game forgets to tell you that his henchmen are all invincible while he's around, something that took me ten tries and five minutes in the Steam Community forums to realize. Also there's some fun balance issues that randomly make the game too easy or hard. And I hate when the game makes me have to run through a Traps level, because not only are you trying not to die to a bunch of traps, you're also playing with a really ♥♥♥♥♥♥ camera angle that hides some of those traps.So while it's not a perfect game, it's rather fun while the unlocks keep coming, but when they stop... oh man, this game starts to fall into a RUT."
,Not Recommended,266510,33505481,Posted: 13 July,all,General Kass,"I feel like something's missing and I can't quite put my finger on it. Yet beneth everything I'm about to say, I still found Hand of Fate to be a fun and addictive experience.Hand of Fate is fantastic as an experimental game. Even the premise is unique: You're a veteran adventurer who has reached the end of the world. A magic fortune teller offers a game that will unlock your forgotten memories. Every card in the game is something that's already happened. That alone is clever. However, the game's style is just as interesting. It's progressive DnD questing in the style of tabletop card game, with interactive combat encounters, a card collection mechanic, and rougelike elements. On the surface, that sounds great.The progressive quests are, in my opinion, one of the most interesting features. Quests take the form of both cards and game board squares. Each quest has multiple sections which are unlocked by completing the previous objectives. Completing a leg of the quest nets you a token which unlocks weapons, abilities, or the next part of the quest. These unlocks take the form of cards, which you can use to ""stack the deck"" in your favor. When starting a new campaign, your hero always has base equipment, but unlocks more through event cards. Unfortunatley, enemies scale as the player does to ""maintain balance."" The result is that you never feel like you can get ahead. Not in combat and not in quests.The quests themselves are well written and a few of them are laugh out loud funny. Unfortunatley, there's only a handful of ways to complete quests. You either offer or ask for supplies, start a combat encounter, or play 4 card monte.The problem with the card game is that it's essentially a dice roll disguised as an actual choice. You have 4 cards. Based on difficulty they will be some variation of ""huge success,"" ""success,"" ""failure,"" or ""huge failure."" This would be ok on it's own, but the game includes a curse debuff that only serves to purposely unbalance this selection process. I'll admit however that I appreciate the fact that the cards are actually shuffled. About 1/4 times you can track the card on top.However, here's an example of what to expect with the 4 card monte:* Have unlucky curse that makes shuffles too fast to see.* Meet ""Cursed Gambler""* Walk away and lose half your foodor* Play 4 card monte* 3 cards are ""failure,"" which results in a curse.* The next card on your journey is ANOTHER ""Cursed Gambler"" and there's still 2 more in the deck.The problem with this card design is that it ""feels"" unfair, which is all that really matters in the question of player retention. Even a rigged dice would ""feel"" better because there's a wider range of options.The farther you go, the more obscene these checks become. Higher level quests (White Minotaur and Spice Trader) may require you to complete 3-5 increasingly unlikely rolls. These quickly become both tedious and ridiculous, especially when you chase a quest all across the board, only to fail the last check before the token. Oh well, better luck next time. Not only that, but some checks are actually completed by failing the roll. You never know what to expect because the rules are constantly changing based on the scenario.So you fail the card selection and enter combat. The dealer draws (2) 4 of Plauges. This means you'll be facing off against 8 ratmen, 2 of them armed with unlimited throwing spears. You enter combat and it's Arkham Asylum style rhythm combat. But there's a problem. Other than pricey artefacts and randomly assigned weapons, you have no upgrades. Standard combat is nothing but smashing the mouse button and raising your sheild when projectiles appear. If you're facing that (2) 4 of Plague, you'll be deflecting poisoned projectiles about every 2 seconds. You gain damage with higher combos and hard mode offers several items that increase your speed and damage so long as you don't get hit, but the projectiles become incredibly difficult to block when faced with more than 5 enemies.All of this makes the combat needlessly frustrating, especially since (as previously stated) enemies improve as the player does and most of them have a lot more HP than you'd expect. Every single enemy in the game has more health than the player, which is needlessly frustrating and I'd argue unbalanced. A default player character has 100hp. A single goblin has enough health to achieve an 11 hit combo with a 23 damage weapon. Worse, they always appears in groups of three. That is objectively bad game design.Mad Max got away with Arkham Asylum combat because it had character upgrades, weapon variation, and enemy variation; Hand of Fate has the same button mashing over and over and over and over and over again. The worst is a quest that requires you to land a chain of 30 hits against enemies with shields who have a 100% to block your attack and will always make an unblockable counter attack to your parry.As a final note, the other problem is the roguelike distribution of event cards on the map. Because a unit of food is used up on each square, you constantly need to replenish supplies. However, you generally have no control over whether you live or die. Non-combat deaths are through no fault of your own. You have no control over your money when a curse (which costs $300 gold to remove) detracts a chunk of your gold at the end of each combat encounter. You have no control of food when the cursed gambler either steals your food or hits you with another curse. Hand of Fate gives the illusion of control through the map and 4 card monte. In reality your choices are limited to stores and how you move in combat. The rest is typically beyond your control or made to look like you're in control when you're just along for the ride. While it does fit with the name ""Hand of Fate"" it doesn't fit with an interactive game.I think I finally know what's missing. Player agency. Unavoidable and disastrous events happen too often for long term play. Combat is too simple and relies heavily on the luck of the equipment draw. Since you know what big creature you're hunting, you can stack the deck for that enemy type, but as you approach the end of the game, you need more and more cards which makes it less and less likely that you'll actually be equipped for the coming boss battle.Pitch Hand of Fate against another rougelike, FTL for example, and see what happens. FTL  put players in a position where they still have options even when they were outgunned and were unable to even damage the enemy. FTL always kept control in the hands of the player, even under the worst conditions.In Hand of Fate the dealer is always in control and the player is just along for the ride. Because the game will choose your optimum cards and because movement squares and event cards are automatically highlighted, you can literally (though with much difficulty) play this game to the end just by endlessly pressing the space bar. If player input is so minimal that a drinking bird can feasibly play at the same skill level as a human, you haven't created a game of choices, you've created a movie that requires button pressing to reach the next scene.All that having been said, I would be open to a Hand of Fate 2 that fixed all of these issues or even Hand of Fate spinoffs in different settings. This is a great experiment, just not a great game."
76561198047941227,Recommended,266510,13690161,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,RedMint,"Here's the best compliment I can give this game - I bought Hand of Fate and Shadows of Mordor at the same time, and Hand of Fate is the one that pulled me in the hardest and I'm playing more often, despite the polish of the other AAA title.This game does something I've always wanted to see in a game - watching your encounters be created through chance or fate around you, while you actually play through it. Have been wanting this since way back in the days of Vampire the Masquerade - and it never really came.  Hand of Fate manages this really nicely, as the encounter you are about to face is created by the very cards you draw.  The smooth Arkham-style fighting rounds this out to be a solid, very layered game.The graphics are unique and nice, a cool blend of fancy hand-drawn card/boardgame and more Diablo-esque arcade environments.  You feel like you're across from your nemesis/Game Master and that it's all playing out based on your interactions with him.  The voice acting of this GM-type character is critical to the game since you hear his voice so much, so thankfully they've got A-list voice work here.Very replayable as you collect cards and expand the possibilities of each game.  Roguelike in that once you die, you die and your current adventure is over, but the cards you've earned along the way are still added to future adventures making for even more diversity.This game is in early access right now and it still plays like a complete game.  It's awesome and in only 4ish hours of play I can already tell I'm addicted to it somewhat.  If the developer/s keep polishing and expanding this, I think it could potentially explode on the scene and start a beloved new franchise because so far it's as good as any I've played.Think Talisman meets Magic the Gathering meets Diablo and you'll be roughly in the ballpark.  Thumbs up."
