76561197980503707,Recommended,266510,29347604,Posted: 18 January,all,Zaimad,"Hand of Fate is... a strategic action brawler game? I'm not quite sure how to categorize Hand of Fate, other than the words ""pure genious"".Picture this: you are a traveller seeking what destiny awaits you. A mysterious fortune teller deals cards face down as if they were the lay of the land, and you move your token across them. Upon contact, the card is lifted and revealed: you have an encounter. You do not necessarily have to fight to resolve most of them, nor should you shy away from combat, nor should you attempt to engage in combat. Each and every choice has potential outcomes and you are encouraged to experiment them all.Of course, you might consider the above description of the gameplay a little vague. Simply put, gameplay revolves around four phases.1) The choice of which adjacent card to move onto, searching for the exit or the boss encounter.2) The event is revealed, which in turn requires that you make choices on your actions and/or throws you into combat.3) The event is resolved, or you died, or something good or bad happened. Either way, consequences.4) You appreciate or despise what happened and move on to the next event as you continue your quest, or start anew if you got killed.The reason this game is so good isn't the simplistic combat when you do fight, nor is it entirely the great amounts of rich descriptions of the events you encounter (although that really helps). It is the dealer's words, commenting on what appears before you, your choices, his scorn when you take his pieces or his joy in seeing you suffer for what torments you. The dealer is an entire third of your enjoyment in this game, and it doesn't disappoint.Frankly, this is the game that I return to play sessions of between 10 minutes to about an hour every now and then. It is wonderful, even when you have seen practically all the possible encounters over and over again. But don't let my words deceive you: you will start the game with few things unlocked. You must complete the dealer's challenges, and with them you are rewarded cards to add to his deck. From better equipment to harder monsters, crossing through new and mysterious encounters as the game naturally progresses to a harsher state with more variability.You will rage. You will laugh. You will listen to a story in which you are the protagonist and the story-teller is your opponent. And you will love the Hand of Fate.Buy it, definitely. Maybe with a discount, but it's really a good game. As of the time of writing, there's also something else you should consider:http://store.steampowered.com/app/456670If you like the Hand of Fate, or if the Hand of Fate 2 is as good or better than the first, buy them both!"
,Recommended,266510,33885921,Posted: 29 July,all,WTWR Zydrate,"I'll write up a full-length proper review eventually but so far, I quite enjoy this game and I'm not overly fond of cardgames. However certain roguelikes recently have enchanted me to the genre, and I'm not a player that appreciates difficulty. I play to have fun, getting destroyed is not fun. When I don't have fun, I don't play.Still, after my extended stint on Shadow of Mordor and Mad Max, I was highly familiar with HoF's combat system which I've taken to like a champ, surviving a dozen enemies on ten health or so, and once my procedural card-bound dungeon actually helped me recover from 3 hitpoints to a full 90 after a few particularly lucky encounters. So the game doesn't go out of its way to ruin you like other roguelikes, as I've noticed the majority of my health loss is from the combat itself (I say right after bragging...) Some say the combat is the weaker point of the game but I feel it does the job and doesn't outstay its welcome; An open world this is not. The combat is there to give yourself a break from the ocassional bouts of reading.So this game is essentially a dungeon crawler that builds itself with cards, and you go through many DnD-like encounters and storylines that include feeding peasants, begging an elf for stuff, and following the trail of destruction from a group of mages. Great stuff.In my two hours I haven't died yet but it's cutting close. Upon subsequent playthroughs, your deck size gets bigger (hurr?) which allows for better chances at decent gear, while enemies remain a bit tougher to take out as well. I find myself having a lot of fun with it and that's what matters."
,Not Recommended,266510,29737325,Posted: 6 February,all,Updog,"If you're looking for a card game / dungeon crawler / Batman simulator, this is the game for you, but you'll probably get bored before the end of the story mode.It does a lot of different things, and most of them work really well. The art is great, the dialogue is well written, well performed, and well programmed (even by AAA standards), and it's just a really sexy premise. However, a lot of the elements clash against each other, rather than gelling together. For example, the Dealer is a fine character, but his dialogue distracts you from reading all the text (PRO TIP: you can skip all the text boxes and not miss anything). The tone of the dialogue is awesomely dark, which makes some of the goofy card text feel inappropriate. The card illustrations feel realistically medieval, and so it's really jarring when the combat looks like superheroes smacking each other in the middle of a laser light show, and the player is represented by a comedic murderhobo with a silly beard.The first big problem is the combat system. It's exactly the same as the Batman: Arkham games, except much MUCH slower, more forgiving, and less exciting. The camera is useless, the hitboxes are vague, the animation and voice acting is terrible, and the rhythm just feels wrong. It simultaneously feels insultingly easy, and unfairly hard. If you're familiar with the Batman games, this game will just be really frustrating.The second big problem is that the game feels really slow and sluggish. Every single thing takes a few seconds more than it should, and it really adds up to a big frustration. In FTL, when you get to a store, you click the ""store"" button and it instantly pops up. In this game, you need to wait for a loading screen to load a completely pointless 3D environment. When you make a decision with a random outcome, it shows this long unskippable animation of cards shuffling. And don't even get me started on how slow the combat is--it's like the battles are taking place underwater! And in case it's not slow enough already, it goes to slow motion whenever you do a special attack. That made sense in Arkham Asylum, because it's a very cinematic game about a badass superhero, but it just doesn't work in a gritty roguelike. (And in Batman, it doesn't slow down EVERY TIME, and you can push a button to cancel the slowmo.) I really wish I could set the entire game to 200% speed.Ultimately, despite all the time you spend on exploring the board and managing your resources, the game just boils down to one combat encounter after another. All the methodical slowness on the game board feels like pointless delays. And since the combat isn't fun enough, it just gets boring after a while. To me, a good roguelike (like FTL) is one you can play over and over again. This game, I'm pretty much done with it before finishing the story campaign. So while there's a lot of good stuff in this game, and I had fun during the short time I spent with it, I have to give it a thumbs down.(The ""hours played"" on my account is not accurate; I accidentally left the game open in the background one day.)"
