,Recommended,266510,31403356,Posted: 27 April,all,Pancakes,"If you enjoy a good card game, then this is immediately worth checking out, and even if not, the narrator alone makes this game worth a look in my opinion. Sure, the animation in the actual combat is a bit janky and sometimes odd-looking, but it still looks at least decent and you won't see allthatmuch of it. Other than that a very pretty game overall, and the card faces, great writing, and animation on the Dealer make up for the combat animation by leaps and boundsThe deck building mechanic is very well constructed and well balanced, and the game can get brutal at times if you aren't careful about how you spend your resources.Just for example, I gave a whole lot of my food to a priest to be blessed, then lost all of my gold to bandits and couldn't buy more food. Luckily, the blessing was being healed for every enemy I killed. Thus, I made my way across uninhabited lands, slaughtering everything I could find to combat my ongoing starvation, until I found a stack of gold right next to a store and blew it all on supplies.And throughout it all, the Dealer just lamented how boring it would be for me to starve to death, asked if it was getting to me yet, and contemplated how he could save me with a single card, but that that would be ""breaking the rules"".I've not found many games that can create experiences quite like Hand Of Fate can, and really, this game is so lovingly crafted I just have to recommend it for the sheer amount of character it has! The voice actor for the Dealer and the creators of the music deserve commendations of some kind, because this is truly a wonderful game to listen to."
