,Recommended,266510,28803437,"Posted: 29 December, 2016",all,Yodzilla,"Hand of Fate is an unexpected gem. It's a deck building rogue-lite with Choose Your Own Adventure elements and combat similar to the Arkham Batman series. If that description is confusing don't worry, the game itself is pretty straightforward and easy to understand.Really the thing that sells this game is the presentation and dialog. The mysterious dealer is a great character who guides you through your quests in a really engaging way. There's a ton of replayability and I've honestly never played a game quite like this.If the game had a downside it's that the combat isn't nearly as smooth as it could be but it still gets the job done. Highly recommended for people who want something unique to sink hours into."
76561198059342148,Recommended,266510,33963975,Posted: 1 August,all,Hmongherooooo,"I really enjoyed the game and I am quite excited for HOF2. As a very unlucky person, I still am able to enjoy this game, half the time you are going to die due to how unfair it is going to get, but at the same time, it's mostly luck.The game is basically played almost like a Rogue DnD session where you are placed on a board of random encounter cards, you have food,gold, and health. Food is basically used to move around the board and also live + regen. You complete each ""board"" of 4-8 cards by finding the ""exit"" card. There's either an endless mode, or a story mode. With each, there's a lot of encouters in the game that make it interesting, of course, once you see a new encounter, you get used to seeing them everytime, but you unlock more the more you complete them. The encounters themselves may have a story to them, or a simple event. Some encounters can be generous while others require you to choose your fate. Most encounters make you select from 4 chance cards ( it can be 1 huge failure, 1 huge success, 1 failure, 1 success ). It's up to your luck and your choice, or you can avoid most of them. Through the encounters you gain random items. The loot is pretty interesting, not too game changing, there are just shields, helmets, armor, weapons, rings, and trinkets which only affect combat. The board aspect of this game is completely chance, you could honestly die from starvation with no control over it ( you do get an upgrade near the end of the game that makes food plentiful).As for the combat from certain encounters or the boss for the story, it's decent and simple, It does take some time getting used to the timing and the camera angle. The first thing to think of is Batman combat with more timing ( and the further you get into the game, the more traps appear on each battlefield). There's not much to such a simple combat, which I like.Overall, it's a pretty good game with interesting mechanics. I came back to the game after getting it a long time ago, but everything is still amazing. As for the graphics, sound and etc, it's all fine."
76561198049194645,Not Recommended,266510,16653156,"Posted: 23 June, 2015",all,Sonic Shoe[NGC],"this game is the definition of wasted potential. sure it's fun for the first couple hours. you'll breeze past the first half of the content in about 2-4 hours, but once you get about two thirds of the way through, the game takes a massive difficulty spike. the game starts reusing old boss fights, but they use them along side other groups of enemies, in addition to the ones that that the boss comes bundled with. see every time you fight a boss they summon 2-4 enemies to fight along side them at the start of the battle. it's impossible to fight *just* a boss. this wouldn't be a huge problem, except that in addition to fighting the bosses again, with more enemies this time, the bosses and their mooks are all powered up, they have more health, and more (and more powerful) moves. now all of theses things combine would be challenging, but managable if not for one major flaw: the arenas in which you fight get smaller and smaller as the game progresses. at the start of the game you fight 1 boss and about 2-3 enemies in a REALLY big arena making it possible to divide and conquer, and avoid attacks. by the end of the game, you can wind up facing about 10+ enemies including 2 bosses in an arena about a quarter of the size in which you found the original boss encounter. oh by the way the second to last boss is in one of the smallest arenas in the game, spawns with 4 ranged units with shields, has undblockable attacks, can block attacks himself, AAAANNNNNDDDDD his minions can't be killed until AFTER you kill the boss. oh and his unkillable minions (seemingly intentionally) position themselves between you and the big guy, and even when they aren't in your way, sometimes your character just seems to ignore him. the autoaim on your attacks seem to prioritize his unkillable minions for some reason, and even when he's alone, it will just ignore him entirely.all of this only outlines the problems with the combat encounters. most of the other encouters in the game are strictly luck based, and rely entirely on you winning a 25% roll, or you lose most of your equipment/health/provisions.all I can say is, I hope the devs look at this game, figure out all the stupid ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t they got wrong, and make an awesome sequel, because if not for its compeletly unforgivable, unignorable, experience ruining flaws, this game would be in the running for the greatest game I've ever played. that said, don't buy it. it's not worth you money because you'll never be able to actually beat it without getting incredibly lucky and I mean that literally, no matter how well you play, no matter how clever you are, most of the game comes down to situations where you have a 75-100% chanace of immediately dying a completely unvoidable death.--------------------------------------------------------------------Response to developer's comment:the graveyard deals a ton of damage (I think I lost like 45 health most of it in max health reduction) to you if you are cursed, and you are always cursed passed the first wing if I'm not mistaken (100% chance for a negative, potentially run ruinning outcome especially on levels like the king of scales where you lose health/food/gold randomly and can easily starve). also the treasure chest goes from being a nearly garunteed free gain to a nearly garunteed chance to lose most of your health to gas and a mimick (again, often in permanent health reduction). those are the ones that come to mind right now, but I know there are others.basically some cards like the graveyard have a garunteed negative outcome if you don't know what they do ahead of time and put them in your deck at the wrong time, and others go from being really good during the early stages of the game to just being a death sentence later like treasure chest.now don't get me wrong, I don't mind that the cards change as the game progresses, I mind that they change completely *without any warning.* if the game told you ahead of time that certain encounters where going to get more difficult that would be one thing, but when an important part of my strategy for getting a good run going with decent gear arbitrarily decides to kill me with out warning... that's when I get a bit upset.my reccomendation would be to put a level indicator on encouters similar to the monster cards to warn you ""hey this has a much bigger chance to go south, you sure you still want it in your deck?"" but instead you have to learn that it can screw over your entire run by having it screw over your entire run, and that really sucks.all that said, I love the ideas you guys put into the game, it's really REALLY cool, it's just that the luck vs. skill could use a little bit of balancing more towards skill --or at least informed deck building-- and the arenas just get way to small and crowded to fight in later on and both those things really ruin an otherwise ingenious game.oh and btw, I hate playing games on easy mode x)"
