,Recommended,266510,14562865,"Posted: 20 February, 2015",all,AlphaDiode ©,"Where did this mystery of a game come from? Out of nowhere it seems. I was intrigued when I saw the store page and watched some videos via Steam broadcasting. There's nothing quite like it. At its core its a card game where you start immediately in some mysterious location, at a very creepy gaming table and even more mysterious dealer. He deals encounter cards which form your ""playing board"".You move your token around the board uncovering the cards and your story or ""fate"" unfolds as the title implies. The encounter cards vary from quests, travelers, monsters, combat, shops, weapons, artifacts, blessings, curses, mazes and all sorts of other things (good and bad) too numerous to mention. Many of the cards offer you a choice which you must consider carefully as it will affect the outcome of the game. Your goal is to defeat boss encounters and move your way up to more challenging decks and bosses. All the while the dealer talking and commentating on the state of the game. The voice acting is superb. A very well done and hypnotizing soundtrack really sets the mood and makes you feel like your taking place in something epic.As you play you unlock more cards which then go into your deck and the dealer's deck both of which you can customize within the game rules. This makes the game even more interesting and varied as you go and replay again. In the end though each play session is procedurally generated as he deals the cards, adding some of his own and making each play through unique. Will you live or die? What waits for you at the end of the card chain? You'll just have to play to find out.Your three primary resources are health, gold and food, all of which are necessary to proceed. Along the way you'll need to (hopefully) acquire enough and manage/spend them all wisely or you might find yourself rich and starving, or poor and overfed with not enough gear to stay alive in combat. It's your choice but balance seems to work the best.The combat takes place in 3D top down arenas played Diablo style. It's fast paced, dramatic, very tense and requires quick reflexes. Here you can use artifacts, special weapon powers and abilities if you're fortunate enough to have found them to help you in your fight. If not then well.....good luck.Table graphics are excellent. The card art is average. The fighting arena graphics won't win any awards but are decent enough to get the job done. It doesn't matter though because the gameplay trumps everything else and that's clearly where the devs put most of their efforts. With the exception of the final level difficulty which is miserably hard, the game is near perfect.It's risky pushing the boundaries of stale genres and the litany of ""card"" games that flood the store. This game succeeds in doing so on so many levels. Highly recommended if you're looking for something different."
76561197994364064,Recommended,266510,23159741,"Posted: 23 May, 2016",all,leftlobe!?,Cool deck building game. Lots of replay value as gaining cards and going through dungeons is never really the same twice. Would definitly recommend.
76561197978024377,Recommended,266510,29415208,Posted: 21 January,all,shaseki,"Firstly, I need to enter in my overall bias for the game. It's Australian made, therefore it's freaking awesome!That aside the game delivers a turned based competent along with a live-action platform environment. I'm going to describe both for you.The turned based competent is a card delivery system where prior to going on your adventure you can select your deck of cards for scenario's and then select your deck of cards for equipment (ranging from weapons, sheilds, armour, rings and spells). The higher you rank in your adventuring quest the more cards you can have in your deck.You start your adventure on a 'dungeon crawl' in a turned based environment where food and gold is your life essence to get to the end game/boss. On each move a random card is flipped to tell you a tale or a random scenario that you will need to select your course of action. The course of action may having you flipping on a x4 success or failure card. Failure could result in lost health or food/gold. Getting to traders and selling some of your gear helps you move on.A scenario based could result in an encounter - which then brings you to the live-action platform part of the game, you have your warrior in a rear facing fight controlled by mouse and keyboard (gamepad optional). The card flip will result in the amount of monsters you are engaging and the tier level of monsters. Your fight then has you fighting trying to keep your hit sequence as high as you can to score crits, so it can bea a fast flowing combat.Overall this is a great go to game when you have 15 minutes or 2 hours to spare gaming. End of game will score you 'chips' which give you more cards to play with.There are modes you can play in for difficulty and an endless mode to see how far you can really go too, which is highly enjoyable or at times distarous based on your choices.A great game for the avid casual gamer market.Oh and the dealer has pure sex for a voice :)7.5 / 10"
