76561197964466717,Not Recommended,266510,29510546,Posted: 26 January,all,GeneralChaos,"25% chance to just game over on an ironman style game. Game over, and very very angry.Let me explain.This is a game where many of your decisions are opaque; you have to make so many choices without full information, and without an idea what might go wrong. This is generally a bad design decision, but in Hand of Fate it is a feature. Early on there are simple challenges with simple outcomes. You keep encountering the same things, and discover through trial and error which things are worth attempting, avoiding.The game screws with you a bit. The same card can have different outcomes that are not visible. When you're out of food, there seems to be a bias for gaining food from encounters, even ones you would not expect it from. There are variations of the same encounters too, which keeps the game fresh. These are excellent designs, though not perfect. I've had at least one run where I found 0 food. Which is annoying, but it's a proceedural game. It's bound to happen from time to time.Settling encounters is done three ways: Decisions, chance and combatCombat, which is often difficult depending on circumstance, but largely skill based (though having the right equipment and blessings will make you into an unstoppable monster). It's possible to win almost every fight regardless of what you are fighting, and your circumstances.Decisions, as I have mentioned are largely opaque, until you have encountered a card many times, and seen all the outcomes.And chance is settled by four cards, which are shown to begin with, then shuffled a number of times depending on the difficulty of the check. A 1 shuffle is really slow, and you can follow the cards with your eyes easily, so can more easily pick the success or failures. A 6 shuffle is so fast you are basically choosing at random.BUT, the great success/success/fail/great failure is again opaque. Sometimes less successful checks bring greater boons.And this brings me to where the system starts to have trouble: Sometimes to progress stories you must fail. Narratively, these make sense, but it takes away your agency. You are already making blind decisions. But now you're expected to go for a failure, when the rest of the game has trained you to avoid it?Finally, the situation I found myself in. Play this game of chance with some devils (the fourth in the chain, I believe, and might be the first time I encountered this particular one). Yes/No. Hrm. These guys have cursed me in the past for failing. I can deal with more curses, if it comes to that. See the range of cards. Keep an eye on the great success... shuffleshuffleshuffleshuffleshuffleshuffle. Oh well. Ok. Hm. Pick. Total failure ""At least you got an achievement, (12 fails/total fails in a single session)"". Great, probably going to get two more curses... Auto dead. Game over.So:Opaque choice.One random, skill-free check.Automatic game-over despite all other conditions.Automatic loss, on an effective total random 25% chance.OK. That just happened. Can I play a game, that through no fault of the player, you can simply lose?I could just avoid that card... but I also know that other cards have several variations. This same run I lost 150 gold and an artifact to a card that I thought only had beneficial effects. So yeah. Instant death can be in other places too. It could be on every card, hidden behind a check I have so far never failed before, or a variation I haven't faced.My trust is broken. I cannot play this game anymore."
76561198075008318,Recommended,266510,14553642,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,Ashcarr,"Terrificly executed game. It's a mash up of everything great in video games. When I read that it had Arkham style combat and deck building I immediately thought, ""How in the world would that work? They're not even part of the same genre!"" This game pulls it off and adds a ton a replayability through the use of random board paths.As the game progresses, it becomes brutal. There's a good chance you will die even when everything seems to be going your way. Score some critical successes on a few events and it doesn't look like anything can slow you down? Critical failure. You're now starving and down to 23 health before a pack of 10 Ratmen gang up on you and poison you to death with their lingering acid.It's both oddly satisfying and frustrating at the same time. It's not perfect, but you'll have so much fun starting up another run that you won't even care."
