,Recommended,266510,28989283,Posted: 3 January,all,Seikon,"It is hard to put this game into words that describe it well. It is in some way a deck building / card game, but all fights are conducted as hack&slay 3rd person fights where the moves are a bit similar to the batman games (evade, counter, attack, some special skills). So what happens in a standard round of Hand of Fate?1. I select a story / main quest to play2. I select a preset deck and review it to exchange cards3. Play (the following steps a & b repeat multiple times):3.a. Move your character across a map made of cards which are revealed upon reaching them. These may then trigger sidequests, encounters, shops, traps etc. They come along with stories where you can often choose how to react to an encounter, which gives you different results.3.b. In case you engage in a fight, you go into the battle mode. This is classic hack and slay action with block, dodge, attack.4. You complete the round by beating the final boss (or dying). During 3. you have completed many events that gave you tokens. These unlock future side quests, weapons or other cards to be used in future rounds. So once done, go back to step 2, to make use of your sweet loot!I really enjoy RPGs, good progression systems, deckbuilding and a fresh gamestyle. In my opinion, Hand of Fate combines these mechanisms into an oh so refreshing and satisfying experience that anyone with similar preferences should not miss!"
76561197999871993,Recommended,266510,29008493,Posted: 4 January,all,ddragon625,"Graphics:I was satisfied with the graphics, they fit the theme very well and are easy on the eyes.Gameplay:Incredibly addicting.The adventure-as-a-card-game theme worked beautifully and you get a real sense of progression: 1) In each individual game you build up hoards of equipment/blessings/gold/food as you move from encounter to encounter.  2) In the overarching game you collect new tokens that unlocks new encounters/equipment as you complete the story mode and also as you trudge along in the endless mode.The combat is crisp and controls are reasonably well implemented. There are occassional frustrations with the non-controllable / constantly-chaning camera angles that messes up your combat movements but they are bearable.The game give players a good challenge that ramps up as you move further into the game (especially in endless mode).  The balance is a good one - you'll never feel so overpowered that you get bored. No matter how much equipment / gold / food you accumulate, everything can change in a second with a bad encounter or curse in the late game.  In the beginning, everything's easy and the loot rains down with very forgiving bad encounters. Towards the late-game of endless mode, when you're decked out with all the good equipment and blessings and gold and food, the game really ramps up the consequences such as losing multiple equipments in a single bad encounter, get 10+ curses thrown on you (one for each ring you have and players are generally encouraged to hoard all the different rings they can buy/find because the effects stack), or get thrown in a gladiator pit with no equipment to help you out in the battle (did I mention that the monsters are usually powered up 2-3 times already at this point due to accumulating curses?).Story:No real story to the game, though the backstory (or at least hints of it) of the dealer and game itself can be interesting for a bit as the dealer provides cryptic comments. Each game is a create-your-own adventure that is formed by all the encounters you experience.Replay Value:Extremely high. No two games are alike and it'll take you 30-40+ hours to unlock all the tokens and see all the equipment/encounters that the game has to offer.Other:Hand of Fate and FTL are the two games that really perked my interest in rogue-like games. Their take on genre are different but both are highly effective in that they immerse you into the game, give you a good challenge, and provides a lot of unpredictability / replay value.  Also, the voice acting in this game is quite good as well.Overall:I found the gameplay incredibly addicting and would highly recommend this to fans of RPG, action. or rogue-like genre."
