76561198408671944,Recommended,266510,34552739,Posted: 28 August,all,DevlinBlack666,"Hand Of Fate is like Mad As Hell, extremely underrated and oddly Australian. Yet here I am in the Australian steam store, paying American dollars to play a game that is co-produced by Screen Australia.  Irony writ very large indeed, eh Valve?The ‘Dealer’ or narrator if you prefer looks like the merchant from RE4 except somehow less necrotic, the accent sounds like some Melbourne art student trying their absolute best to not butcher a mixed British-Muslim accent… its somewhere between cringe-worthy and cult.I’ve only really committed about 8 hours to this game, and I’m not entirely bored with it, on the contrary I picked it along with its DLC on sale for roughly $8. Have I gotten my money’s worth? Hell yes. Would I recommend it to friends? Yes.It looks quite cheap and charming seeming to combine a dungeons and dragons style feel with bog standard arkham asylum combat on a budget. Hit detection is a bit iffy though not enough that it becomes a problem.It is a short, quirky and very interesting game from a mechanical and experiential standpoint.  What makes it sometimes fun, sometimes annoying and sometimes hilarious is that no two play throughs are the same. Everything is randomly generated by the deal of the cards.The dealer-narrator-dungeon master like character seems to really enjoy torturing you, offering unique dialogue with every twist of the knife. The problem with every dungeon being procedurally generated is it can go from being too easy to impossibly hard.Replay value is theoretically infinite, doubly so with the first DLC and all of its ‘modifiers’, if you’re really that in love with it. I have every intention of finishing Hand of Fate, though at the same time, its best played in short bursts on a weekend as it feels very short.I know it’s an indie, and its half TCG half arkham knockoff on a budget, but would it have killed the developers to put in a little more voice acting? I don’t play ARPGs to read walls upon walls of text.However, I will give the art direction props for the insane European tarot card style artwork on the dealer’s cards, it looks atmospheric without being needlessly colourful.  It really makes you feel like you’re playing against a real person.A person who, like you, in some strange meta way has become a slave to the game within the game so to speak. There’s a subtle hint of Dorian Gray in the storytelling and the way the Dealer taunts the player at the conclusion of every move is just spectacular.More interesting still, he levels with you and the more of his ‘Champions’ you send to the graveyard the more he seems to hate yet respect you for beating him at his own game. I wonder if there’s a ‘Fight Club’ style plot twist once you defeat his final champion.And did I mention the resource management? You can die in combat, you can die of starvation… god help you if you don’t have enough money to buy food and weapons, then it’s pretty much an instant game over. Tactical, unpredictable and intense.I’ve only finished about 25% of it in 6 hours or so and for those of you who are feeling truly masochistic there’s also an endless mode I dare not touch for fear it could become more addictive then smack. What’s on the cards for you? Try your luck, buy Hand of Fate today!"
,Recommended,266510,26034614,"Posted: 14 October, 2016",all,Coreus Symphonia,"Mixes cards and dungeon exploring to a result that's both satisfying and interesting. Hand of Fate challenges you to chase down 12 bosses before you can challenge the dealer himself.Each boss quest is like a dungeon adventure, where you choose from cards on a table. Whatever is picked is what you'll have to face. These range from random events, to equipment pickups, groups of enemies, travelling salesmen and lots more. For each step you take on the map, you consume one food. As the story progresses these settings may increase and various curses will make your adventures more difficult.The second part of the game is in the combat, where the game switches to a third person action game. Overcome them and you'll move on.All in all it's an enjoyable mix of two different game genres that I cannot recall to have seen before Hand of Fate did it - and it works surprisingly well.Rating: 8/10 - Play it!"
,Recommended,266510,12585989,"Posted: 20 October, 2014",all,emceekhan,"I will not comment on game play, since that has probably been explained a million times over in other reviews and videos. But this I will say:The Dealer is your Narrator, as well as your Savior and your Opponent. He has offered you the chance to play his Game. As the Player, you are in charge of a pawn - a nondescript adventurer. You are given cards upon which the Game is played. You build the pawn's equipment deck, and the story's encounter deck. The Dealer will deal out the cards and lead you on an incredible tale of greed, hubris and honor. Your pawn will face endless, faceless foes as well as specific boss villains. There will be violence, traps, treasure and horror. The Dealer will attempt to entice you to send your pawn into situations most peril for the offer of a few tokens. These tokens unlock more cards, which unlock more adventure and equipment/treasure.And as you defeat each boss villain, the Dealer will put the card into his cabinet, where you will be able to choose the next villain. Defeat a row of villains, gain a special item. But beware, every Game, every card, every victory will add to the complexity and danger that your pawn will face as you struggle to reach and win the final Game. Your pawns will die, but never fear - there are countless pawns waiting for you to guide them.Who is this man in the robe, who created these cards that influence a world, individuals and items? Who are you, Player? Are we Gods who are meant to play with the lives of mortals? Maybe.You'll have play to experience it."
,Recommended,266510,22016888,"Posted: 23 March, 2016",all,CS-,"Hand of Fate is a fantastic blend of Adventure, RNG, rouge-like and card games.I picked this game up recently on sale for a steal and it was worth every cent. The introduction to the game is simple and easy to follow allowing you to pick up the game quickly and play at your own pace.As you play the game you step from card to card in stages and deal with a number of random events including; battles, moral choices, ethical choices, gambling, quests and visiting shops while progressing through the stage towards the goal of a boss fight. The main story consists of 12 stages each with a boss of its own. All heading towards a final 13th stage that you will not be prepared for the first time. Around about the time you defeat the 4th boss you will unlock a game mode called ""endless"".Endless mode is never ending stages progressively getting harder until you can go no further. I suppose the goal is around stage 30 as this is the achievement awarding level. I personally was never able to beat my record of stage 26. It gets seriously rough. The addition of ""endless"" mode allows you to unlock more cards/ rewards as you complete each cards requirement which can then be used in both story mode and endless.A great addition to the game is the ability to edit the ""world"" or ""level"" by using the deck builder which is available basically at the start of the game. Once you have an idea for the game, the events and items you have preference for you are able to open the deck builder before a main story level and adjust it to your specific liking. The game does offer an auto recommended deck which is fine but once you hit that final 13th level you will most likely need to adjust the deck to your specific play and equipment style.Overall I had a great time with this game, an interesting story, great narration/ music and a play style that was addictive, punishing and rewarding. If this sounds even remotely interesting to you I would suggest you pick it up and give it a try. I loved my time spent on Hand of Fate and I couldn't recommend it enough."
