76561198010038219,Recommended,266510,11155207,"Posted: 9 July, 2014",all,Unicorn Steve,"Early Access - Things are subject to change!REALLY interesting twist on rogue-lite genre that seems to be popular now with stuff like Magicite, Binding of Isaac (and Rebirth around the corner) and Nuclear Throne.Hand of Fate mixes deckbuilding with 3rd person hack and slash combat and roguelite-elements. It still is kind of barebones and kinda unresponsive, but that's early access for you. As a game It really hooked me and I did really enjoy playing this. Deckbuilding is kind of stale until you actually get more cards by beating bosses and succeeding in events.Fighting feels good and meaty and slow-mo-last-hit -effect feels amazing! Still, it isn't really too complex and mostly just spamming X to do damage, in my honest opinion the combat doesn't flow too well having quite long animations and a split-second ""stop-period"" after them if there are no enemies nearby, this makes you really vulnerable, especially if you do not have weapon with counter attacking-modifier and can cause you take lots of unnessecary damage.My biggest gripe about the game is the random element. I see what they're trying to do as drawing cards from deck for random outcome really is the games namesake, but especially early on if you draw an event that really hurts you (takes away lots of your food or health) or do not draw any weapon/armor cards at all can get REALLY frustrating. One could argue that it brings challange to game, but honestly, if how well you're doing is dependant on just pure dumb luck, it really doesn't feel good.That being said, I really don't know how that could be fixed without seriously hurting the games premise and after you beat first three bosses that is negated by little bit, but that can take way long depending on your luck, sooo-- yeah.Overall, I have high hopes about this game, I did enjoy playing it and will return to it when I have more time!"
,Recommended,266510,11148729,"Posted: 9 July, 2014",all,krown,"I'm not much of a reviewer, let alone one for passing on my opinion of games onto others (since it's highly subjective).However, this game is so original & unique its compels me to do so. In an industry that has become highly itterative, Hand of Fate combines tried and true fighting game mechanics with a rogue-lite/dungeon-crawler and blends it into an original package with ""trading"" card game mechanics.The combat is a cross between Batman: Arkham City and Witcher 2. It has the style of combat from Arkham (different enemies do different attacks, organizing which enemies to eliminate first, counter system) but it has the pace of Witcher, in that it is quite slow and you cannot constantly spam the counter button, but instead must really time your attacks and counters. In addition, in this game you are not invincible, each strike landed on you will take away 5-10 health and your health persists for the entire dungeon (you get +5 health regen per ""turn""). this is where my comparison to witcher makes more sense, this isnt a pure action game like Arkham, instead you must really plan the weapons and armor you take into combat, and you must manage your resources, if you run out of resources (-1 per turn) you enter starvation where you lose 10hp per turn. There is also an interesting mechanic where the instances that the game transports you to, is filled with traps that can harm you and your opponents. It a nice little touch that adds to the difficulty.As for the card game element of the game, its not like your traditional TCG like scrolls or Hearthstone, instead the cards you acquire are used to create the dungeon that you will traverse to reach the final boss, you can make an ""easy"" dungeon in some sense of the word, but that will yield very little buffs when you face the dungeon boss. Also, that strategy will limit the amount of gold you get and the Holy card buffs you receive that carryover from dungeon to dungeon.So far I've been raving about the game, but there are some grievances, mostly it comes down the combat. So far the combat is great, but this game essentially revolves around its combat system and for that it has to be flawless. My only gripe is subjective, in that it doesnt quite feel as ""tigh/responsive"" as I would prefer. In leans more towards the witcher style of combat, which is not a bad thing to say; the game just needs some polish. The devs needs to reduce the delay between pressing a button and it registering in the game. Also, at times, the enemies (usually bosses) will have canned animations that they must complete which prevents you from attacking them. Ie, they will continue slashing and NOT take damage from you while they are finishing the animation. That and the fact that the counter attack isnt always responsive does take away from the combat experience. Lastly, the camera is kind of janky and to my knowledge you cannot control it, which can be very annoying at times. However, the game is in early access, so I will give the benefit of the doubt to the devs in that they will sort these things out.Like I said, im not a ""professional"" reviewer, but the game is so unique that it deserves some attention. At the least, check out some lets plays on youtube.  Question is, is it worth it? for me, yes, at the $25 price range, even in the early access state, you can get a lot of enjoyment out of it. However, as a wise consumer, its always best to wait until the official release, but if you are a fan of the genres it combines or have some disposable cash to spend on steam, give it a shot.TLDR: Action game mixed with a rogue-lite dungeon crawler and some card-game elements. Combat is a mix of Batman: arkham asylum and Witcher 2, leaning more towards Witcher. The game is actually pretty challenging, its not a superhero simulator like Batman or even Assassins Creed where you just counter continuously.If devs are reading this, find a way to add MP/CO-OP, perhaps take turns being the ""dungeon master"", the game has soooo much potential."
