,Recommended,266510,31842424,Posted: 19 May,all,drAgunov,"TLDR; cute, cheap single-player adventure cardgame with rewards that evolve your deck. Nice amount of adventure cards and fun gameplay, for casual and layed back gaming. No stress or pressure, lots of fun! Don't buy if you want high speed action, explosive graphics or multiplayer Hearthstone like tactical/pay-to-win/frustrating action.9/10I love this game. Played it a lot. You're meeting a cardplayer for a mysterious reason, somehow you are forced to keep playing the game. The deck develops as you complete cards, giving more adventurecards (as a story that continues) or useful equipable items. You deal with 12 bosses, that will each appear at the end of a path of individual adventure cards that have to be encountered before the boss can be reached. A new deck can be selected and built before each boss, and changed in between attempts.The game is extremely casual. Low consequences, many rewards, nice adventures. For layed back play before going to bed and for players who enjoy an adventure without being drowned in reading that adventure, but just want to play it.Pro's:-Nice role-playing mechanic. Easy to be absorbed into the story.-Many (unknown) items to collect and a high variety of story cards make the early and mid part of the game fun!-Dying has no consequence other than a restart of the level, so the game is not ""hard"" or frustrating in that sense.-Rewards from completed adventure cards are also awarded when dying. So when the levels get hard, you still get rewards and are progressing in deckbuilding. Which adds to the casual factor of the game.-Narrator is fun, not very repetitive (i.m.o.)-I really enjoy the little metal coins that award new cards or items as you complete a cards adventure. Cool feature!-Low specs alow for playing on relatively simple laptops and computers.-Love the heap of artwork.Con's:-Game can rely on chance for progress, which can be slightly frustrating at times.-Combat is quite cluncky and simplistic. (although real-time combat in such a game gives a nice depth and adds to player activity, compared to just drawing cards, and rolling dice.)-Equipment could be more creative and extensive. Current situation: 1 weapon, shield, chest, helmet, gloves,  (wear multiple rings/trinkets, more gear slots like shoulder/belt/pants or add features like tattoos with small boost effects, add weapon upgrades upon completing adventures, add feature of combining two gloves: mainhand glove/shieldhand glove.)-No character creation. You are a random dude...I really love this game. The con's are forgivable and I'm looking forward to Hand of Fate 2, which is in the making. But I hope to finish this version before that.Let me know if you think I forgot something in my review that i should add."
,Recommended,266510,16582147,"Posted: 21 June, 2015",all,Terminally Nerdy | CBSA82,"I find myself moving down this dusty corridor, dodging flame traps and a spike ceiling trying to crush me.  I catch my breath for a moment, roll past some arrow traps, and grab a chest!And my reward is some cards.  And the man across the table from me makes some cryptic statements about my past, or the history of that card, or something vague and menacing.This is the sort of thing that happens in this game, and its amazing.Hand of Fate can be best described as a Deck Building Action RPG hybrid.  You are a nameless someone, who has decided to play a game of life and death against a mysterious Dealer.  Your goal is to defeat the 12 members of the Dealers Card Court.  Your weapons, tools, and even dungeons are the very cards being used in the game.I have not played for very long as I don't want to spoil the game for when I do a video playthrough of it, but suffice to say what I have played has my interest piqued.  I want to know who I am, where I came from, how I got to this place, and why this Dealer is such a snarky ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥.Recently, the devs put out a Free content expansion, which adds another little mini story to the game.The basic gameplay is that you have a deck of cards that you have built.  Well 2 actually: Equipment and Encounters.  The dealer then spices things up by adding cards to them, cards you have no knowledge of.  He then lays out a dungeon face down on the table, made up of cards.  You then move a token around from card to card, and experience a variety of things.  One card might be an Ambush of Skeletons, another might be meeting an Elf Lass, another might be a dangerous ravine, or a trap room.In the case of combat, or trap rooms, the game switches to an Action RPG setup, using a combat system very similar to the new Batman Arkham games.  You can dodge, roll, attack, and eventually should you find the gear cast spells or special powers.  One power I had early on let me cause all my attacks to generate cash on the ground that I could pick up.The devs have said the main campaign takes about 12 hours to get through, so about an hour per court member.  There is also Endless mode, which is of course Endless.Hopefully more content updates come down the pipe as I can see myself playing this for quite a while."
