76561198031749387,Recommended,266510,16828239,"Posted: 1 July, 2015",all,silversnake7,"""Hand of Fate"" could have been a total mess, a hybrid of a collectible card, board, choice, hack & slash, rouge-like and various other game elements, with an ""opponent"" who is sitting opposite of a table to you and just insults you most of the time.But somehow, it isn't a mess, but all it's aspects are put together in such a smart way, that it makes for an interesting, engaging, fun and awesome game to play.At the core of the game is a ""deck of cards"", packed with various encounters, events, vendors, monsters and equipment. Here a big part of it already starts, because as you progress through the game, you mostly become responsible for which cards are in the deck and you form your own adventure. Though, at the same time, the role of your ""opponent"", the dealer, becomes obvious soon, when he includes some cards himself into the deck and deals the cards to you, taunting you, looking down on you when you fail and showing his spite on your success.This theme and the dynamic presented by the only one who actually gets some character, which is the dealer, already creates an intriguing setup.Then, when the cards are dealt, you have to continue over a kind of ""board"" made of the encounters, which are usually revealed as you step on each card. Sometimes something mandatory happens, but most of the time a choice will follow, how you want to deal with the encounter and as you progress through the game, you will learn about the consequences of those decisions. And sometimes, through the encounters, you will have to play in a completely different setting, where a lot of the actual action and fighting happens, which requires your skill to overcome those chellenges, though sometimes it feels somewhat unprecise.And like that you progress through the game, board by board, gaining new cards, events, equipment, but also new monsters and other chellenges.And so the weird mix turns into this game, which you can influence in a lot of ways, the way you want to play, with which cards and how to act upon encounters, spiced with some chance and skill, delivered through an awesome theme, underlined with some story, which just makes it awesome."
