,Recommended,266510,35492677,Posted: 5 October,all,wyulf,"firstly, if you are expecting a CCG the likes of magic the gathering or whatnots, then perhaps you should temper your expectations again, or just look for a different game.hand of fate is first and foremost, more of a rogue-like rpg, and the cards simply become gameplay elements, dictating your gear, and the story. if you've played games like card crawl on mobile devices before, you'd have an idea of how it's like.the fun part about hand of fate however, is very much tied to the way you configure your deck itself. you therefore dictate what kind of random items could appear in your game, what kind of encounters you'd face, etc. and of course, the dealer himself (like a game master in pen and paper rpgs), do inject some random elements of his own into your deck. all this put together, would amount to your single session in the game. facing different foes, picking up different loot, and going through different tales. as there's tons of different cards available for you to pick from (and more as you unlock them), it gives the game a pretty decent replayability.while luck does play a major factor in how your game progresses sometimes, it does get easier as you accumulate more gold, better gear, and some blessings. there's also the matter of balancing your health, with your gold, and your food too, all of which could potentially lead to your demise at any given moment, depending on the scenarios you'll face. some challenges can be truly rewarding, and just as easily it could be fatally punishing. but i suppose like most rogue-like games, it's something you get used to after a while, for better or for worse.all in all, it's a pretty interesting concept, and an overall fun game that has lots of possibilities, and thus a lot of replayability. looking forward to the sequel, to see what improvements the developers have added."
