76561198005271335,Recommended,266510,16287015,"Posted: 9 June, 2015",all,Pale Dolphin,"TL;DR:Excellent visualization of what's happening in your head, when you play board-game IRLWe all love board-games, don't we? The only problem with them is that there's too much left for the imagination. If only there'd be a game with board-game rules and visualization of, say, Diablo III or Torchlight, or something similar... If you ever had a thought like that (and I know that I did), you're welcome to buy Hand of Fate as soon as you'll finish reading this review.Hand of Fateis a game that's very simple to play, yet very complex to explain: basically, it's a card game, where you move your token from card to card, encounter monsters, treasures and various obstacles. At the end of each scenario, you fight a boss. Though, the complex thing is that when you encounter an enemy, the game turns in something or an action-RPG with you controlling your hero, using skills and items to actually fight your enemies in real time.Graphics are good, I did enjoy both hacking and slashing, and browsing through on-board adventures (not all of the cards include you teleporting to the arena and fighting monsters, obviously enough). The dealer is a nifty masked dude with creepy yet charismatic voice (you might expect a new announcer with it in Dota 2, though), which follows his own rules and easily admits defeat if you slay his henchmen.As you progress through the storyline, you encounter more powerful enemies and gather a stronger loot. Every scenario is unique, thanks to the randomizer -- you can even call these levels procedurally generated, rogue-like style: every time you start over, both scenario decks (yours and dealer's) are shuffled, and you're getting a new adventure each time you start over.- - - - - - - - - - - - - - -I'd strongly recommend this game to all of the RPG fans out there -- it's a breath of refreshing air on the modern RPG scene, really. If you're not into RPG, you might want to check the game out anyway -- it's well-done and interesting to play overall.Rating:8.9 out of 10.0"
76561197987582315,Recommended,266510,17260170,"Posted: 27 July, 2015",all,RENATO ARAGORN,"I'm going out of my way of not really bothering about reviewing games just to say this:-If you don't likeany the multiple sub-genres involved in this game (deck-building, RPG, old-school tabletop, Rogue-like, Arkhan-like combat) just don't bother giving bad reviews, you won't get the message the game is trying to deliver (it could change your mind on those, hardly though);-If you're new tothose genres, buy it and play with an open mind, don't give quick judgment and the game will show its beauty to you (don't just give up after a few plays);-If you, like myself,enjoymost to all of the aspects of those genres, buy and play it, you'll surprise yourself with a richly complex and mysterious story inside this very much balanced (don't let the bad reviews get in your head) tabletop inspired (some luck involved, sometimes, andnotunfair) and build your own adventure RPG. The combat element is tough, but satisfactory and rewarding, it's not 100% as perfect as some AAA titles but it does a good job and that's enough to have a good experience with the combat part. This is an indie game, so don't expect a perfectly polished game in all aspects, the Devs (who are such great guys and responsive towards the community) are constantly polishing and releasing patches (and DLCs) to fix and improve the game experience, so it just gets better and better.TL:DR version- Don't like the genres? Don't bother (but it would be nice of you if you bought it to help the indie community C: );- Aren't familiarized with the genres? Try it for yourself (truly do, you won't regret it) and don't let bad reviews get to you;-Like those genres?YOU WILL ♥♥♥♥ING LOVE THIS PIECE OF ART CALLEDHAND OF FATE.(sorry if my english is not 100% ^^')."
,Recommended,266510,16688395,"Posted: 24 June, 2015",all,hkennyrules101,"Pros:+ Roguelike collectible card game dungeon delver brawler roleplaying game+ The dealer's narration is spot-on and immersive; some of the best voice-acting I've heard+ Graphics and ambient sounds are amazingly detailed+ Customizable decks allow you to play like you want+ Fun side-adventures that have unexpected consequences+ Collecting cards through gameplay allows for deeper and varied customization of your deck to fit whatever is needed+ Manages to stay fun, fresh and challenging the whole way through+ Enemies grow stronger with you, challenges get harder, random chance gets stacked against you... it's great+ Rewards skill while still utilizing luck of the draw+ Overall polished final product - and it shows+ I have never felt this conflicted about beating a final boss+ Developers are invested and involved with the community; are releasing more new content to continue spicing up the gameCons:- Typical repetitiveness that comes with any roguelike game (Mr. Lionel, hello, give me my shield please and I'll be on my way)- Typical aggravation associated with chance-only games (that treasure chest cost me half my health with nothing to show for it)Overall:This is a game that seems strange at first, but then after the first game, I realized I was playing something inspired.  You make your deck, then the dealer adds his own cards to it.  These cards make up the ""dungeon"" and are placed face down (mostly) randomly.  You move your avatar from one card to the next to explore each dungeon, turning the cards face up and resolving their events or encounters as you go along.  Maybe it's a shop, maybe it's an ambush, maybe it's an event where you get lost in the swamp, or goblins steal your equipment and you have to kill them before they escape.The variety and depth is impressive.  Some events rely on skill (beating down goblins who just stole all your weapons, for example), while others rely solely on chance/luck of the draw (picking from 3 success cards and 1 failure card to climb safely down into a ravine, for example).  As the game goes on, it introduces more and more facets, all of which give another layer of chance and strategy.  Combat takes place like the Batman: Arkham Whatever games, where you just smack enemies until they fall over and counter when it tells you to, but it's still fun, and the enemies provide enough challenges to keep from being boring/easy.Bottom Line:Absolute recommend.  This is one of those rare times where a game tries to do a little of everything, and manages to succeed at it fantastically."
