,Not Recommended,266510,17075088,"Posted: 16 July, 2015",all,Rhapsody,"I'll start by saying that I want to love this game. The atmosphere is incredible, the pretense for the story delivered through a card based roguelike dungeon is genius in how it capitalises on the strengths of both card games and roguelikes. Even the ambitious combat scheme is generally pretty engaging (if flawed in a few small ways). I adore a lot of what the game is doing. That said, I can't recommend it in its current state.I originally wanted to say that the game is too difficult, but that's not true. The game is outright unfair. I'd be fine with the game being difficult, because difficulty implies a requirement for careful application of thought and skill. This is not what this game offers. Especially nearer towards the end of the game, there are an incredible amount of cards the dealer plays that may as well read ""Player loses game"". For an example, in the final encounter I'd unlocked before giving up, the deck was stacked with entirely uncounterable cards that reduce maximum life by 50%. It wasn't uncommon for my health bar to consist of a maximum single hit point by the third floor, if I was lucky enough to make it that far.I've read on the Steam forums that as of the 2nd of July a rebalance patch has been planned, but with no current ETA I cannot recommend buying this game unless you are a) the proud owner of a 16 leaf clover or b) a supreme masochist."
,Recommended,266510,16512753,"Posted: 18 June, 2015",all,A Stupid Baby,"Fun game so far. Not finished but:Combat might or might not get deeper than it is - counter/reflect projectiles, dodge roll, stun, and combo multipliers.In many encounters the difficulty seems to be mainly from managing both the actual enemies and the arena itself which can be laden down with traps. Even at the start I find it taxing to manage both, but the game doesn't seem to expect you to be able to come out unscathed. The other part of the difficulty is managing resources as you move through grid dungeons.The story itself is deliberately vague so far, it fits the setting and the delivery from the deckmaster really sells it. The game might be hinting at a deeper story involving the character's past, or it might just be dressing for the nature of the game, it's hard to tell. I'd condiser it a bonus if there's a payoff, but what's already here definitely nails the atmosphere.I'd say the atmosphere is definitely the game's strong suit, and the developers did a really good job with the little details such as using expanding lighting on load, sound effects for things like the opening of the token bowl and dropping of items. The game also knows its exact limits in terms of graphics and animation, and utilizes those things very well.If I have a complaint so far it's mainly just that the use of the game world load for merchant visits is a little bit pointless, though the location and appearance of the shop does change with respect to what kind of shop it is and (I'm guessing) what kind of dungeon you are running.All in all an excellent game especially at the sale price."
