76561198001192813,Recommended,266510,18483252,"Posted: 15 October, 2015",all,McFly,"Hand of Fate is  a strangely addicting mix of dungeon crawler, rpg and card collecting games. The game plays like a Roguelike with all encounters and items being randomly placed while the combat is reminiscent of simpler RPG games with a plethora of weapons, items and spells to combat your enemies. You can only encounter about 10% of the cards at first while you play to earn more, both increasing your chance at good loot on your next journey AND often making the game harder by adding more special encounters.In short,GOOD:- Combat can be pretty hard at the start, but feels very good to get better at.- Nice variation of monsters, bosses and other enemies. You can't have an RPG without cool enemies!- The Dealer is an interesting character and serves to make the game feel really alive.- Feels great with a 360 controller- Graphics and loading times are pretty good although it doesn't seem very optimised, which could result in framrate loss depending on your computer.- Enough originality to make you want to unlock more and more cards to see what more the game has to offer.- Addictive and can be played in short bursts AND long runs depending on how you like to play.- The studio guarantees more content for this game, so that means lot's of more stuff to explore in the future.NOT SO GOOD:- You miss half your combat moves at the start of the game, you can't even block. It feels good to unlock more stuff, but I remember really hating the first part of the game where I could only dodge all the time. This can make you put the game down before you even really start.- As it's basically a Dungeon Crawler the randomness factor can really mess you up sometimes. I guarantee you that you will have a run going great only to be ruined by an encounter card you couldn't possibly beat with your current equipment/health/whatever.- The Succes-Failure card system. On MANY encounters you're supposed to watch how he shuffles to choose the correct card, but it's basically impossible 80% of the time either because of shuffle speed is way too fast or because all the cards are layered over each other in a way you can't follow them. Feel a little too unfair.- Story mode might just be a bit too unfair, with luck kinda winning the game for you. Don't expect to kill the King of Scales without any stunning weapons. If the game doesn't give you any even after succesfully completing all encounters, then you're simply boned and ahve to start all over again.- No in-depth options to try and optimise some of the graphic problems this game has.Randomness aside the game actually has a pretty intruiging overarching story and the Dealer is a well-acted, expressive and likable character that gives the game most of it's tone. All in all I'm quite happy about my purchase. I'm sincerely hoping for some more content in the future which could hopefully also fix some of the more broken problems with the game.NEVERMIND DISREGARD ALL THAT YOU JUST GOT A +40 CURSE CARD INSTADIE ENJOY THE GAME.^^ the reason why I quit playing ^^"
76561197971411710,Recommended,266510,21214805,"Posted: 14 February, 2016",all,Inconmon,"Clever game. Highly suggest acquiring and playing it.It's difficult to describe -- you follow the game as if you'd be playing a tabletop RPG using cards for encounters, while the fights are classic 3rd person view battles in 3D. It includes inventory management (scaling your character) and resource management (health, food, gold). There some cards which represent skill check - pick one of four face-down cards to see the outcome (success or fail) -- it may appear like luck, but you can actually trace the cards while they are being shuffled.Also manages to do a decent amount of story telling in this odd format.9/10 would draw again"
