,Recommended,266510,17786092,"Posted: 29 August, 2015",all,Tynon_2112,"Aw yeah son! If you don't buy this while it's 50% off... well... go home, you're drunk and/or just bad.HESITANT recommendation; Edit at endYou're sitting across from a man with the facial features of an aged Arabian belly-dancer but with the voice of a sophisticated Atheist.He do fancy floating card tricks. You do choice, luck and basic Arkham-esque combat.He do menacing. You do persevering.The Cabinet - the resting place (either dead or in-wait) of Dealer's lieutenants (as it were) - is pretty sizeable with 12 steps towards besting him.You have Gold, which you can use to buy new Equipment (should you luck out and land on a Merchant) and Food, which you expend one of with every move - heal yourself for a certain amount with each meal.The random encounters range from a disgruntled wife who needs you to fetch her drunk husband, to a priest asking for charity, to a wounded soldier asking for aid in hunting down his assailants, to an arena with multiple stages, to a devil you can gamble with, to goblins who attempt to steal your loot, to a trap-filled labyrinth... my ""Deck Progress"" bar isn't a third of the way filled.The combat is very simple but also quite satisfying; though it mimicks the Batman games, it isn't quite as refined or fast-paced. On controller: X to attack, A to dodge-roll, B to stun (shield-bash), Y to parry (only with a shield) - LB for weapon ability, RB for Artefact.Your priority is always to get a shield. I had good luck consecutively in obtaining one from the goblin dressed as a man (""Mister Lionel""?); ask him what he wants: Why to help you my boy! Here's a shield!Once you have a shield, you will get the... iconic (and epic and emotional and cinematic and *buzz-word*) prompts above your head when an attack is about to connect. Best not to button-mash, though HoF is much more flexible in this regard than Arkham is.The majority of the game is in playing across from the Dealer; the combat sequences never last as long as they should.My hope for the game:More extra Cards (read ""Decks"") added to the game than I could hope to go through.A mode released later down the line that would allow more of a focus on the third-person action. Maybe not a full campaign, but just the most basic of stringing together the different arenas, with the ability to use any equipment you've previously unlocked, to versus any creature you've previously fought: The most extended Training mode / wave-based survival thing ever... *faints from awesomeness*The Dealer could be giving voice-overs every now and then, either playing the role of Dungeon Master (more... impactfully(?)) or giving exposition on his past (if it's not further explained later in the game)... so... I guess, yeah, another campaign...Regarding the game as is, the only faults I have:The highlighted card isn't always the next face-down one; is the one you just left more often than I'd like. Of course, rage needs to be accounted for in a game ("")so based on luck(""); in such moments, I'll just spam A to get to the next card, only to exacerbate my anger by inadvertently wasting one (actually two) Food.The Succeed or Fail challenges; four or five cards shown you, turned face-down, shuffled into one deck (one or two times) in such a way that you can hardly discern. It can easily be argued that we're given a better chance at picking a good card than would be given us IRL, but, with the way this mechanic is presented, I was hoping for more of a ""Find the ball in one of these cups,"" something feasibly able to be beaten (as the Dealer admits that he ("")doesn't cheat("")).There is an Endless Mode in which you have a better chance of unlocking more cards to put into your decks for the Campaings. Upon selecting your target (one of those twelve lieutenants), you can then build your deck. New cards have unknown effects until drawn in the game, so you've several playthroughs ahead of you, aimed at simply identifying all the cards, for to build the best deck for your golden runs.I absolutely recommend this game and have little doubt it's worth full price. My one bit of hesitation (as applied to all games that aren't open-world sandboxes (i.e. Just Cause 2)) is in how much repetition there is in the text events, in the limited pool of cards and arenas.EDIT: With (I assume) the game being completely finished (since the sequel is soon to drop), I must say that my absolute recommendation is strained now. SO many of the new cards are extremely archaic in the how you must go about besting them. When I wrote this review, the game was much more reliant on skill, though of course luck(/your perception) was almost as big a part; now, without the aid of walkthroughs, the task of completely beating the game is a ridiculously daunting task. One example of this is when you get lost in the desert and must pick from the four cardinal directions at least four seperate times, in the hope of finding what you're after. Another card actually necessitates that you Fail the first check and Succeed the second. At least five cards seem to be designed solely with the Iron Hunger player character in mind, going so far as to have no (good) effect on ANY other player character that lands on those cards. I still have so much love for the game but there is no denying that the amount of ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t present herein is something to beware of. I don't really enjoy my time while playing any more but am compelled to - progress is a stupid grind, strategy is up to fate, even if you are able to keep up with the shuffles and pick the ""right"" card each time, there is no telling if that will actually be correct according to the devs apparent ""♥♥♥♥-you-lol"" mentality (it would be fun, if the game wasn't such a chore to play in situations where you are doing well and two bad hands can kill you) and so much of the game actually plays itself. Without the third-person combat which many seem to dislike, I argue the game would have little substance."
