,Recommended,266510,33463196,Posted: 11 July,all,Radene,"Hand of Fate is a game made by an Defiant development, an Australian developer - fitting, because it's essentially a solitaire game that is out to murder you in your sleep.The concept itself is ingenious if simple - deckbuilding meets roguelike. Build your decks and take on them, resolve combat in third person, pray to RNGeesus to unlock more and better cards (or some really terrible ones), and push your way through a court of twisted suits - skulls/skeletons for hearts, plague/ratmen for diamonds, dust/bandits for clubs, and scales/lizardmen for spades. There's also a few unconventional suits that serve as miniboss (or even boss) encounters.The gameplay is simple as well. Your spunky adventurer piece moves space by space through a trail set by cards dealt from your encounter deck by the helpful Dealer. Some of them are resolved through simple multiple choices, some through a game of chance (but if you're paying attention you can often see where the card you want will be, or at least the one you really don't want), and some as mentioned through live combat; or of course a combination thereof.Add resource management into the mix, and the game gets more complex. Usually every move costs a unit of food, and as long as you have any of that you'll also heal damage slowly as you move; but run out of food and each move will bring you closer to the cold embrace of death. Naturally, you're going to have a speed date with the Reaper if you lose all your health, too. You acquire equipment and other bonuses through encounters, or through shops that are sparsely strewn through the paths of cards. That, of course, requires gold which is again acquired mostly through encounters.It starts off easy enough, a few quick and pleasant runs to give you a taste of the game, but the Dealer is a crafty fellow, and on every stage he adds a bit of his own nasty cards into the mix, the deeper you go, the worse they get. He might treat you as a worthy opponent, even in a cordial manner, but remember that he is not your friend.All in all, it's quite an addictive and replayable experience, despite the occasional rather frustrating chance fails or cheap shots from the Dealer. I do recommend anyone who has the patience to learn the game, and, if all else fails, fight cheese with cheese. Because turnabout is fair play and beating a game that abuses its mechanics against you by abusing its mechanics against it is quite rewading."
