,Recommended,266510,20290919,"Posted: 4 January, 2016",all,Papinet,"A very creative game blending several gameplay genres! (Story-telling, table game, 3rd person, ""destiny"") It brings together several very opposite mechanics together in a unique style. If you liked, like I did, the books ""You are the Hero"", you'll enjoy this game for sure. The balance between customizing the potential story, and the way you are completely ""unprepared"" to what can really happen is great. The action sequences aren't revolutionary and really look alike some well-known attack/dodge system seen in other games. In addition to the unique blend of gameplay, the art design and the ambiance are most certainly the key factors making this game shine.Cons:- Action sequence less original.- Slow-pace sequences. (some transitions can be skipped)- The ""I was screwed from the beginning"" feeling.Pros:- Very unique design direction.- Blending of different genres.- Ambiance well-fitted.- Amount of content.Hope you enjoy it as much as I am still doing.Thanks,Maxime Pinet"
,Recommended,266510,19375198,"Posted: 29 November, 2015",all,Kensei,"This is a very unique game and I recommend you play it. However be aware of the fact that it does have a few issues, despite being late after release.For starters some cards don't trigger properly, and you might have to guess the solution yourself. For example a card may require you to pay 5 gold, but the option would be grayed out no matter how much you have. On the other hand, if you have 0 gold, you can pay the price and it will be deducted from 0.Poor card trigger code aside, another issue with the game is the camera. At later levels you will absolutely curse it when traversing traps. What happens is that instead of maintaining a top-down angle, camera is scripted to do whatever the ♥♥♥♥ it wants and provide you with a more ""cinematic"" viewing, even though you know, you're trying not to get stabbed, shot, impaled, skewered, crushed and barbequed.Also be aware of the somewhat poorly designed combat in the game. At later stages flaws become aparent, such as getting stuck between a turret and the boundary collider that prevents you from falling out of the arena. The dodge is not long enough to dodge certain attacks and traps, and not enough time is given for a second evade in order to avoid damage.Still, the game is interesting enough to play. The nagging issues prevent it from being a trully entertaining piece, mostly due to the frustration provided by an assinine camera logic and underdeveloped combat. You may have spent your last 3 hours running around, collecting gear and becomming overpowered, but all it takes is 1 level to screw you over in order to make you lose. This creates the feeling of a cheap loss, something mechanical, instead of punishment for a lack of foresight.Despite the dealer so often repeating how fair the rules are, they aren't entirely upheld when you are pitted against 5 lava giants in a cubicle sized arena that blow themselvs up just for giggles. Also the game deems it unfit to let you collect any gold you have lying around after combat. While a minor problem, it does force you keep someone alive in order to collect the bounties, however the lack of a health bar on enemies makes this task akin to playing the lottery.Other than that HoF provides an interesting perspecting on the roguelike genre and is definitely worth a buy at 50% discount. I recommend the full priced game only for hardcore players or TCG mega fans."
