76561198041995956,Recommended,266510,14631261,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,bahamut66,"Played this game since early access and it's only gotten better upon release.  This is a wonderful blend of deckbuilding, board games, and arena combat.  It features great organic storytelling with individual encounters stringing together a journey towards a big boss that you play in sessions.  The combat is smooth, fluid, and highly skill based.  You are dropped into an arena for combat and you need to fight, break guards, and counter your opponent to kill them before they kill you.  Outside of combat, you make choices and take chances to advance your story and unlock new cards for different encounters.It's a magical experience where you feel immersed in a world even when not fighting.  The game is very heavily RNG based, but I'd say it is more reliant on skill than other rogue-like games.  You can still get screwed by RNG, but you can survive a surprising amount through sheer force of will and skill.Musically, the game is superb, with memorable battle music, suspenseful main themes, and a very peaceful shop and certain encounter music.  The best part though is the narrator, who is equal parts friend and foe, your companion through the game who both tries to kill you, but also encourages and balances your experience.  Every line of dialogue from him is quote worthy and awesome.Graphics are...one of the games few problems.  Card art is great and even the 3d designs are cool, but it's a bit low quality and prone to clipping.  Numerous times I've played the game and monsters or my character will get caught in scenery or the character models will freak out rag doll style at the end of combat.  Most of the time its not game breaking, but it can be annoying.  And there are a few bugs that need to be worked out.  More than once, I've had my music and sound effects fail on me.These are minor annoyances for a highly unique and surprisingly addictive game though.  Highly recommended.  Fair warning though, the final boss is total BS and feels very unfair, so be prepared for a little frustration."
