,Recommended,266510,14922131,"Posted: 16 March, 2015",all,Krevlornswath,"An excellent roguelite based on the idea of choice, chance, and consequence. Many players have commented on the increase in difficulty. This is true. But several people ignore the fact that it's about chance and consequence.One reviewer mentioned a card that makes you lose 66% of your max health. This is true. But you can ignore that completely and just not take the chance. If you do it and succeed though, you get a HUGE reward. There aren't any cards that just exist to kill you. There are many that exist that let you risk death for the prospect of reward, though."
76561198102348030,Recommended,266510,15680339,"Posted: 3 May, 2015",all,Captain Tibbs,"The Arkham Combat System (ACS) is the weakest part of the game and highlighted by some of the relatively small arena spaces and somewhat stiff animations. However, every other mechanic of the game makes up for the ACS.Hand of Fate is an excellent, unique combination of gaming sytems that would best be described as the hidden mechanics of many videogame RPGs brought out and given a life via the cards and their 'choose your own adventure' dealer. The themes and art are great and the narration is fitting and well done. Aside from some personal issues with the ACS, I recommend this to anyone that is a fan of card games and Medieval-style RPGs."
,Recommended,266510,14628227,"Posted: 23 February, 2015",all,this_is_chris,"Hand of Fate is a really fun card game with beat 'em up elements. The game features two modes; Story and Endless. This will mostly be focused on Story, as I've not played Endless yet.The game is fairly simple; the dealer will lie down cards on the table and you will move your piece onto the cards. Sometimes, this is linear, but sometimes it isn't. Some cards will activate things like visiting a shop, encountering baddies to kill, traversing a maze or coming up against a situation where, of 4 cards, you must pick the ""Success"" card in order to win. You will have, at the bottom right, three ""stats"": your health, your food & your gold. Every move consumes 1 food, but you'll restore lost health. Gold is fairly self-explanatory.When you get an encounter card, you are placed onto a small plot of field where you will fight against monsters, ranging from goblins to skeletons, zombies and bandits. While variation is limited, it doesn't pull away from the experience. However, the fighting / combat is rather wonky; borrowing from the Arkham series, you will basically use WASD to move around and left click to attack. You cannot hard target a specific enemy, which can be a bit frustrating, but again, really doesn't affect the game greatly.Situation cards vary, from finding a weapon in a crevasse to saving someone from being swarmed by enemies. Successfully ""winning"" these situations nets you a token from the dealer. At the end, all of your accrued tokens are counted up and you are given specific rewards based on the tokens. For example, I was tasked with defeated a knight that had been overrun by some skeletons. Once I defeated them, he told me I could keep the mace I was given prior to the fight, as his kingdom was flush with them. Once I completed the level, his token rewarded me with 2 Mace cards.You progress through the 'levels' by travsering through the cards, finding that particular level's 'end card' and moving onto the next level. At the end of the final level, you will fight a boss. Defeating the boss gives you more tokens, which unlock things like weapons, armor, encounters and other varying cards.One of the coolest things this game offers is the Deck Builder. On one side, your deck has cards for Equipment; weapons and armor and trinkets. The other side are your encounters, from visiting shops to situations. If the card has a lock icon on it, that means it has a situation / encounter you've yet to face. Drawing & defeating that card will net you another token.Last but not least is the Dealer himself; an elderly mage who speaks to you throughout the game. His dialogue is superb and I found myself actively listening to what he had to say. The first level, I drew a card that had a goblin giving me a shield. The next level, I drew the card again and, in this very dry tone, he said ""I think you purposefully put that card in there just to get an early shield."" (or something to that effect) It's minor, but the fact he recognizes that made me smile.I know my hours played as of writing this is low (think it's barely 2 hours), but honestly - the game is immediately fun. The combat is a bit wonky, but everything else excels so well that I don't mind. It doesn't hurt that the game also looks really good & sounds pretty good, too. I can't wait to jump back into the game and have more fun with it. :)"
76561198082730311,Recommended,266510,15621227,"Posted: 30 April, 2015",all,Rhodes,"I want to warn everyone who wants to have this game !The game starts awesome yet you will stop playing it once you reach 5th or 6th deck (level).The difficulty of the game increases immensely. Cards won't help you. You will die a lot and you will restart the deck which means you are going to kill everything that you killed previously. Then you will find yourself skipping everything (Cards ask you if you want to cross the river or not ? - Do you want the chest ? or not ?. I personally died a lot and started to click NO to every options to reach the boss fight in order to pass the level and have some other new features. Trust me it does not help !I need to be honest. I love the atmosphere, ideas and gameplay yet the game design gets too limited when you move further in this game. You play the same fights over and over. You pick the same cards over and over. Still I liked it yet I recommend you to wait for the sale to buy it ;)"
