76561198033866805,Recommended,266510,20389351,"Posted: 7 January, 2016",all,h0b0king,"Hand of Fate is a good game, the simple brawler mechnics of the combat sequences are fun and challenging enough, like a slightly harder version of the Arkham/Batman games with far fewer variables or moves.  The narrator is amusing, the graphics cartoonish in a lovely way that pops on the screen totally appropriate for a game that is within a game.The basic conciet of the game though is pretty briulliant - the player is playing cards against the enigmatic narrator who is some sort of dyspeptic frog voiced oracle or wizard. He's fun enough and he has new quips for most new cards, but I could I can see a DLC with a different dealer being profoundly satisfying - say a urbane devil, petulant child or defeatist death.  The card came is itself an adventure, with the randomly selected (you can build the decks though - within certian limits) card laid down and most cards offering a garphic of a charming woodblock image, a paragraph and a choice.  most selections lead to a pick and choose mechnic where four cards representing degrees of success and failure are shuffled monty style and the player picks one.  Other cards lead to combat.  In general when the player is successful with a card they gain a token that's convereted to another card at the end of each game.  Thus as one plays more and more choices are added.  It's fun, and for an ""unlock"" method of providing content feels very natural.Despite that praise, I almost gave this gave a thumbs down because even now, long after release (and to the developers' credit the seem to keep adding cards and content) the game seems to suffer from technical issues.  It lags, it slows and it crashes with alarming regularity on my laptop - which while no gaming machine is well above the minimum specs.  This isn't a general set of errors, more a steady degradation of capability culminating in multi minute load times for combat sequences or simply sudden crashes in the combat engine.  Whatever the cause these errors, they make the game frustratingly unplayable - becauase I want to play it and it's a good game.I'm still giving it a positive rating here because when it does work (and sometimes it's fine) it's a very fun, very smart game."
,Recommended,266510,20443699,"Posted: 10 January, 2016",all,Jake Salvage,"I ONLY KIND OF RECOMMEND THIS GAME WITH THESE CAVEATS:I do NOT recommend paying 25 dollars for it (which is the going price as of the writing of this review.)I've put a good 30 hours into it so far, and I think after beating the final challenge, I'll be done with it until there is more DLC or a HoF2. Once you've completed the encounters, there's really only a few variants in Endless mode that are somewhat interesting, but I don't think I'll be playing through them all, as they consist of encounters I've seen a million times.The gameplay consists of a randomly dealt and organized map of cards which you traverse. When you complete encounter cards, you get tokens, which unlock new items, encounters, and more, which pertain to the cards defeated. The difficulty of these encounters ramps up very quickly and sometimes seem impossible with their ridiculous requirements, which bank almost soley on your luck in drawing the right encounters previously.This is a huge problem, as a lot of the encounters rely on luck rather than skill. The bigger problem is, a lot of skill portions rely on how well your luck is at picking success cards in those encounters (if you can't play Four Card Monte and follow the Success cards, you will not enjoy this game). It took me a lot of grinding to finish a lot of the encounter cards, and as of right now, I still have not beaten the main Story mode, because you are restricted by the curses you are given when you enter a level, and the last boss has ridiculously overpowered curses that make the last level about luck rather than challenge.The combat in this game is similar to the Batman Arkham games, which is cool, and very close to as smooth as those games. But the VERY limited enemy selection and TRUE boss battles (not just better versions of main enemies) makes this tedious over time. The selection of weapons gets bigger as you finish more encounters, but as you are given them randomly during play, a perfect loadout is left to chance, which is mostly ok, considering a perfect loadout would make you practically invincible, but not ok when you end up with nothing at the end of a dungeon because of a poorly placed random chance card.I purchased this game when it was on sale for 9.99, and I think at that price, it's worth it. If you are someone who enjoys a challenge, this is a very challenging game, but the challenge is mixed in with a fair amount of true unfairness, which I think sometimes is confused for challenge.Just know that this will be frustrating as all get-out."
