76561197994490550,Recommended,266510,20544262,"Posted: 15 January, 2016",all,Grimvarr,"Hand of fate is a Dungeons & Dragons inspired card game with hack 'n slash combat. As you progress through the game and solve quests, more cards become unlocked for you to bolster your deck with. Your opponent, or Dungeon Master, sits across you and deals you the cards as the game unfolds, offering comments, threats, and wry observations as you play.Combat is fast paced and feels good and different blessings and curses you accrue over the course of the game influence your tactics both in and out of combat. As you solve quests, deal with demons, or help the innocent on your journey, the DM awards you with coins. When you die, and you will die, the coins are shattered and give you new encounters, weapons, armour, and blessings to fill your deck with. But beware, for as you grow in strength, so do your adversaries.Your deck is the permanent feature of the game. The cards you unlock carry over from one game to the next. Each game you play is like a new adventure. In this respect it kind of reminds me of FTL: Faster than Light, although death isn't nearly as certain in Hand of Fate than it was in FTL (unless you play Endless Mode).It's compelling, beautiful, and very more-ish. As every individual game is highly influenced by chance, very few games are similar. There are weapons I have yet to use because I haven't drawn them in a game yet, even though I unlocked them many games before. No game sees you go through your entire deck, so you never quite know what to expect, or when to expect it.TLDR Pro's & Con'sPRO:Great atmosphereRandom factor (no game ever quite the same)Persistent rewardsGood solid combatFeels rewarding (even if you don't win)Multiple questlines that you play through 'simultaniously' over the course of many gamesCON:Random factor (sometimes the deck is just stacked against you)No direct control over your starting equipmentMouse hover-over selection doesn't always work quite right (sticks to first option) so you have to make sure you have the right selection highlighted before making a choiceI highly recommend this game. This is the closest I've seen a PC game come to capturing the feeling of playing an actual table-top card game with someone."
