,Recommended,266510,14544604,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,Rend,"I don't write reviews often, but i started writing this for my friends on facebook and accidently reviewed it.So here is my very positive review.Guys, If you ever wanted a game that supports Australia in the game development industry. I cant stress this enough.GET HAND OF FATE.This game is amazing.Created by Defiant Development, this game mixs a table top card game with a top down action rpg.After the tutorial, you have to edit your deck (or use a reccomended preset) and in doing this you choose what encounters, shops, weapons, armor and enchantments will be randomly drawn throughout the game.These items get reset every game, but you add to the total cards in the deck. Which means you have wider variety to build a play deck with.Each floor consists of face down cards. These are encounters. You have to move your token across these, one after another, down the depths to find the boss at the end of the dungeon.This part is similar to Nethack.Each time you touch a new card, you have to decide how to deal with it.Be it scaling down a cliffside to reach a weapon or an angry mob wanting to steal your food.Resources!In this you have 3 resources.First, obviously, is your health. This is gained each time you move or take a heal action through an encounter. Maximum health can be gained or lost through different successes or failures. Lose all of this and you have lost the game.Second. Food.Food is used to move. Consuming 1 food per movement. There are events in this where you can lose or gain food, sometimes lose all of it too, very harsh as i learned.If your food has fallen to 0 then every movement will cost -10 health.Food is gained through combat, gain cards or shops.Third. Gold.What dungeon crawler would exist without the treasure?Gold is used to shop with, buy off bribes or charity through events.Gold can be stolen from you and you can also gain it through events or combat.Now, this gets better. because you have a full inventory.Head, Armour, Hands, Weapon, Shield, Trinkets.Lots of combos that do lots of things.Some weapons have elemental damage that do extra to different creatures, or less!.This can be found in treasure chests through events, given to you, bought, sold.These items are preset into the deck by the deck builder, but you dont just get them, you need to EARN them in the game.Combat is simple and short, but enjoyable.The dealer will select monster cards (or you do, depending on the event)These monster cards will say things like Four of Skulls or 3 of Dust.The 4 of Skulls will summon 4 Skeletons. 3 of Dust will summon 3 bandits.The combat now moves into a character control, no longer a card game but a top down action rpg, think of Diablo and you will be getting close.Combat is a little clunky, but nothing to make this game anything of any sort of shabby.Some weapons have abilities like exploding, gaining damage through combos, do more damage the less health you have, that sort of thing.Some shields can reflect range damage back and some trinkets will do things like throw 8 daggers around you, some will activate and give you gold-per-hit and some will give you temp poison.The goal of this is to kill all 12 bosses in the story mode, all with a varying range of tactics.So once again, Want to support Australian developers and get something worth while out of it?Hand of Fate."
