76561198005651913,Recommended,266510,18452094,"Posted: 13 October, 2015",all,Kira,"Wow, I haven't enjoyed a game this much in a long time!  Hand of Fate is a card-based action RPG.  It's essentially a mix between ""choose your own adventure"" books and a D&D campaign.  You acquire loot in the form of cards and tailor your equipment and encounter decks to suit your playstyle.  Love combat?  Done!  Throw in ambush-style cards.  Prefer games of chance?  Excellent!  Gamble to your heart's content.  You can make this game as punishing as you want or give yourself well-deserved breaks from the torment.  Hand of Fate also sets great goals; often beating a quest will add another layer to the story for the next level, which prove to be more challenging and makes the reward that much sweeter.My only complaint would be the short length of story mode, with only 12 levels at ~1-2 hours each, I'm trying to savor the last few.  However, there is an ""Endless Mode"" which is also a lot of fun and increases play time.  If expansion campaigns were released, I would buy them right now.  100% worth your money!  (Spread the word!)"
76561198070134646,Recommended,266510,20341487,"Posted: 5 January, 2016",all,KumaBear,"overall - great game, But do not buy it as a hack n' slash game.hand of fate offers a pretty unique experience, melding cards, adventure, combat, and a bit of role-playing. This game does not do one of those things terribly well, my opinion, some may argue. What it does do well is make the whole situation work, all of these elements together, how random and unsyncable they may seem, come together to make a really interesting experience.I would compare hand of fate to a very simple table top game, munchkin perhaps. You get a map made up of cards, which are adventures, meetings, shops, curses, and eventually - an exit from the current map. Each game has a certain amount of maps, and then you get to the end, where instead of an exit, you get a boss. So far, the boss has been an upgraded version of one of the vanilla enemies, with a twist. The combat is boring at best, but this is coming from someone who has difficulty capped 2 souls games.Honestly, I give the game about a 8 right now with the boring combat. The narrative of each game makes up for it, I would really almost prefer a table top combat to the hack n' slash that they have. more strategic, maybe involve rolls - but that might ruin the balance they got going, so i dunno.One thing it does need is a workshop for endless customizability. Also, I would be over the friggin moon if they figured out a way to make multiplayer work."
