76561197992411030,Not Recommended,266510,35426297,Posted: 2 October,all,Tilkka,"Pretty ok game at first, becomes pretty boring quickly"
,Not Recommended,266510,23814161,"Posted: 25 June, 2016",all,Rodalli,"Been playing games on Steam for nearly a decade now. It is June 25th, 2016, and this is the very first game I have ever requested a refund for.The game is trash, disguised as a treasure. It seems like a lot of fun on the surface, but once you get about 3 to 4 hours in, you realize that none of the decisions you make matter at all. You follow the same tired formula of ""choose to do nothing, and nothing happens, move on to the next card"" or "" choose to do something and unlock a token, which unlocks a new card"". Return to beginning of the loop. There is not a modicum of skill or involved, and very little decision making. Every ""success"" or ""failure"" is literally you drawing randomly from cards that say ""success"" or ""failure"". You can try to follow them being shuffled, and sometimes that results in success if the same card stays on top twice in a row... but really, it's just pure luck of the draw. Once you realize you're playing an RPG on rails, and your choices don't matter... it gets bad. When you then realize that it's just pure luck to hope you randomly pull the one ""success"" card out of four cards, so that you can advance the storyline for that one series of cards... it becomes absolutely, insanely frustrating. And that's an awful thing to feel, playing a low-key, deck-building RPG.The only good things I can say about it is that the production value is quite high. The writing is very good. The art is good. The voice acting for the dealer is excellent. The core idea of trying to merge these RPG, deck-building, action and rogue-like elements is really quite innovative and is what lured me in.Unfortunately, the gameplay just wasn't thought out in the long run. It is not fun to fail over, and over, and over again when there is absolutely no mechanism in your grasp to try to prevent it. It never goes well in a video game when you remove every semblance of control or input from the player's hands. At the end of the day, you'd be better off just clicking ""roll"" over and over on a random number generator. That's pretty much what's happening here."
76561198255596335,Not Recommended,266510,31455605,Posted: 29 April,all,Rick Bishop,"1. You draw an encounter and win. You get a hammer. You now have 7 food and 10 gold.2. You draw a store. You can't afford anything. You have 6 food and 10 gold.3. You draw the beginning of a quest. The required donation to the bard is 15 gold. You now have 5 food and 10 gold and fail the card.6. A fight. You get 3 food.4. You get in a fight, lose health, and are cursed. You have 7 food, 10 gold, and a curse.5. You draw a healer who wants 75 gold to lift a curse and will sell you nothing you can afford. 10 gold, 6 food.6. For half your gold you can beat this card. You now have 5 gold. Oh! It's a chance draw. You fail. Lose 15 max health. 5 food.7. At 4 food, 5 gold, and 85 health you find a quest that will give you equipment but no gold.8. At 3 food you crawl into a shop that wants 44 gold for its cheapest item.9. You have to back track one card to reach the last card. 2 food.10. With one food left and almost your starting equipment, you face the boss and die.All the while you have to listen to a guy who sounds vaguely like Ollivander prattle on about the meaning of this mystical game.If the money mechanic worked at all, this could be a fine game. As it is, you can spend a long time, including waiting on the interface, only to find that nothing you did could possibly have mattered. Hand of Fate indeed. Why?"
