76561198053498233,Not Recommended,266510,16917762,"Posted: 6 July, 2015",all,sl0p0k,"Great idea for a game, but unfortunately, the more you play, the more frustrating little things that didn't seem too terrible at the beginning become.  The biggest failure is the combat system.  Being able to use your mouse to control the direction you move would be great, but instead you're limited to A,W,S,D as though you're just a piece on a chessboard.  That doesn't work so well when you're surrounded by bosses and add ons in a tight space.  I saw some of the unlockable achievements being to fight X number of battles without taking any damage.  Yeah, right.  I'm all for things being more difficult the more I progress, but as others have commented, the difficulty spike soon makes the frustration outweigh the enjoyability factor far too quickly.  I've tried to love it, but the more I play, and the further I move along, the more likely I am to delete this game, count my blessings I got it on sale, and find other, more enjoyable games to play.  Hopefully the developers will read through some of the negatve reviews and continue to revamp the game.  Great idea for a game, but still needs a lot of work to deservite its ""Mostly Positive"" rating it currently has."
,Not Recommended,266510,14612039,"Posted: 23 February, 2015",all,Bastwood,"Quite a fun little mismash of genres - Up to a point. Hand of Fate lays deckbuilding card games, roguelikes, action brawlers and choose-your-own-adventure books onto the table and shuffles. The end result feels surprisingly fresh and innovative, even though none of the individual components would really stand on their own.Initially, the game works wonderfully because of its brisk pace and laidback feel - There seems to always be something new around the corner and the game is just a joy to play. However, as the end draws close, the difficulty is suddenly amped to eleven and the game turns into a grind. During the last few rounds the deck is so stacked against you that even with immaculate play, you can still lose terribly.Yes, I understand that the game is a roguelike and you're supposed to die a bit, but going from not dying at all for 90% of the game to losing twenty times in a row is just poor balancing and design. A shame really, since with a bit less punishing difficulty curve Hand of Fate would've been a surefire recommendation. It delivers innovation, fun and respectable production values, but eventually turns into a plain old Three-card Monte."
