76561198078997529,Not Recommended,266510,14955367,"Posted: 18 March, 2015",all,professor_chaos_,"I wanted to really love this game, but I feel like there is some big room for improvement.First, I must say that the concept is great. It makes for interesting and variable playthrough. I think with a few improvements this could easily turn into one of my favourite games.So the big problem I had is that the combat became very dull and one dimensional about halfway through the game. I felt like as soon once the number on enemies faced in each combat scenario got high enough I ended up just tapping the counter key constantly and could not do much else, and without a shield the was no hope of completing more than a couple of combat scenarios.The deck also started to feel unbalanced partway through the game, which I suppose added to the difficulty, but it seemed like too many cards had a 75% failure or epic failure chance with signifcant consequences and samll chance of reqrd, which was frustrating at times.I think encorporating a bit of dungeon crawling could really liven things up as well. Rather than just being thrust into an arena for each combat, creating a larger level where you could approach the enemies and the combat situation in multiple ways would really improve the gameplay.I am a bit torn about recommending or not recommending this game; I still think it is an interesting concept and worth a playthrough, but there is definitely a lot of room for improvement."
,Not Recommended,266510,16715368,"Posted: 26 June, 2015",all,Aliandris,"Unfortunately I have to give this game a thumbs down, for now.tl;dr - It does a lot of things well, and starts off fun, but the difficulty gets extreme enough to make the game unplayable as anything but a suicide simulator.It frustrates me that I have to give a negative review to this game, because it was really fun when I started playing.  The animations were nice, combat was fun, the voice acting was great.  It was a really well polished random adventure generator game.The basic mechanic of the game is that encountering cards generates an encounter, whether combat, puzzle, story, what-have-you, and completing the card will unlock that card's token, which will in turn unlock more cards to add to future decks.  It gives a good incentive to try to encounter many cards and figure out how to unlock more.  Quite cool.As you progress in the game, unlocking more cards, you will also encounter bosses.  Beating them unlocks the next boss card, and after you beat enough bosses you will unlock an artifact that gives you some bonuses but will also make the game harder.This is the point where the game goes wrong for me.  The difficulty increases introduced by the artifacts make the game virtually impossible by the end.  It was not unusual for me to start a game and the very first card would be a combat against a prior boss, 9 of their minions, on a trapped battlefield with an accompanying totem.  There were so many high powered threats my brand new out of the box adventurer had no chance to win.What makes it worse is that there's no going back.  Once those difficulty spikes are unlocked, they affect the whole game, retroactively.  If I go back to the very first boss of the game, my first encounter on that level might be the aforementioned impossible fight (and was, the time I tried).  The fun of the game, of running around kicking bandits in the face and solving problems for townsfolk became overshadowed by a constant string of deaths brought on by unwinnable fights.There's an easy mode that gives the player some benefits, but activating it disables achievements (gotta punish those filthy casuals) and you can't access any of the other character archetypes in the game, which locks out almost all of the games replayability.Currently the only solution to get rid of the difficulty spikes is to use the 'Erase Progress' feature, which you don't realize until it's too late.  Now, after playing for 12 hours, I'm forced to decide to either erase everything I've accomplished or give up because the game is unplayable.Neither of those choices make any sense, and are a big part of the reason I can't recommend this game.  There's a great premise here, and the underlying system is really, really cool, but it becomes difficult to the point of impossibility and I've got better things to spend my gaming time on than dying forever.Should the devs put in a way to disable the artifacts, or otherwise customize the difficulty of the game in a way that doesn't lock out every other character option, I will revisit this review and hopefully change it to a positive."
76561198032339106,Not Recommended,266510,16701407,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,Elvis,"This game was almost good.I understand that this is not a AAA game. I'm fine with the memory hogging, the stuttering in fps here and there, even ok with the combat not being that fluent when a lot of attackers are attacking at the same time. Even semi-ok with a few of the button prompts in combat popping up a bit late (after it's to late to actually block).I'm a bit less ok with some other stuff. Like the camera, seriously why even make the game 3d if you can't control the camera (also WAAAAAAAAAY to zoomed in)? Just make it isometric and use 2d graphics a lot less work same result, probably better. Why can't you skip past some of the shuffling, I was removing event cards that I almost liked just cause I don't want go through 4 pick this card events...Even with all the above I would have recommended this game to my friends, cause I enjoyed playing it (on hard) progressing through the sometimes quite unlucky near insta fail runs... until...Last boss 1 shot insta fail QTE from 90 hp with heavy armor. ♥♥♥♥ off. There are several games with instant kill QTE, none of them without continues/saves or similar and none without it being a regular part of the game mechanic. Tossing this in on the final boss is just ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, seriously ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥. I'm sorry but I will not be buying any more games from you guys, cause I can't in good conscience support game design like that.Whomever made this design choice shouldn't be designing games.P.S. I actually made the QTE (but still died from it)."
