,Recommended,266510,17196654,"Posted: 23 July, 2015",all,TheJohnnyK,"TLDR:Gameplay - 7/10Graphics - 7/10Audio - 9/10Controls - 7/10Overall - 7/10I WOULD Recommend.Hand of Fate is an interesting title from Defiant, a hodge-podge group of Australian blue bloods and potential filled greenhorns. After launches of games on multiple platforms with varrying degrees of success this group turned to kickstarter to help get one of their more ambitious games released. After a Succesful funding of $54,095 AUD the game was released to steam with very positive reviews.GAMEPLAY - This game offers a wide variety of different aspects. At the surface it is an RPG-like linear adventure game following a random itteration of card placements that the player picks almost at random. As the game progresses the player is introduced to both Hack-N-Slash fighting reminiscient of the Batman games which comes across somehow as both novel and trivial. Finally the player is also introduced to what lies at the heart of this game: deckbuilding. While the game appears to be centered around this aspect it is just as easy for the player to never have to do any of their own building to progress through the entirety of the game. This allows for the player to choose how they would like to play the game and allows for a game that is more immediately approachable by a wider audience. 7/10GRAPHICS - Upon first glance of the title screen with our singular character floating and shuffling his deck of cards by magic it is easy to think the game is beautiful. The atmosphere of the games setting feels volumisically appropriate and well designed. The cards artwork is appropriate, but lacks the subtleties of a physical card game such as Magic or Munchkin. The games biggest graphical downfall comes from the animations. It is first noticed on the initial dealings of the cards that the cards aren't quite as fluent as you would want them to be from a magical card shuffling man, and that is even on the highest of settings. It is also quite apparent that the hits and strikes during the combat portions of the game seem to miss entirely but still do damage. Despite the issues with animations the graphics don't feel poor. 7/10AUDIO - The audio in this game is very subtle. The voicework of the Dealer is well casted and recorded, and despite some repeats in dialogue feels varied enough to keep the player interested in the storyline. Background noises and sound effects always feel in place but do lack the instant recgonizability that all developers would like to obtain. The voice work however in this game is done masterfully and used in conjuntion with the simplistic soundscape and effects the audio deserves some praise. 9/10CONTROLS - This game doesn't ever feel out of hand. I am not sure as to whether or not they recommend that you use a controller, but that was the preferred method during my playthrough. The game feels fine under keyboard and mouse as well, despite a few issues with selecting cards, the game still feels intuitive. Any control issues come down to the combat once again where the controls feels both too simplistic and without force. 7/10GAMEPLAY - The game excels in its script. The Dealers dialogue is both humourous and insightbul at times as well as a pleasant driving force through out the game. An action RPG that lets you play through a trading card game feels new and different, however the action part of the game does feel hampered. It is easy to play the story mode through without touching the endless mode at all. Endless mode, while fun and different, feels like a remnant of Defiants IOS past. 7/10"
76561198179803039,Recommended,266510,16779304,"Posted: 29 June, 2015",all,mag,"Fun, reflex based combat system with a light strategy touch (positioning, mainly).Replayability is very good and there are enough different encounter cards that it keeps things interesting even if you have to play through a ""level"" more than once.Card effects can be a little harsh, especially since it is based on RNG. I mostly die of being broke and starved, and it happens enough that it can't be called bad luck. Also, there are very OP cards which make encounters trivial.Overall great concept, but need balancing work so that drawing a card increases or reduces the difficulty in an appropriate way, and there are less game breaking card draws.Still a thumbs up as it stands."
