76561198030775494,Recommended,266510,16731237,"Posted: 26 June, 2015",all,Arkatreides,"It's hard to sum in in just a few sentences.On the surface it is fairly simple. The game consists of about a dozen missions (each with a different boss encounter at the end, each taking about 10-30 minutes). You have a deck of cards that represent the items you might find during each mission and another deck that represents the encounters you might come across during the mission. The encounter cards also form the 'dungeon' in that they are placed face down in a pattern and you need to walk over them to activate them.At first you only have a few basic items and a few encounters, but each time you 'beat' an encounter card, you get new cards, either new items, new encounters or both. This happens even if you don't beat the boss at the end. Thus even an unsuccessful mission rewards you with more gear for the next time you play the mission.The neat thing is that you choose the set of encounters in the deck yourself, meaning you can stack the deck towards a certain type of encounter.The other thing is that the encounter unlocks themselves tell a story, for example there is one encounter chain where you first come across to lovers who want to run away together, you will later unlock further encounters that tell you what happened to them afterwards. This unlocking of quests gives you another progression axis, so instead of just running the missions and progressing that way by beating the bosses you also progress on this encounter-unlocking axis which makes failure much less frustrating and runs much less repetitive than it would otherwise have been.The narrator is absolutely awesome and really pulls you in to the game.The combat is ok, it's a low prodction values version of the Arkham system. I see some people complain about it not being that great, but it is perfectly functional. The combat sections generally are quite short, and for that the way it works is fine. I have not had any complaints."
76561197995118921,Recommended,266510,14534756,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,Izumi,Great game
76561198042370159,Recommended,266510,15495338,"Posted: 22 April, 2015",all,benrsmith,"Updated review based on further play and updates:This game had the potential to be brilliant, and indeed, it starts out that way; fresh, original and challanging, it draws you into it's world, rewarding skill and punishing carelessness in a way that feels balanced and well thought out.The presentation and voice acting is sublime. I loved the dealer and his snarky little remarks. The VO is superb and I hope to see more of this kind of thing in future games. Another good point are the mechanics of the game; Easy to grasp and introduced smoothly and clearly. If you have any exposure to card or tabletop board games at all then you already know how to play this game, it is that intuitive.The game is hard, unforgivingly so in later levels, but the 'cheapness' and unfairness seems to have been toned down a bit. The brilliance seen at the start now shines through at all points of the game, something I am immensly pleased about.5 Hanged man cards in a row? Yes, that will happen again and again. Nightmare Golem Hunting party cards? Yup, over and over! If this doesn't kill you then the game will just start throwing bosses at you whenever it feels like it; ""Oh I see you are approaching a shop....KING OF DUST AND A DOZEN MOBS!!!!!!!!"" This will come after some unlikely card removes your best weapon of course. Do not think this is exaggeration, it is impossible to exaggerate how much this game enjoys shafting the player.At first I thought this later spike in difficulty and cheating ruined the game, but on reflection I think it adds longevity and I suppose it is in keeping with the theme. Some of the more outrageous BS does seem to have been 'dialed back' which is defintely a positive move. I do not mind losing a game, but losing through no fault of my own, again and again was getting galling.Overall this is unlike any other game you will play. It has absolutely massive replayability and the charm of the presentation, and fun of the core game is enduring, never outstaying it's welcome.I will be keeping and eye on this developer if this is the standard of game they put out!"
