,Recommended,266510,21829119,"Posted: 13 March, 2016",all,kburns10,"The game is not going to win any awards for ""depth"" so to speak, but it's a great game for what it is. You play a traditional card based aventurer where a fortune teller of sorts draws your fate through cards. Any combat is done in real time with an ""Arkham City"" like fighting system. It's very basic, but gets the job done. Really the combat only serves to move you along in the story.If you are looking for a fun adventure game that can be played in short sittings, look no further. What it lacks in depth it makes up for in story."
76561198008345873,Recommended,266510,21751562,"Posted: 10 March, 2016",all,sourface,"The best offer that the elusive genre of ""card game come alive"" has to offer: the random element of a card game meets action gameplay meets fantasy."
76561198061824645,Recommended,266510,16819312,"Posted: 30 June, 2015",all,wesleto02,"Rougelike, CCG, brawler, with a dark and interesting antagonist.It's an indie title that's tried something new, and nailed it in my opinion. on't be everyones cup of tea.But the game is laid out fairly simply enough, it's a rouge like where each card is an encounter of some sort either won by luck, prior knowledge, or through brawling. There are a 3 decks, your deck of cards that you can select to put into the pile, the antagonists deck which he picks from to screw you over as you play the game, and the static cards put into the pile based on which boss awaits you at the end of that run. Each time you play you can earn new cards by successfully beating an encounter for the first time, this will give you more cards to pick from when you play the next round. Will you make your deck challenging with higher rewards for those risks, or easier with less rewards which will leave you less capable of fighting the boss at the end of that run...?The story arc is interesting and I never lost my curiousity for what the main character is trying to achieve by challenging the antagonist in this card game."
,Recommended,266510,21784112,"Posted: 12 March, 2016",all,Kral Sumavy,"Hand of Fate is one of the games I literally fell in love with. It can be described as an action hack and slash rpg, with certain aspects of collectible card games.The premiseis simple, yet incredibly addictive. In the beginning, players have a handful of encounter and equipment cards at their dispositon from which they create a deck. More cards get unlocked as the game progressess and individual encounters get resolved - either by combat or choose-your-own-adventure style dialogue.The combatis reminiscent of Rocksteady's free flow style, implemented in the Batman series.The graphicsare easy to look at, however they suffer in details, undeniably due to a relatively small budget of the independent developer.The audiois great, especially the dealer's lines and voice acting gives the game a necessary ""oomph"" to underline its atmosphere. Asa downside, i would mention the inability to choose the looks of your adventurer, so you are stuck with the same character all throughout your adventure.tl; dr It's a great and unique game. Give it a go if you are into CCGs, RPGs, and ""freeflow style"" hack'n'slash combat."
