,Recommended,266510,21728567,"Posted: 9 March, 2016",all,pendantry,"'Hand of Fate' is a wonderful game.It's a fascinating blend of card deck builder and adventure game, with a dash of philosophical introspection. One of the things I particularly like about it is that it teaches you how to play as you go, you don't need a lot of preparation before setting off on your first adventure. There aren't many controls to learn, and the mechanics are introduced naturally along the way.It's a 'roguelike'; you only have one life -- but death, when it does come, isn't much of a drawback, since you retain any cards you gain in every session, for use in the next 'life'. Even when you lose, you win.The artwork is superb, as is the background music. The dealer's voice is particularly well done. (It sounds to me like Jeremy Irons, but the credits say it's Anthony Skordi.)The only real criticism I have of it is that I find the fight scenes a bit awkward due to the choice of a fixed camera angle. I'm spending far too much time mashing buttons in the fight scenes as left becomes right and up becomes down, and I fear for my keyboard!It's only single player (I don't mind that at all, though I know it's a turn-off for many).I picked it up on sale, but would happily have paid full price for it (why are such gems so few and far between?)"
