76561198066971781,Recommended,266510,16636890,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,sketch_zeppelin_ag,"Its amazing how presentation can spice up a simple game.This is a rouge like where you guide your hero through various challenges, slaying enemies and defeating the boss at the end of each level.  the twist is everything is depicted as card wielded by a mysterious stranger playing across from you.  each encounter is a card thats flipped over and revealed when your peice lands on it and it can be anything from an enemy abush to helping a wandering priest.most of chanllenges will be simple text scenarious where your given a choice of what to do. depending on your answer you'll sometimes auto succed or fail or four cards with fail or succed will be revealed (how difficult the challenge depends on how many of the cards are success and how man say fail)  the cards are flipped face down and suffled and you pick one and pray.  your rewarded with supplies, equipment, and gold and punished with curses, injuries, and loss of provisions or fights.Various events will lead to the drawing of monster cards and suddenly your in an arena fending off enemies with arkham city style combat controls.Then comes another clever twist. often completing challenges will unlock new cards at the end of the round.  you see the challenges you face and the equipment you might earn come from a deck that you can alter.  each round has a requires your equimpent deck and enconter deck to have a certin number of cards and you can swap out encounters or equimpent you don't want to chance coming across in favor of ones you like so you have some conrol of what you'll run into during the game, though the dealer will always shuffle in a set of his own cards to try and trip you up.And all the while the dealer taunts teases and converses with you.  He's really one of the main highlights of the game.  Its like playing a card game with Ron Peralman dressed as a masked wizard (no its not him but thats what the dealers voice reminds me of)This game reaks of charm and personality and i highly recomend it. The game play is simple but how its presented makes it into a unique experice."
76561197970765882,Recommended,266510,16638316,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Fakey,"Combat is very similar to the Batman games, although not as fluid.  Still fun however.Metagame is presented to you as almost a form of Tarot reading.  There is really no exploration, just a series of random events in somewhat of a chain.  Also character progression is not normal, don't get too comfortable with a certain piece of gear.  Also, shields are your life.It seems deceptively easy at first, changes after you get a few bosses in.  Much more of a challenge in terms of both what you're facing and managing your resources.All in all, worth the price."
,Recommended,266510,16638637,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Dr.McLickerTitty,enjoy the hell out of this game
,Recommended,266510,16638739,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Cpt. Smug,"This is a wonderfully made indie card game/action game.  This game is something I don't think has quite been done before.  You build your deck to determine what happens during a round and the mysterious dealer (who is wonderfully animated and voiced) lays traps and misfortunes for you, but he's not your enemy outright.  He plays more of a dungeon master role and lays out the game's story for you.  A lot of time was put into him, as he remembers what cards you used on previous playthroughs and remarks on your playstyle.  If you rely on the same card too often, he will laugh at you for using cheap cards as a crutch.  If you make the enemy deck too easy, he might add a few difficult cards to keep the game interesting.  He has a series of around 16-ish foes for you to challenge, each one harder than the last.You move your token and land on dealt out cards which determine the environment; then the environment comes to life and fights you in a fighting style remniscent of Arkham Asylum.  There are also trap sections you run through.  The animations during this sequence feel a little mechanical and the default difficulty is MUCH too forgiving.  You can just tap the attack button and win.  I recommend upping it to hard mode ASAP.  It causes all the run and hit animations to move faster, hiding some of the awkward motion during action sequences and keeping you engaged in the battle.The game has a great soundtrack with SFX that mirror what the card's effect on your character is.  The voice acting and animation of the cards and the dealer is fantastic.  A single game takes around 15-20 minutes depending on how fast you click through the UI, but there are challenge cards that you can throw in to handicap your character, adding to the replay value.An original idea executed better than any game on the Unity Engine I've seen thus far.  Worth playing."
76561198002869265,Recommended,266510,16639761,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Arius Aneid,"Hand of Fate is quickly becoming one of my very favorite games. If you enjoy tabletop games, board games, card games, or any kind of storytelling game, this is the game for you. The controls are simple and the game seems easy at first; the first few levels have easy challenges, battles with slow counter-attack times, and weak enemies. But then it ramps up. I'm about halfway through the game and it's gotten challenging, but not so much it's just annoying to play. Counters are more difficult, if not impossible at some points, and enemies take a bit more strategy to beat. The storyteller is sarcastic in the best way, often getting annoyed if you wait too long or making fun of your resources if you're doing poorly. The only issue I have with it is there are required cards for every mission, and some of them get old after using them again and again. But they do change up after you get the token for the card, so that's good at least. Overall, it's been a fun experience and I definitely plan to buy the expansion (and any more that come out)."
