76561198040562746,Recommended,266510,16696973,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,spasm57,"One of the most entertaining gems to come out of steam. One part rogue like, one part Fable-esque hack-n-slash, one part deck builder, add in some truly wonderful monologues from the Dealer, and you arrive at Hand of Fate.The combination of deck building and roguelike allows for a unique choose your own adventure style of play. With the release of the Wildcard dlc the replay value skyrockets by adding in new ""Fate"" cards (essentially new player characters) that come with thier own unique challenges.The game starts out reletively easy, with a limited number of cards and shorter dungeons. But as you progress you unlock upgrades that improve your abilities but also thte abilities of your enemies, creating a more traditional roguelike experience (i.e. hard as hell). While not overly difficult with thte default Fate, it becomes increasingly more difficult when playing as the Warlord (hard mode) or the Monk(no gold!!). Top it off with some real nasty curses and this game would appeal to the most masacistic roguelike fans.On the downside, and it really is the only downside I can see, the combat gets a little stale after a while. It boils down to more or less hit and run strikes, although with the right equipment this ceases to be a problem.Highly recomended, one of the best additions to the steam catalogue. With the simple addition of new cards the potential for expansion is nearly infinite. 9/10"
,Recommended,266510,16703126,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,Laserface Jones,"I figured I would  have written a review of this game by now. Easily in my top games in recent memory, it combines Fable-esque combat with deckbuilding RPGs and fun, ominous story bits. The game starts out easy, ramps up, and kills you with super mean RNG effects. If you like roguelikes and deckbuilding games, I can't imagine a better suggestion."
76561198048556706,Recommended,266510,16703795,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,thewhiteknuckle,"So I walked into a bar and a guy in a hood asked me if I wanted to play his hipster version of DnD. I went ""sure, why not, I'm bored"", and promptly started to hallucinate while he dealt me cards, and I was left wondering why I'm even in a bar, considering I don't drink...Hand of Fate is a rather story-vague game that puts you into the place of some kind of wandering adventurer. Our status is unknown (alive? dead? neither? both?), and we've crossed what's known as ""The Thirteen Gates"" to come and meet... whoever this is, we'll call him The Dealer (not that kind). The Dealer seems to be offering the adventurer a chance to get whatever they want, be it riches, eternal life, answers or what have you. Honestly, I'm not entirely sure what's happening, all I know is that I don't trust him and that whoever he is, he's going to give me what I want. Bit like a Djinn if you will.Although that's a point in the game's favour; it allows the player to make up their own little story and figure out what's going on while getting hints of a past life from the cards that are played against them.The gameplay itself is surprisingly well done; the first portion of the game is a DnD style card game, where the dealer acts as a sort of Dungeonmaster to explain what occurs on each card, then gives you the necessary tools to resolve them. Cards can either give you Health (self-explanetory), Gold (ditto mark), and Food (required to explore and continue in the game), Armor/Weapons (more self-explanatory terms), Special items and other assistances. Cards can also be negative, and punish you with loss of any of these above subjects, or even summon monsters to fight you.Upon drawing a monster card we're placed into the Brawler aspect of the game, wherein the game takes an adequately presented 3D perspective to let you physically fight your opponents, which change based on card suit and number (3 of Dust for bandits, a 2 of Skulls for undead, so on and so forth). Your weapon and armor cards become actual weapons and armor to use, and special items can be activated to change the outcome of the battle if necessary. It's well presented and flows excellently, allowing fluid dodging, countering and attacks to whittle down enemies for success. There's very little to complain about.It's not an extroardinary game, mind. It feels more like something you'll flick on every few hours to kill 10-30 minutes, something to occupy you for a bit while you wait. Almost like a mobile game effortlessly intermingled with a dungeon brawler game. It's impressive in its own way, and rather enjoyable."
