76561197994641567,Recommended,266510,16546052,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,Zen Tractor,"Hand of fate is an interesting game.  The combat is kinda simple, but the real meat of the game is in the 'meta'game.  Playing the cards and messing about with the decks you want to build to equip and fight against is a ton of fun, and there's a lot of anticipation and foreplanning when it comes to exploring each floor.A good portion of the encounter quest cards lead to more encounters, often in a narratively sense as well as a strictly unlocking sense.  Making your way through a boarder town for the first time, for instance, will open up new frontier lands (in the form of new encounter cards) for you to adventure forth to.I am also very fond of the main character.  While he is a bit of a silent protagonist, you do get a lot of insight to him from the cards and the encounters, which are based off of his past life and/or memories.  I also like that he's not just a generic sort of a guy; he's got an interesting but not overdesigned look, and clearly isn't afraid to do what he desires.  This is also somewhat shown through gameplay, as while you often get several choices of how to respond to some encounter prompts, only one of them will progress you to future encounters.  It lends a sense of ""this is how it actually went"" to thing.At the same time the other main character, and your opponant, the Dealer, has his own story, some of which you unravel as you play.  He is voiced very well, and manages to capture one's attention as he comments on both your gameplay choices and the narrative happenings in the plot.  It's like you are both playing a game with him, and yet telling a story with him through your actions.The system is also very expandable, so it's fairly safe to assume that there'll be some DLC in the works for this game.Overall, this is a very solid game, and one well worth throwing a fair few hours at.I would recommend a controller, if you have one, as it makes the combat feel a little better."
