76561198053675470,Recommended,266510,15598102,"Posted: 28 April, 2015",all,BrantWarder,"Hand of Fate is a unique blend of deck building, RPG, and action/adventure with a good, if vague, story and a lot of replayability. It's quite fun and different than most games in any of its genres. It's not without issues but I would highly recommend this game.Pros:•	Well blended combination of gameplay from its three different genres•	Excellent soundtrack and voice work•	The random dungeons reward exploration while avoiding any grind due to the wide variety of encounters•	Each gameplay session is a different story in and of itself•	Excellent difficulty curveCons:•	I'm only going to put one thing here: the combat. Now don't get me wrong, I enjoy the combat, it's not broken, nor does it make the game unplayable. The problem is that it goes for counter-based combat of the Arkham variety. Unfortunately do to the fact that this is an indie game they didn't have the animation budget of something like Arkham City or Shadows of Mordor. As a result the combat is often feels janky as your character suddenly breaks off his combo to block the attack of an enemy behind him. While this is largely a visual thing it also effects the gameplay. At times it can be hard to tell whether or not an attack will hit you, it can also lead to you combat rolling into an enemies attack rather than away from it. Fortunately the combat doesn't outstay its welcome and the game as a whole is solid.To summarize: I loved this game! The combat was a bit of a hiccup but it's functional and the exploration and aesthetic more than make up for it. Plus the new DLC adds more play options each with their own twist. Buy this game because, if nothing else, you won't play anything else like it!"
