76561197990029262,Recommended,266510,15476360,"Posted: 21 April, 2015",all,Licious-D K&D,"Verdict: Surprisingly addictive game with a charismatic antagonist and charming (though sometimes frustrating) mechanicsTo be blunt, this game is not what I expected. Then again, what was there to expect from a game that advertises with being a ""card game"" with action game mechanics. When I first saw it, I figured it had to be something like ""Persona"" series of games, and to SOME extent, this holds true. The random nature of each ""dungeon"" is what you might say these have in common. The similarities end, however, when you actually play the game. If I had to compare it with something people already knew, I'd say it is a weird hybrid between a ""Make your own adventure"" game, mixed with a collectible (sort of) trading card game, some D&D and a pinch of Arkham Asylum - if that makes any sense.The gist of the game is this: You are a nameless Adventurer that battles against a mystic card dealer that sets you up with a different dungeon every time you start a new mission. Your adventurer is actually represented by a small golden gaming piece that you can move about the track of cards layed out before you. The cards obviously face down, and the moment you step on it, it is turned to reveal your fate - and behold there is quite alot to be revealed. The scenes are described using text in a the fashion you'd see a dungeon master read from them in any kind of fantasy rpg. ""Action"" in these scenes is usually resolved by being presented some choices and depending on which one is picked, some event happens. An example would be the ""Angry Guildmaster"": He bullies you out of the way with his horse, and you have the option to either ""Humbly apologize"", or try and steal from him. While the first option lets you continue on your way, the second lets you pick 1 of 4 cards to see how things develope. Dragin a ""success"" card will net you a reward card (coming in the form of food, gold, health potions and such), whereas a failure might result in you getting thrown into a dungeon, having to fight your way out against a number of opponents, which - you guessed it - is determined by the pick of a card.You'd be surprised how littel ""action"" there is actually going on. Only a minority of cards (still plentiful, mind you) actually leads to you being set into an action scene to fight. The game has a few set areas or stages where combat might take place, depending on where the descriptive card you landed on told you you were. There is quite a bunch of them, and some of them are trap-ridden and require keen awareness and movement.The combat itself is basically Arkham Asylum's Reflex system, where you have three different actions. Attack, counter, shieldbash. It is, literally, the same thing, but it works quite well and you rarely get the feeling you are not in control. It is nothing new or astonishing, but have you ever heard someone complain about AA's combat system? Me neither.As for items and such, you get a pretty standard array of axes, hammers and swords, a couple of rings, shields and armours, a bit of magic through ""artifacts"", pretty much standard fantasy stuff. Again, it works well enough to keep you entertained and allow for some meta-gaming.Now, you might wonder, what is my goal in this game and how does this card thing come into play appart from being a random mechanic? The longer you play, the more cards you unlock through ""tokens"", which are attached to some cards. Resolve the card in the intended way successfully, and you get new cards. You can then use these cards to build your decks: One is for all your own goodies like weapons and armour, the other for possible encounters - that's right, you get to determine what encounters you might have in your adventure! But beware, the sinister card dealer has a word in this, too. With every new adventure, he puts in increasingly more challenging cards. Also, each of the story mission comes with some kind of ""mutation"": Sometimes everyone moves faster and receives double damage, another one might forbid certain actions, make things more expensive, etc. It will keep things fresh for quite a while, at least for the ""story mode"", which is, essentially, just you wandering from card to card until you reach the next boss. When story mode is not enough, you can always try endless, where anything goes and you continue until you are dead.Now, with the card game mechanics come some things you'd might expect that make the whole experience a little... tainted. Especially in the later stages of the game, you might simply be unlucky and die without being able to do much about it. I had an especially annoying series of events that left me with ONE max HP (that is right: My maximum HP have been reduced from 100 to 1!), no food left (you lose Hitpoint when moving your piece without having food from ""starvation) and nothing to redeem myself. In essence, the game just laughed at me. Now, these extreme cases seem to be very, very rare, but there are other cases where you realize you will probably not stand a chance against the upcomming boss because you simply had no chance of drawing equipment cards, never receiving gold or food, or the dealer drawing two old bosses (once bosses are beaten, they can be drawn as ""regular"" enemies in encounters) very early in the game, causing you to either die or losing many hitpoints. Also, while it caters to the games charm, it is not always clear what the developers intended with certain events and what a certain choice might lead to. This ""trial and error"" principle is probably there to pad out the game a little bit (which would fall a little short in content, otherwise), but be aware that this game sometimes just doesn't seem to ""play it fair"".I also find it a little disappointing that the action sequences are so limited and that the majority of the game takes place ""at the table"". The game does make up with SUPERB voice acting by Anthony Skordi, whom you might recall from voicing the more cockney'esque Dark Elves in The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim. He also has quite the number of lines to boot, but still, it would have been much nicer if there had been a smoother transition between the card play and the actual action.Also, the overall card and deckbuilding mechanics fall short once you have unlocked all the cards. There is no ways to get ""doubles"" (apart from what the game gives you), or winning ""boosters"" to alter up or otherwhise improve your deck. The developers have already released one DLC, but need to bring more options if they want to bring longevity to this game.Of course, you have to consider that this is a kickstarter game and much of what I critisized could never be expected from the limited scope of ressourced the developers had at their disposal. The game is also budget-priced, so again, the equation fits. It is hard to do this game justice and it is a shame they do not provide a demo. It was a blind pick for me and I was pleasantly surprised, but it is hard to say whether this game will be to your liking or not. It is a fresh idea where the result is greater than the sum of its parts."
,Recommended,266510,15479265,"Posted: 21 April, 2015",all,UnKnown Player,"A fantastic short play game with an oddly smooth story telling element for what is semi random level design. It links trading card elements (you create your own decks which are used alongside the dealer's decks) with 3rd person combat and a feeling of enemies, progression, good and evil from the original Fable. You progress through levels by turning over adjacent cards, these invariably provide you with a challenge or opportunity which you must overcome, some are done through role playing choices, some through combat and some through basic games of chance. Along the way you need to keep an eye on your health, food and gold supplies, buy things from traders, give charity to worthy causes and collect more powerful items. As you defeat cards you gain new ones of your own which may or may not be dealt out as you progress through the game. Add to this the fact that the same card can have different outcomes on different play throughs and the replayability is high.Although not graphically stunning it is pretty enough and it is the voice of the narrator / dealer that makes the game come alive.A great game for 30 minutes or 3 hours, deffinitely worth a look especially for those of us that remember Hero Quest or Fighting Fantasy books."
