76561197973051663,Recommended,266510,14539263,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,Popcorn Colonel,"Hand of Fate is a clinic in good game design.  Yes, it borrows from many sources:  choose-your-path books, collectible card games, arcade fighters and more.  But it blends those diverse elements into something you've not seen before.  When you've been gaming for four decades as I have, playing something unique is a rare treat indeed.+ Eye-catching art+ Interesting writing and voice acting+ Understated sense of humor+ Gameplay that appears simple but becomes more complex and challenging the longer you play+ S T Y L E.  Oodles of it.  In an endless sea of MMO, RTS and FPS clones, this stands out like a bright beaconNothing is perfect, of course...- The basis for the interface design is obviously consoles, which makes keyboard and mouse slightly awkward.  Not game-breaking by any means, but it is noticeable for PC Master Race types such as myself.  Still, it shouldn't stop you from buying.  You'll quickly get used to it -- or just plug in a gamepad.- A few minor spelling errors.  I'm a self-admitted grammar nazi, however, so most people probably won't notice or won't care even if they do notice.  A niggle, nothing more.  Pardon me while I stroke my neurosis.Summary:  Just buy it.  I promise you haven't played anything exactly like it before, and at the price point you'll easily get your ""movie standard"" value out it.  If nothing else, it shows support for game designers who aren't swimming in the blood gutter of money clones, and we could do with a lot more of that."
