,Recommended,266510,14539721,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,Onions,"I find this to work more like a board game.  If Talisman tried some rogueish influence you'd have Hand of Fate: an interesting game where you play levels: first the jack of a suit, then you restart and fight another suit's boss after a level, rinse, lather repeat.  Simple enough.  The game is played by using facedown cards as tiles, moving one space at a time (using food as a resource), discovering each card and playing out each scenario -- Might be an enemy ambush!  Might be a shop to get new armor, weapons, spells, etc.  Completing some cards in certain circumstances (like score a critical success) will reward you with new cards for later levels. You get to pick some of the cards that are used on this playing field, though there are other cards involved in it to.  Combat isn't terribly exciting, just whackwhackwhack counter chance! whackwhackwhack counter! Roll!!  The adventures themselves are still quite enjoyable, though not too difficult.An overlooked part of this game is the Dealer character. The only speaking character is the monologuing Dealer, who has a very good attitude for a 1-on-1 DM. He has some interesting things to say, no matter how small: Sometimes when I get a blessing, he'll say he made the card a little overpowered, and should rebalance it sometime.  Things like that just come across as genuine, though you'll hear him say much more interesting things.As far as pricing goes, even $20 seems a little high, I'd recommend picking it up around the $10-15 range."
