76561198035290819,Recommended,266510,14575471,"Posted: 21 February, 2015",all,Mr. crazydude,"A very interesting and deadly game of cards.The story telling in this game is amazing. I love how the dungeon master (or whatever he is called) always works against you. Outing his anger when you gain something and laughing at you when you are closer to death. The cards are just as intruiging as well. A big variety of encounters, roleplay (aka find the right card out of 4) and shops. Endless mode is just a bunch of fun so you can play to your hearts content.However the game is not without it's flaws ofcourse. During every card encounter the game gives you the option to ""take the challenge"" or ""leave"". That's really not a great option as you will most likely always click the ""yes"" button. I don't really see a point in not doing a challenge either. If you are low and you skip it you will most likely be dead on the next card as you can't skip everything.combat is it's biggest flaw I'm afraid. It's very nice to get down and personal in a fight but the mechanics are a bit lacking. You can easily win every combat you encounter. There should either be a more complex version of it or a difficulty setting (as there is none in the game, just default difficulty). If you want a better version of it, go play one of the pc batman games. Same combat style but better designed. On a side note I also love how the arena constantly changes by what card you drew. From deserts to castles to forest etc.... depending on the card you drew and the boss you will be facing (so far I encountered: dust, undead, rats and lizzards as monster mobs, I guess that's also the only ones in the monster decks)Overall I'm enjoying it very much! I would recommend it if you are into card games, but not if you're a combat veteran."
,Recommended,266510,14575488,"Posted: 21 February, 2015",all,gondorle,"I don't write reviews everytime I play a new game I enjoy. I need to really love it or hate it. Why? Well, I am a lazy geek that enjoys procrastinating and well, do nothing. In this case, I really need to say a couple of things:I bought this game on a whim. I liked the concept and the music in the trailers sounded cool. The price was just right for my ""I buy a new game on steam every month"" thing, and so I did.This game brings back memories of old. The soundtrack is awesome, our opponent is awesome as well and the replayability is absolutely tremendous. Everytime you play, it is a different game. You don't quite understand if the card dealer is a friend or a foe, maybe both, but you'll love him for it.It is as much as an RPG as it is an Adventure game and well, a card game as well. You keep playing, betting on your luck and mixing it with micro-management and you'll eventually finish it all. It's not as easy as you might think though, you need some combat skills as well. The game is not all about playing cards, you do need to fight your way through various combat situations, which is cool. The combat system reminds me of games like Batman, where you need to counter enemies attacks. Of course you'll need some nice equipment and nice equipment you get throughout your gameplay session. Never the same mind you. The bosses - yes, there is a boss for every ""playthrough"" - are hard enough, but you'll probably won't find any real difficulty, unless you've been real unlucky in the past like getting robbed by goblins of your food and pieces of equipment, or even a tough unfortunate card you've chosen that made you lose life etc....All in all, it's not exactly up to you how you end the playthrough. It depends both on luck and skill, which is like in everyday life, where most of the things are outside your margin of control. The game is an awesome improvement on card and rpg games alike, and should be played by as many people as possible. The price is awesome, for an awesome game. Hand of Fate is my new favourite game, buy it."
