,Recommended,266510,14639097,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,IRMA,"Even though as I write this review I only have 3 hours into this game, I felt like a game this phenomanel deserved a reccomendation. Hand of Fate isn't just some card game though such as Pokemon/Magic/Yu-Gi-Oh. You move around your piece onto different cards for different encounters such as an ambush or a shop. If you land on an enemy encounter you don't do the normal turn-based attack like most jrpg's/card games, you actually fight the enemies with the equipment you have gathered on your journey like in mmorpgs such as Neverwinter (but in Hand of Fate the combat isn't tedious/monotonous). Other aspects of the game are the voice acting which is just fantastic, or the graphical detail which is also amazing. The game's replay value is almost infinite seeing as how once you unlock endless mode you can play randomly generated matches until you perish. Hand of Fate is a game I would most definitely recommend  to about anyone who like card games and rpgs. I give this game a 9.5/10."
76561197962473519,Recommended,266510,14940063,"Posted: 17 March, 2015",all,Caff,"Love this game.  Every play through is a unique randomised roleplaying experience.  You uncover more experiences each time you play, and each playthrough has it's own story, and it's own highs & lows.Even thought it's based around cards, it's NOT a Hearthstone game.  This is a new concept, yet it feels like a classic game you might have played (and loved) as a kid.You travel by uncovering cards and facing random encounters, playing against ""The Dealer"".  He's a sinister and challenging figure who both taunts and encourages you through the good and bad cards you uncover.  It feels like a boardgame and roleplaying game being played out just for you,  The combat sequences provide some relief through action, yet are difficult if you are not prepared with appropriate armour, weapons and blessings.Best game of 2015 for me so far, and I really recommend this to anyone who's ever played and loved ""Hero Quest"" or the old ""Fighting Fantasy"" books by Ian Livingstone & Steve Jackson.  It's old skool - yet new skool - and I have hopes that more people will discover this wonderful game."
