76561198065548571,Recommended,266510,18437184,"Posted: 11 October, 2015",all,Insanity Shotgun,"This is a difficult little review to properly put down, but I enjoyed most of this game enough to want to recommend it, though with a little explanation of why you may also want to leave it be at the same time. I loved most of this game, but really just started to hate it near the end, and not for the reason the mocking narration would want me to.To talk about it's positive features, Hand of Fate can be very immersive with its vague storytelling, atmosphere and gameplay. It's mostly easy to just lean in and become engrossed in the voice acting, artwork, movement of the cards, etc etc. The combat sections that happen in between moving your token along the path of cards laid down are very simple for the most part, and a nice little bit of interaction that may have kept the game from getting too hands off, even if it is a weaker, if neccesary, part of the game.It's easy to just listen to the dealer speak through every draw of a card and outcome of an event, doing your simple obligatory counter-attack combat straight from the WB games. Quite enjoyable.However, it was around the halfway point the game started becoming very, very hateable, specifically on the Jack of Scales boss. While I had had a bad-ish run up to that point, I was still capable of fighting the boss...until the game started crashing, in the middle of every fight attempt. And it turned out, it was a glitch related to his tail slap manuever a few other people had had problems with. Now, had I had a good run I could have blitzed him with a powerful artefact and a weapon ability...But I hadn't had a good run, so I had to forfeit the game and start over, not because of difficulty or utter bad luck with my run, but because the game was crashing. That combined with a bit of the slightly mocking narration from the dealer? Ooh, rustled my jimmies abit, but I tried to keep going.But it just kind of went downhill from there. Lots of stupid♥♥♥♥♥♥would happen, like getting a card that requires you to move a certain number of spaces before a time limit takes half your health away, and having the destination just be beyond that time limits ability to reach. That has no strategy to it, no risk or reward. You just trade half your health for a probably underwhelming item that barely helps and you only knew you were doing that AFTER you couldn't go back. That's kind of ♥♥♥♥♥♥.And then of course, the cards start glitching out and you have a bad fortune card drawn and stuck on your screen, it sticks through the loading into a shop and then you cant sell things to buy food because a card is hovering in front of that crap, and you have to quit out the game and come back in, only to die the next turn because you couldn't buy food or heal on the shop because you wasted your turn quitting out because of a glitch, and the next combat had you fighting 5 lava golems in an especially small arena.It's also worth mentioning my only ever encounter with the minotaur thus far resulted in a weird, awkward combat where he would charge around the arena, sliding off of pillars instead of impacting them, seeming basically impossible to hit, until he got stuck in a wall and his model started glitching out something awful.And the whole time anyways, The Dealer is making his smug little commentary on your bad fortune, and it feels more like he's mocking you for playing a buggy video game than for having bad luck in the game you are playing against him. Immersion breaks, you grit your teeth and try to keep playing because you want to see the outcomes to things...Obviously, that's a personal experience and it could not occur on someone else's playthrough...but still.Summarizing anyways, Hand of Fate can be alot of fun, can be very engrossing, but can also be very frustrating and some of the bugginess in the game, while minor, really, really can upset the experience. I do recommend the game, it's well priced for what you get, but think twice if you're not sure. Maybe wait for a sequel or another iteration of the game where the developers have perfected things.7/10, would reluctantly watch a minotaur warp in upon himself again."
