76561197979537904,Recommended,266510,14540154,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,EdgeTK,"it's simple, batman / assassins creed style combat in a game vs the devil, he shuffles the deck and you get to control what cards are in your side, he controls whats in his. some cards are for drawing (weapons, armor, items etc) some cards are bad encounters (special enemies, bad events, traps) some cards are good encounters (Shops, npcs, healers).The tile cards are placed face down and you choose your path, sometimes its totally open as you try to advance to the next level, sometimes it no choice in direction but its ALWAYS randomized. You move you use 1 food but heal 5 hp, you start with 100 hp though you can increase it, every move becomes a choice of do I explore and heal or progress to conserve food. Each card a potential encounter to help or hurt you, some levels are fights, some levels you explore, some levels you... well you'll see. It's simple, basic and wonderful. Very rougelike and as you play the dealer (devil) gets harder as you get stronger, you get better items to stack your draws with, but so does he, you get better armor, but he gets better enemies, you get better trinkets / artifacts (think pixel dungeon) but he gets to curse you. It's very nice and progressive and if / when you beat it, you can go for an endless mode for a true rogue like action fighter card game. Never played a game like this but happy I picked it up. It's 20% off right now, I've been following it through EA but this last patch  sold me on it. This is just a wonderful game, makes me wish I had gotten it sooner. Kudos to the Dev's."
,Recommended,266510,14540177,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,jssrfx,"What a unique experience; and I mean this in the most positive way possible. I usually get negatively surprised when I decide to try out a title that is not part of a series, style, or game type I know I'll enjoy. It's rare that it happens, but this time it is the exact opposite.I have often wondered what it would be like if you combined ""Magic the Gathering"", ""Dungeons & Dragons"", and some kind of ""Diablo"" based game. Looks like this it. The way medieval styled fantasy deck cards are combined with a very pleasant story narration, and action based dungeon crawl elements, is truly well done. Very well done. I cannot stress this enough.The game/cards/session is randomly generated, which technically makes the replay value pretty much infinite. This title is very atmospheric. The music is utterly great; it reminds me of folk tunes similar to what you would expect from artists such as Loreena McKennitt; it's soothing, but also thrilling at the same time. The narration is top notch. Truly a story teller, something that certainly is the ultimate game master. Wouldn't we all like to be able to shuffle cards like that?I wish the graphics were a little less cartoon-ish looking, but I also think that the 'polish' of the game is just right. It looks like an old board game has come alive, and shows you all the magic in beautiful effects. Playability wise, I think it works perfectly fine with mouse and keyboard. I don't have a controller, I don't like them, and I find it no better or worse to control than other games of the same kind.To me, this is a game with barely any shortcomings, except for the fact that I agree on the repetitiveness of some of the fighting sequences. That's a minor issue though, and is hugely outweighed by the rest of his marvelous experience.For an Indie game this is a true gem, and I wish some of the developers of AAA titles would take some notes in regards to originality. I'm from a generation that played games before the first 3Dfx cards came on the market; nice graphics are certainly awesome, but the narrative, presentation, immersion, atmosphere and originality outweigh any kind of shaders, ambient occlusion and anti-aliasing for sure."
