,Recommended,266510,14556823,"Posted: 20 February, 2015",all,valkymaera,"Absolutely solid indie rpg for the price. Tabletop RPG fans will feel at home. The mystical theme works well, and the ""Dealer"" is executed elegantly with his dark wit, personality, voice acting, and nuanced gestures.The gameplay consists of a set of cards dealt faced down on the table in a random path. These represent the ""level"". A figurine represents you on these cards, and you move across them in a direction of your choice, one card at a time, revealing them and resolving them as you land on them. They might be fights, traps, or story events, or some combination of the three. While doing this, you are balancing how much food you have left (it is lost every move), whether your gold is better spent on food, blessings, or equipment, whether it's worth it to explore further or look for a shop on the next level, etc. You are also engaged thematically with the style of the scene, and the banter of the Dealer, while making story decisions for the cards, or engaging in combat.Fights bring you into real-time combat using the gear your have found, in a freeform twitch / reaction combat style similar to the batman arkham series or Middle Earth: Shadows of Mordor. It is not perfect; the camera is a little rough and the animation and targeting can be slightly shaky, but it is still very good, especially for an indie game. I grew comfortable with it pretty quickly, and I haven't had any significant issues. I enjoy it, and I think it's the best form of combat for this game.One of the cards on the level is an exit to the next level, which will clear the table and draw a new map of cards. Depending on the mode of play, you are either descending to ultimately fight one of an impressive number of bosses (story mode), or descending indefinitely into ever-increasing difficulty (endless mode). Endless mode uses all cards that you have found. Story mode uses custom decks that you build ahead of time.The customization and collection aspect of this game really make it shine:As you play, you unlock cards that are added to your collection. You use this collection before each game to build 2 customized decks: Equipment, and encounters. Your equipment deck isn't what you start with, but instead represents all the items that you may find in shops, chests, and as combat rewards throughout the game. Your encounter deck represents the cards that make up a level. So you are putting together the pieces of your story. You are deciding what you'll run into, and what you'll find, with some other things added by the dealer. You unlock new cards to add to your collection as you go.From a developer perspective, these guys put a lot of care into this game. There are elements of conditional dialog, animations, and menus; things like the dealer saying something different or being aware of your stats, things like a menu screen that changes based on whether or not you've completed the tutorial level, and other things that may seem trivial, but took consideration, time, and effort to include, when really they didn't have to. Bigger games have been released with far less intelligent scripting.This has quickly become a personal favorite."
