,Recommended,266510,14730217,"Posted: 2 March, 2015",all,Gatemoth,"There's a lot that seems antiquated or unpolished, but I found myself wanting to continue and complete the game.The dealer is a neat character, and the way the game is setup, through trading cards, adds an excellent storyline and backstory: the card drawn is a 2 of lava golems, so the player must fight 2 lava golems.  That's meant as praise to the intriguing minimalist game tableau rather than as lambastment.The combat is more engaging than it initially seems.  This is batman's combat without gadgets, without control of the camera, without special moves, and with movement that always feels erratic.  There is 1 attack, 1 shield bash, a batman-style autocounter, and a dodge.  The challenge of the combat is chaining long combos, which deal increasing per-blow damage and add a minigame to the simple action.  Continuing combo chains becomes difficult in the later levels with boss monsters, unblockable attacks, and constant projectiles interrupting player combos.  It's simple, but it keeps the attention.The graphics are wince worthy.  Blur effects are often more a nuisance than a graphical enhancement, and the in-combat graphics feel 10-years-ago. Annoying shop load times and card shuffle animations really emphasize that this was meant to be a text-based game.Overall, I've been wavering between thumbs up and thumbs down.  The game has so little, but I keep going back to try to collect more tokens and beat the last levels.  Thumbs up with reservations."
