,Recommended,266510,15023979,"Posted: 23 March, 2015",all,Jerot,"The random encounter element leads to some interesting scenarios, its fun to go through and try to unlock more stuff. The combat starts really slow, but speeds up as you progress through the story, in the end its not super compelling, and at times can be a bit grindy, especially on runs where you have bad luck with weapons. But ultimately it didn't detract from my enjoyment of the game, and at times it can feel really badass to zip from enemy to enemy countering and deflecting ranged attacks while building up a massive combo.It is definitely a unique take on deckbuilding, as you have to balance risk and reward, you can hand-tailor the difficulty by including more challenging/risky encounters to make the game even more intresting. I feel like $25 is a fair price if a bit on the high end of what I personally think the game is worth, if the game is currently on sale, I would definitely recommend buying it.At the time of review, I've spent about 11 hours with the game, beaten the story mode to completion including the final boss which was a very interesting and challenging encounter, you're in for a treat. But there is still plenty left to do, I have only unlocked about 80% of the available cards and every journey into endless mode has been very different. Sometimes the deck is generous and I can spend several floors feeling like a god, and others I'm smited down immediately by seemingly insurmountable odds, but either way, it can be a single encounter that changes the course of the game, it keeps it very engaging."
76561197969718615,Recommended,266510,14596308,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,joepez,"I don't write a lot of reviews, but this is a good game and warrants one. It's one of the better indies I've played recently with a lot more depth and fun than it seems to posses at first glance. The story is interesting with you playing against a rival for some unknown treasure; the skill ramp is slow, which gives you time to learnt he mechanics; and the gameplay is extremely varied.There's a nice mix of ranomness, luck, and skill to each play session. Combat is twitch based, though not overally aggressive; the deck building is fun; and the overall story is interesting. I especially like how cards can have stories that unlock additional cards as you succeed at their demands.The animations can be a little jerky in some spots and there's a few odd bugs (ex: change categories in a story, right click and then hit ESC (thinking it will close the window) and your cursor disppears. For those that his this, simply alt-tab and then alt-tab back to the game and your cursor will come back).I'd recommend this game anyone getting tired of the rouge-clones that are popping up and looking for something fun and engaging."
,Recommended,266510,14597048,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,JRSVaultBoy1974,"I'm very into deck building card games at the moment so there was a lot of appeal going in for Hand of Fate.  The price is also reasonable so I figured I'd give it a try.I've played through the first three bosses and I have to say I really like Hand of Fate.  There's something very exciting about it.  Let me walk you through the game play.  You and your mysterious opponent both have several decks of cards to choose from (that you can customize after the first run through the dungeon).  These cards represent the journey you'll take to get to the boss.  They also hold encounters and equipment you can gain to upgrade you hero.  You hero starts with basic equipment (a sword and light armor), 100 hit points, and some food.  The stranger places the cards on the table to represent the path to the boss.Then you'll move from card to card dealing with whatever you find there.  Sometimes it's a peaceful ecounter with a friendly merchant, sometimes it's a trap, other times it's an encounter with a powerful demon.  You hero must deal with each card and continue along until they get to and defeat the boss enemy.  When it comes time to battle you zoom into a battle ground and you see your cards turn into your hero complete with all of the equipment you've found to this point.  Then you fight whatever was on the card you drew.  It's a lot of fun.The thing that probably makes this game for me is the dialog of the mysterious stranger and the music.  It really sets the tone and atmosphere of the game.If you like rpgs, choose your own adventures, deck building, or adventure games you may find something to like here.  I would definitely recommend this title."
