76561197998891378,Recommended,266510,14119697,"Posted: 22 January, 2015",all,Cheshire,"You play a tabletop card game with (or better say - against) its creator, a mysterious man in hoodie - Dealer. He offers you to defeat twelve his most powerful servants. Then' you'll try a luck defeating the Dealer himself. Chalenge accepted!In some way, Hand of Fate feels like a mix of text quests and Jumanji, where unhurried quests with choice, contingent dice rolling and resource management intersects with fast fierce real-time slashing episodes.Before plunging into a travel after a head of Dealer's ugly servant you might manage two decks - Deck of Items and Deck of Events. First deck contains cards equipment that you eventually find during this travel, the second one defines quests. Every journey is made by bunch of good stories, so in Hand of Fate any road to the precious boss head is made by that quest cards. From gambling with demons to helping a couple in love to escape from the town, from dreaming on poppy field to passing dungeon full of traps, from speaking with drunk stranger in pub to praying in the middle of nowhere to gods (with equal chance to obtain either blessing or curse) - the variety of situations is amazing!And of course, sometimes the situation turns out that someone just wants to kill you. Bandits, robbers, pirates, ratment, more exotic creatures and other bad guys  make every effort to stop you from cutting out that damn boss head. So, when it's time to kick some♥♥♥♥♥ the game (just like in Jumanji) sucks you into a small, directed by the scenario of event, levels. All combat is based on an attack\counterattack mechanic, similar to last Batman games, Sleeping Dogs or Shadow of Mordor. You don't have to be a professional pianist for beating the enemies. Still, it's not as easy as it looks - combat might be a little tricky (especially when you haven't got a shield).Successful event passing not only makes you closer to an end of a travel but also unlocks new cards for you decks. And If new equipment expands your arsenal, events are more complex. Some quests may hold different scenarios, so you don't know what will happen next time when you'll get this card. For example, a sleepy man under the thee can be either a bleeding gaurd captain who asks you to find his enemy or a thief who will try to kill you for you goods.Also, some situations lie far beyond one event, and one card is only a part of some bigger story. For example, at first you've got a card, where you help a captain to get back his cursed team captured by some evil spirit. Then, after successfully finishing this quest, you'll get a new one, where that evil spirit will chase after you. Or you meet a group of druids who ask you to protect them during rituals. After thee different defense events you will see the end of this story in a separate card.I recommend Hand of Fate as a addictive randomly-generated game with satisfying shash mechanic, interesting events and enigmatic atmoshpere of everything that is happening."
,Recommended,266510,14111308,"Posted: 22 January, 2015",all,Tready,"What an incredible game! This is the most impressed I have been with a Steam Early Access title to date. I have never played anything quite like it. The closest thing I can think of to compare it to is the PC adaptation of the board game Talisman, but even that doesn't fully describe it.It feels a bit like playing an old school, pen and paper Dungeons and Dragons game. You are the adventurer with the dealer serving as the DM. And the dealer does a great job as DM! He is very well voice acted, his animations for dealing and setup are kind of mesmerizing, and his comments can be funny and/or taunting without being obnoxious. He really makes you want to play ""just one more hand"".Each game, the dealer arranges event cards in a pattern and your character's game piece progresses through them card by card. Each event is one of a wide range of things...shops, people in need of help, monsters, blessings, curses, traps, etc. Some events result in combat, where the game switches briefly to a third person, action RPG style battle with mechanics similar to Shadows of Mordor or the Batman Arkham series. As you successfully complete these events, you'll occasionally earn tokens from the DM. The tokens unlock even more event cards to be included in your deck on the next game.All in all, it's engaging, entertaining, and very hard to put down. I highly recommend Hand of Fate, and I'm excited to see its evolution through the Early Access process!"
