,Recommended,266510,21123056,"Posted: 11 February, 2016",all,Spirits | MSYB!,"IN SUMMARYPro'sVery good voice actingMasterful presentationImportance of proper ""Deck""-BuildingInteresting world & loreCon'sRather dull fighting systemSmall level variety (in combat only)IN-DEPTHWhat it lacks in combat depth, Hand of Fate (HoF) certainly makes up in presentation.Don't be fooled by the cards on the table, essentially HoF is a dungeon crawler with perma-death and the cards just represent the the various rooms, like in Binding of Isaac for example. Content seems to be no problem, the developers are actively still working on the game, adding new content (for free & DLC) and fixing bugs. It is very atmospheric and manages to pull you into it's strange world, masterfully narrated by the card-dealer, who you are playing against.The only thing that could be made better would be the combat system, it strongly reminds me of the Batman Arkham games (Arkham-Combat), however due to money limitations, the devs couldn't afford the mo-cap equipment necessary to execute it well. The animations sometimes seem clunky, and the difficulty is simply determined by the number of enemies on screen, as they sometimes grow in numbers so much, you can't really counter the single hits or ranged attacks thrown at you anymore. However, the combat encounters are short enough to not make it stand out too much, so it's more of a small annoyance than a real problem.Additionally, since your rooms are technically cards, you have to build a deck full of encounters and weapons, all with different effects. This adds another layer of depth to the game, so choose your cards wisely!In the end, Hand of Fate is a masterfully presented rogue-lite, which makes you more interested in it's world and the people (or monsters) that live in it. Combat is dull but scarce enough to not make it stand out too much. If you played it to the end, no worries, there's an endless mode."
