,Recommended,266510,25497556,"Posted: 13 September, 2016",all,Telarius,"Having recently developed an affinity for card-based games, Hand Of Fate caught my eye.  It is a very unique hybrid of a CCG and an RPG, that I personally find quite engaging.  The inclusion of real-time combat also adds another layer of gameplay.  I recommend this game to anyone who enjoys card-based games looking for a bit of a twist.  Personally, I find the card art a bit dull, but if I am seeking that, I'll go play something else.  Definitely a good purchase, though I recommend picking it up on sale with the expansion."
,Recommended,266510,25367829,"Posted: 5 September, 2016",all,MasterBETA,"This game is very enjoyable and scratches numerous genre itches. The game is set up with a character and the character is given a deck that you improve each game. As you unlock new quests, items, and other ""tokens"" in the game this serves as a permanent change to your deck. This also works with creatures, as you progress the deal will also get a harder and more robust deck. Every time you die in the game, your character and progression through the story has to restart, but any tokens you won are permanent (so it is sometimes worth dying and having to restart the game so long as you have a change at a permanent token). The combat is fun and fast, fairly easily button smashing with some strategy. The game is fast past and designed well enough that you can pop in and out of games. 10-15 minutes can be enough to actually make progress. I normally prefer very long and in-depth games that take 100s of hours, but this is something nice to break it up, or if I want something that is better on controller. Honestly you should pick up this game if you are in the mood for something different."
,Recommended,266510,24385202,"Posted: 17 July, 2016",all,GentleGeorge ( ͡° ͜ʖ ͡°),"One of the best rogue-like game out there. You could actually win something and go far in endless mode. You can actually pick the card you wanted, if you can observe the card shuffling process properly tho. It wasn't just random shuffling for visual only where the card choosing is left to fate or luck. DLC is optional but its actually pretty fun. I recommend buying the DLC too."
76561198079020363,Recommended,266510,24486812,"Posted: 23 July, 2016",all,crickit90,"Hand of Fate follows in the foot steps of great games. There is a single character narrating your adventure. In this case it is your opponent, the dealer. It has roguelike elements. The game actually grows as you play it. It has a story and an endless mode. It is an adventure rpg with randomized dungeon encounters. You attain powerful gear, and your character also gains power as an individual. Your choices matter. While there is a random element, you can overcome it with skill. The combat is simple and fluid. This is a direct game with a lot of charm and some poignant humor.In spite of all of these features Hand of Fate is simply a good game. It's overpriced at $25, grindy, and easily becomes repetative. The story mode is short, and endless is simply a good way to unlock more cards for your deck. There are three difficulties: apprentice, adventurer, and warlord. The wildcard dlc adds more, but they don't feel very different. Each adds a few cards to the deck if you grind through them long enough, but it doesn't feel worth the tedium to accomplish it. I'd recommend picking up this game at $15 or less on sale.There are a few other complaints I can see people having. Here they are. Some people might complain that you cannot play as anything other than a male who hardly looks different  than the bandits. There is very little representation of female characters, and it's hardly positive. An elven maiden who grants a boon, a mother who can't provide for her children, a princess in need of rescue. a pair of lovers (the girl is rather flighty), a bandit's nagging wife, an angry spirit, and the queens of each of the suits. Lastly the Descent to the Underworld free dlc adds a new enemy that seems like it is a reskin of the plagues standard melee unit, but that's about it."
,Recommended,266510,24271578,"Posted: 12 July, 2016",all,Tenshi,"Where to begin? I usually start off by comparing to a popular game in the same genre but this one right here... it's quite unique.So, what is Hand of Fate and why you should try it?The game itself is played against the Dealer, as you attempt to beat different challenges and combats that he throws at you. They are represented by cards, some designed to help the player, some to hinder and most are a mix of the two, so the difficulty is balanced on the edge. To help you on your quest, you have two decks, Encounter and Equipment, which you set before hand, but each round the Dealer adds his cards into them as well to balance out the 'goodies' you put in.The cards will vary from straight up story encounters, which usually require the player to make a choice, and may involve combat. Combat is played out top down-ish in a limited area against pre-set enemies God of War style but much more basic. There is nuance to it but not much.PROS- Captivating obscure story, challenging you to find out more by unlocking more cards and beating encounters;- Charming sound design, every clink and slam are in their proper place;- The Dealer: ahhh, the Dealer... fully voice acted, enigmatic, aloof, sometime even tender towards the player. He will frequently comment on the happenings in game, even remembering the cards you used before. You are never quite sure if he is routing for you or trying to hurdle you and bitter at your progress. Intriguing character and SUPERBLY voice-acted. Probably enough of a selling point on its own.- Mouse and Keyboard controls are re-bindable and perfectly functional (i.e. doesn't suck without controller). Controller still probably recommended if you got one.CONS:- Combat camera cannot be controlled and is sometimes pretty awful;- Some people will find the totally unfair and ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t RNG (tm) to be too hard to handle, such people should STAY AWAY from this game.- RNG will screw with you. You will die. Repeatedly. Sometimes the Old Gods decide that 90% of your total HP is just about right to take away because you♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥them off......OVERALL:HIGHLY recommended to any RPG lovers out there with a bit of collecting cards mixed in. Dripping in polish and a lot of TLC."
