,Recommended,266510,14655801,"Posted: 25 February, 2015",all,UMBRA,"I am absolutely in love with this game. It takes deck building, choose-your-own-adventure, board games, Arkham-style brawling and roguelite elements and mixes them all into a melting pot, and the atmosphere is the final ingredient that brings it all together.You're essentially playing through an adventure, using a deck of cards as the base, with the dealer providing colorful commentary and setting the mood. It's like playing a personal, one-on-one game of DnD with someone...or like old shows like Knightmare or similar. I can not overstate how impressive the atmosphere is of the game, with each card full of flavor and every encounter interesting and exciting. You never know what you'll find!The dealer himself is a very interesting character, who half the time seems to want to help you and half the time seems happy to watch you twist in the wind. He'll applaud you for victory, but just as quickly savor your defeat. Maybe you decide to swap out an axe for a sword? He'll snark about it, asking you if it's really what you want to do. His commentary, though sometimes cryptic, does an immense job in building the world and turns every card into a fully fleshed encounter, dripping with detail. Every monster, enemy and boss is played up with description, sometimes terrifying and sometimes mournful.Honestly, I have no complaints about this game at all and have had no issues or bugs with it...at least so far. Some of the RNG can get truly brutal in the later encounters and the combat itself isn't exactly door-busting, but it's more than servicable and for anyone who's played the Arkham games, Assassin's Creed or the like will find it easy to learn, though the difficulty ramps up greatly.I can already see this being one of my favorite games of the year. I sincerely hope they intend to release more content for it, as I'd love that, though between the Story mode and Endless Mode, I can see playing this for a long while yet."
,Recommended,266510,14655841,"Posted: 25 February, 2015",all,Noble Insanity,"Just started playing and I can already tell this is a great game. Similar combat to the Arkham series, with wonderful deck building adventure quests.Tons of replayability possibilities it seems!2 thumbs up!"
,Recommended,266510,14656957,"Posted: 25 February, 2015",all,Stealthxero,"Don't want to read the wall of text below? Watch my first look of Hand of Fate here.http://youtu.be/umvlXyDrUA8Much like most of the other great games that have come out this year so far, Hand of Fate is one of those that could have easily slipped through the cracks. It is a difficult game to categorize, but it's mix of card game mechanics, brawling and table top RPG mechanics proves to mix together very well. Let's break down each part and see how it stacks up.The Card Game -Easily the best part of this game. When I heard this was a card game I went into it expecting something along the lines of Hearthstone, but I couldn't have been more wrong. Your deck controls what is in each level, and gives you equipment. the dealers deck on the other hand (heh card puns) contains the monsters you fight, the prizes and punishments from encounters, and a few cards just to mess with you. Its very unique and very addictingThe Brawling -Easily the worst part of the game. It's not bad, but if you have played Shadow of Mordor then this is going to feel quite clunky. The combat is just imprecise and the trap level that all depend on movement are hard to navigate. It should be noted though that its not BAD, just could have used some more polish and seems rushed compared to the rest of the game.The RPG Side -Much of the game comes down to what are essentially dice rolls from D&D, though in this case is a card pick. This is what ties the whole game together. With this system even playing the same deck time and time again will give you a different playthrough. It is a deep system and allows for almost infinite replayability, and in a time where games are getting bashed for not having replayability  *cough* The Order *cough* its good to see.Hand of Fate is easily one of my favorite games of the year so far, and I highly recommend picking it up is you have any interest in card games."
