,Recommended,266510,26936149,"Posted: 23 November, 2016",all,Colonel Gentleman,"Hand of Fate is a very unique game that combines a story rich ""Choose your own adventure"" RPG, with deck building elements, and Batman/Shadow of Mordor encounters and combat.  Also did I mention it’s a roguelike as well?One would assume this to be a disaster in the making with all these features vying for the players attention, but in reality it is an oddly perfect fit.While you play the game against your foe, the Dealer who takes delight in commenting on almost every action you do.  Once again another potential recipe for disaster averted due to the crisp excellent voice performance that sets a strange level of immersion where it indeed feels like a game within a game.  The dealer always has something witty, interesting, deep, or teasing to say about every card that is played.  He even catches on to certain situations like where he happens to notice you milking a card for all its worth in multiple plays, or makes note on your lack or abundance of certain resources.  There’s so much dialogue that not only does it remain fresh; it paints a 2nd story reflecting the lore of the main game, not just the one you are playing.The music is quite good, though the tracks are limited and you will find yourself hearing the same battle song over and over again.  The game is a good deal for what it is and you will find yourself playing game after game as the difficulty starts to ramp up to unfair levels of play.  Since it is in part a game of chance, it is certainly something you will have to accept.  (Even though the card shuffling in the 4 card Monty games are indeed legitimate and not random in their answers like other games)The only main strike against it I would give is that the combat can be a tad wonky at times and almost feels like it was added as an afterthought.  If the controls were cleaned up better and the combat more fleshed out, (or even removed) it would be in my top 5 list of games I’ve played this year."
