76561198005846873,Recommended,266510,26325142,"Posted: 30 October, 2016",all,ShadowTemplar59,"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mNgXyyczBZEHand of Fate is at it's very essence is a 3D card game with some basic combat elements. You swap cards in and out to build a better deck so you can fight the bosses at the end of each run. What separate it from it's card brethren like Hearthstone is in Hand of Fate everything is a card. From encounters, events, enemies, and the bosses themselves are cards. On top of these cards the dealer himself has a deck which along with your cards are than arrayed on the table in different configurations, and the match up of the two decks serves as the game's board. As you move along the board the dealer also serves as the narrator and draws you into the experience. I only wish the story wasn't paper thin, but it is serviceable. The only major fault I have with this game is it's combat system. How it works is when you land on a card that isn't either gain gold, health, food ect, or lose gold, health, food ect. A 3D world is generated with your generic character and whatever armor and weapons cards you have happened to pick up. There is nothing inherently wrong with this system, but compared to the deck build aspects this part is a let down. All and all I would highly recommend this to people who are fans are cards games, or those looking to try a new and interesting game"
