,Recommended,266510,29433006,Posted: 22 January,all,ZëL,"This game is absolutely charming, is very well made and innovative and an absolute pleasure to play.The gameplay is really unique, since everything you do, from your health, to your food, to your inventory, to the adventures you have to complete, is represented by cards. You ""craft"" the encouters for your adventure by building your own deck, but you absolutely don't have to like card games to enjoy this one. This gives the game a really distinct look and charm, while also being a system to add replayability and a choose-your-own-adventure vibe.When you enter the combat, the whole game transform into an action RPG, with WASD + mouse controls to move and attack monsters. The equipment you have found during your journey in the card game will transform into real weapons and armors. The combat encounters lasts for a mere 1-2 minutes on average (excluding boss encounters). I have to say that this part of the game seems a bit out of place, the main fault being the spamminess of the attacks, which don't look like they carry lots of weight. It is not my favourite part of the game at all, but it can be enjoyable nonetheless.The encounters are really varied, some are luck-based, some may require combat, some advance the story a little. There are really lots of them, from the simplest dialogue-based ones, to events having multiple possible outcomes. Most encounters form an arc, spanning multiple encounters and playthroughs to reach the end of the narrative. Some events, if kept in the deck, can become a bit stale and repetitive, of course, since the outcome of an event is scripted (at most depending by 1 or more luck/skill based card draws, or a combat encounter), but they can be swapped out for other cards to keep the game fresh and enjoyable.The DLC Wildcards, which I got for free during a promotion, adds even more events, on average more complex than the base game ones.  It also adds talents to the player, which change a bit the way of playing. You have to choose one talent before starting your next adventure, with can increase/decrease the combat proficiency, the speed of cards in the card draw minigame, the health and damage of the monsters etc. I find that the DLC increases exponentionally the replayability of the game. The only thing I didn't like of DLC (up until now, at least) was the Goblin Hall event series, which have the player try to reach the end of a little maze filled with traps: since the game was not made for a platformer, avoiding traps and obstacles is way more cumbersome than needed, making that section a little frustrating. Except for this, I recommend getting the DLC for this game, for the replayability and variations it adds.Huge props for the card dealer, which makes the game really interesting and fascinating.Overall I find this to be a really great gem of a game, I absolutely recommend this to everyone.Looking forward for the sequel!"
