76561197992229015,Recommended,266510,34908312,Posted: 12 September,all,Dire,"My god, was I torn between a good and a bad review. Why, you ask? Because of the final ""boss"". Hand of Fate challenges you to defeat 12 regular bosses, most of which are rather easy, but still somewhat fun, but the final boss pitches all 12 bosses against you. 3 at a time. With no chance of healing in between. Fun times. Since the game is also based around chance a lot you can simply have a run in which you are pretty screwed. While - in theory - you could win that fight even with your starting equipment and 1 health, that's the same as saying DS can be beaten that way. Yes, it can be done, but 1 mistake and that's it. Back to the pit. Start all over again. Basically I was hammering away at the final boss longer than at all 12 other bosses combined. About 3-4 hours or so on normal.Now, more about the game. It's basically a card RPG with real time ""Arkham-style"" combat.The good stuff:- Great presentation and narrator. You're actually playing, well, a game of fate on a real game board against the dealer.- A ton of variety - from different quest cards you can complete to unlock new cards, to equipment cards, curses, blessings, etc. there's pretty much something for every situation. And unlocking new stuff and reading all those fun stories is what kept me going.- Bosses are all unique and at least sorta fun.- Game can be played rather quickly.- Endless mode with a lot of individual modifiers to test out.The bad stuff:- Sometimes the RNG just ♥♥♥♥s you over completely, which is ""ok"" in Endless mode, but was really annoying in story mode. For example, there are certain cards in the game, which have high requirements or require you to acquire another card in the run first, such as the metal ore and the monastery. Well, bad luck when the monastery is on a preceding floor than the ore. Then both cards are absolutely worthless.- Chance cards are terribly designed. Basically you play a game of guess the correct card with success and failure states. These cards are then shuffled in front of your eyes. If you are lucky you can spot the correct card if the game lets you. Other times you just have only 1 success card and that one is shuffled so obscurely that you can only guess. Then the game may shuffle the cards two, three or four times and increase the shuffle speed, making it just a guessing game. And ob boy, those failures can completely kill a run, but attempting these cards is vital to get new equipment or get out of a bad situation, which you could not have avoided in the first place. I just feel like the design is taunting you and makes this unnecessary. A % chance would have seemed fairer.- Trap cards are the worst. The camera is so wonky and the controls so terrible that it's hard to avoid damage in the more difficult ones. Especially when you then just stumble from one trap onto another. Fun times. And often there's not even anything to gain.- Speaking of which, cards that only have negative effects and no way of avoiding them aren't ""fun"".- Combat is extremely lackluster. You can attack, counterattack, block and dodge, as well as use a weapon ability and a character ability, if you have those. Some attacks are unblockable, some shields need to be broken to attack enemies. All very basic, but not executed well. Not only does it look terrible it also plays terribly and will be the one thing that will bore you very quickly.- About encounters: ♥♥♥♥ you for throwing me into an arena with 2 bosses, 10 mobs and lots of traps on a CHANCE encounter. On the second to last floor. Yay.Ultimately this game can be a lot of fun, but also somewhat frustrating at times, especially since you need to remember what each card does, lest you want to get cursed or lose Health or Food or Gold or Items...I'm gonna play a bit more in endless mode, but I don't see too much more long term fun to be had here."
