,Recommended,266510,35047206,Posted: 18 September,all,Maz,This game is honestyl so addicting and good. I love it how every run through is different and that its mainly pure chance most of the time when dealing with situations and encounters. I give this game the sticker of Maz Approval :D
76561198023082933,Recommended,266510,35093431,Posted: 20 September,all,toucanbuzz,"Unique and fascinating game in which your hero navigates dungeons (monsters, traps, and chance-based encounters) based on cards you accumulate, mixed in with random ones based on the scenario. The narrator, a master of fate, creates your dungeons by flipping over cards as you choose a path. The more advanced the scenario, the more deadly the cards he mixes in. Players can let the computer decide what's a good mix, or you can choose your own deck. You'll need chances to get equipment, health, and so on as each scenario you begin with only the basics. Also, many cards have built in quests, so when you complete those, it opens up another card in that quest line. Keeps the game fresh (even if you die, you may have made progress toward a quest line.)Death can be frustrating, you die and the entire dungeon is over. Combat is a little tricky to master as there isn't a major tutorial (and some monsters require a specific maneuver or you'll never beat them, e.g. lizard men with shields). Still, it's worth it.Finally, the narrator's voice and dialog is fantastic and really makes this game shine. It was a blast.Two Cons:-  difficulty when you get to the higher tier scenarios. They are insane-  RNG plays a huge role. In the higher tier ones, a single bad random number and you're screwed."
,Recommended,266510,35009474,Posted: 16 September,all,Studious,"This game has a lot of unique things going for it. I was pleasantly surprised and thoroughly entertained for the vast majority of the time I spent playing this game. However, some of the undercooked parts of this game really soured my final hours of play.Basically, this is what you would get if you threw a board game, a session of D&D, and the battle system from one of the Batman Arkham games in a blender. It's a surprising and unique blend of roleplay, chance and action that I haven't seen a lot of games try to replicate. But functionally when you tear things down, the game is actually quite simple. You have a row of cards, and moving uses up a unit of food. The card you land on can be anything from an event, to a battle, or a game of chance. Act heroically, or get really lucky, and you'll unlock weapons, gain gold, and other cards and events that help you along your way.As you climb your way up the ladder, beating the various bosses, you'll unlock quite a bit of loot. Your resources expand as you encounter different situations and learn what gets you rewarded and what gets you hurt, or worse: cursed. If there's one thing I can applaud this game for, is that the difficulty curb for everything but the last few bosses is buttery smooth. Bosses go from rather easy to somewhat challenging. And for the most part, I felt as though the game was being fair in its approach to difficulty. Even after the bosses start getting tough, I felt like the game was still giving me a reasonable amount of resources. I didn't die to any boss except one that has a surprising and also annoying gimmick.However... The jump in difficulty between the last few bosses to the final boss is crazy. Events and stage conditions get downright punishing; and the bonuses you are allowed are either too random to be useful, or circumstantial and weak. You quickly find that stacking random bonuses, or blessings, does little to help in general, seeing as the vast majority are situational at best. In the final stage, you are disallowed from having any of them at all. The bottom line is that you're faced with some pretty gruesome curses in the last level, some of which are run ending. To top it all off, events are now stacked against you more than ever; so aside from events that just hand you goodies, you aren't getting jack.Sprint your way to the finish on the final level, and you're greeted with... literally all of the bosses you've fought, gauntlet style. If you weren't lucky enough to outfit your character with a few good items and/or some kind of healing trinket, then there really isn't much to do about it. You get one shot at the boss, just like any other, and then you need to restart the entire run. In other games, when a bossrush is thrown at you, you can expect some sort of leniency. A way to heal, an easier way to win, or balancing so you don't get stomped. You don't get any help for this fight. Aside from some situational healing items you have a (slim) chance of getting during the run, the health you go in with is the health you'll have. What a joke.I really wish this last part of the game was better thought out, if I'm being honest. This really left a sour taste in my mouth. Some QTE and fighting all of the bosses you've already fought is all that awaits you in the final level. So, I hit my head against the wall for maybe two dozen attempts. That is, until I found out that restarting the game before you die puts you on the turn before the boss. Then I kept restarting the game when I took a few too many hits. Dodging four hit combos, teleporting attacks, ranged hits that transition into combos, etc etc. Fighting all of the bosses three at a time really isn't fun, especially when they pingpong you back and fourth between themselves. Over and over until I finally conserve enough health to make it through a particularly tough part of the fight. Enough health to brave the final attacks. Enough health to win the game. Hand of Fate ends with one garbage fire of a bossrush.This game does get punishing. Despite what the dealer says, some times you aren't left with any real options. You'll make it to the final boss and have to choose between going in with half health or starting over. You'll get crippled before you even have a chance to fight. It's really a shame. With blessings completely off the table, your options for getting more powerful are rather limited. If there was another path of progression unlocked with the final boss, like leveling up your character, or being able to bend the rules of the game the way the dealer does, then this would be balanced. I know the final boss of a game should be the hardest, but it should not be break your controller hard. And that's what it comes down to. For what its worth, this game is definitely worth a buy. I was seriously having a lot of fun before that final boss. The game presents to you a dungeon with a myriad of tiny mini adventures packed in. It's a lot of fun, just don't expect any mercy from the last level, or a satisfying conclusion."
