76561198090054326,Recommended,266510,35077291,Posted: 19 September,all,Teemo Main (sorry),Just the first few secs of the game got me hyped to play more. I don't play many card games but this one is amazing and makes you want to play more. 9/10
,Recommended,266510,14544189,"Posted: 19 February, 2015",all,XartaX,"This game... Oh my, is it good. I finally finished story mode, so I feel like I can give an educated opinion now, so lets get down to the details.Hand of fate is a mixed card game and action RPG. On their own they are both average at best, but they complement and enhance each other very well.You have two decks (Sets of cards, for those not familiar with the lingo): The equipment deck and the encounter deck. The encounter deck will be used by The Dealer to construct the levels you play on, along with the cards he add himself to help and/or screw you over. These cards can be everything from a shop to buy and sell items in, to assisting (alleged) druids with their rituals. You start the game standing on a card, and you can move to any adjecent card to get closer to the boss so you can beat it and win the game. Every card is initially hidden, so you have no idea what awaits you before you move to and flip a card (certain items can reveal cards under certain conditions, though).A session consists of several levels, which are each constructed by a bunch of the encounter cards. For example 10 cards can build up a level, and one of these cards will be a travel card which lets you travel to the next level, where more cards will be used to construct it. Every encounter card can also have a golden symbol on it, which means that if you handle the encounter card in a certain way (usually defeating the monsters or getting another positive outcome), you will unlock more encounter and/or equipment cards.The equipment cards in your deck are the cards you will be able to obtain during a session. You can gain these by completing encounters in certain ways, or buying them at shops. As you complete more encounters you will, as mentioned earlier, obtain more equipment cards. This increases your potential power for each subsequent session (you start every session with basic equipment, although you can obtain better starting gear as you progress in story mode). Like the Encounter deck, the dealer can also add cards to the equipment deck.Equipment comes in seven different types: Weapons, shields, armor, helms, gloves, artifacts and trinkets (I suspect they are all rings as I haven't seen other types yet, but the category is called trinkets. Possibly for DLC down the line?). You can use one of each at a time, except for trinkets who are all active as long as you own them. Equipment can have both passive and active effects. The exception are artifacts, who only have activated abilities (they are your spells, basically).There are two different modes: Story and Endless mode. Story mode will put you up against one of the bosses of the game(SPOILER::::::The last boss forces you to fight every single boss in the game, three at once four times:::::ENDSPOILER).In story mode you'll start with certain curses and The Dealer will add certain cards himself to your different decks as mentioned earlier. Usually these will be encounter cards. It is possible to just play a story session with almost any kind of deck (as long as it's not outright terrible), but specializing your deck for the stuff The Dealer will throw at you is probably a good idea unless you're like me and put as many ""unfinished"" encounters you can into your deck to unlock more cards more quickly (warning: this will likely result in a lot of rage as you try to unlock more stuff, fail, and get screwed over for the session).I have yet to play a lot of Endless mode, as Story mode kept me occupied for a while (I've slept with my computer running the game and such, though, so take hours/played with a *grain* of salt). From what I can see, you don't get to construct your deck here (you use all your cards), and the session continues until you die. In addition every time you travel to a new level of the session the dealer will throw in more bad things you have to deal with (feel free to correct me in the comments if I'm wrong, and I'll update it. I'll play Endless mode more now that I finished Story mode myself, though). As you start without any curses, it's probably an excellent way to go for unlocking encounter cards.Speaking of curse cards. There are two kinds of cards I haven't mentioned yet: Curses and Blessings. These are persistant effects that will buff or debuff you for the duration of the session (or, rarely, until a condition is fulfilled and it fires). Examples here can be spending food to counterattack, but doubling counter attack damage (a curse), or a lightning bolt striking down one enemy at the start of each combat (a blessing). Curses are usually really expensive to get rid of (at least the ones you start with), and blessings are expensive for their cost to obtain, and have varying levels of use. You could get a blessing which won't be of any use for an entire run, or a curse you will barely notice. On the other hand, you could also get really powerful ones which will be a great boon, or completely screw you over.Whew, ok, only a few mechanics left to mention now. In addition to what's already been mentioned, you also have health, food and gold. You start with 100/100 health, and both your current and maximum health can change during the course of the run. Current health can be knocked down both by encounters, and by taking damage during combat. You spend 1 food every time you move, and if you run out of food every movement will cost you 10 health points. Gold is simply used to buy things at shops (equipment, blessings, removing curses, food, etc.). All these resources can be refilled through encounters, or purchased at different types of shops (selling in the case of gold).The combat itself is a very simple Batman ish combat system. You attack and counter attack, and can dodge roll. You can also use the activated abilities of your different items. The combat itself can feel a bit sluggish (animations are a bit slow), but the controls are VERY responsive, and I hardly ever felt like I didn't avoid something which shouldn't have hit me. Combat itself can be triggered during an encounter card, and you will draw from the dealers monster deck whenever combat has been initiated by an encounter (although what strength/kind of monsters you can draw is usually decided by the encounter card).Do I recommend this game? Hell yeah I recommend this game. It might peter out a bit after you finished the story mode and start just screwing around in endless mode (I don't know yet, although I've yet to unlock all the encounter cards), but so far it's been a LOT of fun. That said, it can be ridiculously hard towards the later story sessions (it starts out easy, though). If you don't mind the difficulty you should definitely take it for a ride. I'd be very surprised if you end up regretting it!If you didn't like something about the review, or felt some information is lacking, feel free to drop a comment! If you felt this review helped you come to an informed decision, I'd very much appreciate a helpful rating. If you felt this isn't helpful at all, you can of course vote it down, but I'd appreciate being told what you feel is wrong so I get an opportunity to change my review if your points are valid. Have fun gaming!"
